<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCWOM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURN OF GOMEZ MEANS DECISION TIME FOR UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; MALIBU, Calif. _ A decision looms for No. 8 UCLA: Point guard
Erica Gomez returns early, perhaps for the Bruins' next game.
</P>
<P>
   From all indications, Crescenta Valley graduate Michelle Greco
will find herself out of a starting role upon Gomez's return.
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, Greco said Saturday, she accepts it. But she
wants to start and she made a strong case with a career-best 20
points in Saturday's 86-67 victory over host Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I want to start,'' Greco said, ``but coming off the
bench and being a sparkplug is OK, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomez, sidelined with a shoulder injury, likely will debut
Friday at Cal State Fullerton and be joined in the backcourt by
freshman Nicole Kaczmarski, who also scored a career-high 20 points
against the Waves.
</P>
<P>
   But there's one other option: a three-guard offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can go with three guards in a second,'' UCLA coach Kathy
Olivier said. ``I have no problem with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Greco's and Kaczmarski's play was just what the Bruins
(4-2) needed. Pepperdine (2-4) used a zone defense, collapsing on
post players Maylana Martin and Janae Hubbard and daring Greco and
Kaczmarski to shoot from outside.
</P>
<P>
   So they did. Greco had 13 at halftime and Kaczmarski had 11. By
game's end, UCLA had made eight 3-pointers, one more than their
season total and one shy of the school record for a game.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting opened up the post, allowing Martin to score points
in bunches and finish with 21 and moved past Ann Meyers into fifth
place all-time at UCLA. Meyers scored 1,685 points from 1975-78.
Martin has 1,704.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Philman scored 13 points for UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine's press wasn't completely ineffective. It held UCLA
to 38.2-percent shooting in the first half and helped overcome a
double-digit deficit during a 25-10 run of 11 minutes, 58 seconds.
Guard Rasheeda Clark scored the last 10 points of that run to give
the Waves a 34-32 lead with 2:57 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Clark finished with 19 points and Dee Braxton had 13.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves also held a 30-20 halftime rebounding advantage, but
UCLA's second-half post play trimmed that to 45-44 by game's end.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine's shooting woes continued, typified by Moorpark
graduate Damaris Hinojosa's 3-of-18 game. The Waves shot 27{
percent in the first half and 31{ percent for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rasheeda can hang with Kaczmarski, and Damaris can hang with
Greco,'' Pepperdine coach Mark Trakh said, ``but we have no one to
stop their big two. It's pick your poison.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA, meanwhile, has to pick its guards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
