u s BC-HKN-ONHOCKEY-BRUINS-B     12-12 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ONHOCKEY-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING DOING WITH BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There aren't a lot of good things happening for the Bruins right
now. They're 2 1/2 weeks past their last win, most nights they
struggle to score even a pair of goals, and Saturday night's 5-4
loss to the Red Wings sank them to just an inch over .500
(11-10-8).
</P>
<P>
   It's time to state the obvious: Uh-oh.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, no one should have been counting on the Bruins running
away and hiding in the Eastern Conference this season. But
suddenly, this is a team taking on losses and taking on retreads
(Mssrs. Joe Murphy and Marty McSorley) in a year when virtually
everyone who ever pulled on doublerunners believed youth and
enthusiasm might carry the B's to, say, a conference final, maybe
even slip them into a best-of-seven June dance for the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not happening. Last Saturday the lowly Blackhawks
visited the Vault and crushed their bones, 9-3. It was the worst
beating a Pat Burns team has taken on Causeway Street. He
apologized. His players apologized. For a moment, we expected the
players to line up at the wickets and hand out rainchecks as if it
were K mart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come back another time, will you?'' they might have said. ``We
don't always stink this bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Red Wings are hardly the Hawks. In fact, Mike Ilitch's
multimillionaires handle the puck better than anyone in the league,
at times snapping off four or five tape-to-tape passes, virtually
unheard of here in hockey's dead-puck era. Let's not forget,
either, the Wings are only 18 months removed from winning their
second of back-to-back Cups. Losing by a goal to the Red Wings
carries a lot more honor that getting shellacked by the
barely-breathing Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played like we were intimidated a little bit,'' said gritty
Bruins forward Rob DiMaio, the center of the night's only bit of
nastiness, a slight dustup with dastardly Chris Chelios, ``by their
talent and their experience.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins have any chance of beating Detroit, or a club such
as Phoenix (Monday night's visitor to the Vault), a little bit of
intimidation can be a healthy thing. If it translates into a fear
of losing, and the repercussions that might follow, then that blend
of intimidation and anxiety can draw the best out of a club.
</P>
<P>
   But here in the Hub, it's clear that the players don't feel that
immediacy. In large part, that's because there is no pressure from
underneath, from the minor leagues. Baby Bruins are called up from
Providence like one-a-day vitamins. Joel Prpic was Saturday night's
vitamin C booster shot. He played all of six shifts and 4 minutes
31 seconds. As bad as Jason Allison is going right now (7 points/14
games), does anyone expect the towering Prpic to knock him off the
No. 1 line or otherwise change the composition of the regular
trios? Of course not.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no one in the organization deemed worthy of stepping
in and making a difference, winning a job, stealing a paycheck,
then indifference is what you get among the rank-and-file. It's not
that these Bruins are lazy fatcats. But their game, their effort,
their lack of seizing the moment, says they're complacent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've lost against poor teams, and you've lost against
good teams, you have to start wondering, where are you in the
mix?'' said Burns. ``As a player, you go home and you don't worry.
But as a coach, you go home and you worry. You gauge yourself, and
it's worrisome.''
</P>
<P>
   In times like these, coaches can look up and find themselves
suddenly out of work. It happened last week to Kevin Constantine in
Pittsburgh. He's a good coach, not quite in Burns's category, but
he had the ever-changing, bankrupt Pens 24 games over .500 the past
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh GM Craig Patrick decided last week that he didn't
like his club's funk and reached for the old, reliable
fire-the-coach manual. Constantine was out. Herb Brooks was in. The
next four months will tell if it was the right move. Constantine,
by the way, began coaching the Pens at the same time Burns took
over the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Will Burns get the hook here? It's not likely. But it is, to
quote the coach, a results business. When the results don't come,
no matter how justified, reasoned, or even imagined, then coaches
pay the price. We present Fred Creighton, Gerry Cheevers, Butch
Goring, Rick Bowness, Brian Sutter, Steve Kasper. In times of
trouble on Causeway Street, the perceived cure often has been
handing the coach his hat. Perception hasn't often been reality,
but that hasn't made the firing line any less real.
</P>
<P>
   If losses don't worry his players, and Burns no doubt is right
about that, perhaps they'll worry if they get the idea that they
could cost the coach his job. Every coach worries. Some even would
worry with a five-goal lead late in the third period of a
Cup-clinching game. Some even believe that anxiety produces
positive results. They are the anti-Norman Vincent Peales.
</P>
<P>
   But here are two very real worries: The Bruins began the season
0-5-4, their worst start since the mid-'60s. They're now without a
win in six games and barely remain in the scrum for one of the
lower playoff berths in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Count on this: If six games turns into nine games, 10 games
without a win, then something big will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Will it be an infusion of minor-leaguers? No.
</P>
<P>
   A giant trade? Forget it.
</P>
<P>
   Then what? If the players aren't asking themselves that by now,
then that alone could be the answer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
