<HEADLINE>
RUIZ TAKES OUT ANGER ON REPLACEMENT FIGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUNICA, Miss. _ Johnny Ruiz was feeling truculent Saturday night
and took it out on the only guy who hadn't had a thing to do with
his peevishness.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz learned Friday that the opponent he thought he would be
facing, Jade Scott, had disappeared, taking with him Ruiz's chance
for national TV exposure. In his place had come Thomas ``Top Dog''
Williams, someone Ruiz had never heard of and Showtime knew so
little about that it decided to take Ruiz off the televised portion
of its show at the Grand Casino.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 24 hours, Ruiz sat in his room at the Grand Casino
and fumed; by the time he was called out of the locker room, a fire
was raging inside the Chelsea heavyweight that he used to consume
Williams, bombing him out in 50 seconds of the second round with a
stiff jab, a body shot, and a following flurry that drove Williams
to his knees.
</P>
<P>
   When he got up, Williams said he was ready to continue but when
referee Fred Sidewinder III unhanded him, he tottered forward and
fell into him _ and that was that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't need to see anything more,'' Sidewinder said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did Williams (24-5), who later claimed he could have
gone on but had been hit with everything Ruiz had, including
several things normally not part of the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not making any excuses,'' Willia id. ``He's a stong
puncher, but he hit me with an elbow and a shoulder. It got pretty
rough in there.''
</P>
<P>
   It was pretty rough right from the start when a seething Ruiz
(36-3, 27 KO) rushed out of his corner and cracked Williams with a
solid jab. Williams went to hold on, and next thing you knew, both
tumbled to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   When they got up, Ruiz continued to punch with a terrible
purpose, repeatedly knocking Williams back with a stiff jab and
hard rights to the head. But Scott's last-minute replacement was
game, if nothing else. He threw back, even catching Ruiz with one
solid body shot, but the WBC's top-rated heavyweight ignored
everything but his fierce purpose until he rid himself of at least
a portion of his irritation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like everything was going wrong all week,'' Ruiz
said. ``My opponent didn't show up. They moved me from 10 p.m. to 9
p.m. They took me off TV. I was pretty upset and Williams was the
only guy in front of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Not for long. In fact, not for that much longer than Scott, who
was never in front of Ruiz at all after a national conference call
on Wednesday in which he was asked his New Year's resolution and
said, ``I am moving in the same direction as Ruiz.''
</P>
<P>
   That was true only if Ruiz was heading back to Chelsea, which he
is not. Instead, Ruiz made short work of Williams, which was
essential in the situation he was in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning a decision wouldn't have been good enough,'' said
Norman Stone, Ruiz's manager. ``He had to look good. He had to blow
the guy out. The TV guys screwed themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering Williams's shaky record (losses to Marion Wilson,
Melvin Foster, Jse Ferguson, Obed Sullivan, and Dannell Nicholson)
and his questionable arrival time, Showtime executives feared
perhaps only the second half of Top Dog's nickname was applicable
and, hence, made the decision to pull the plug on Ruiz's fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't happy about it, but we decided to honor the contract
and fight,'' Stone said. ``With King, you gotta look at the A, B,
and C's, not just the A's.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz understood that, as well, and not only took care of them
but also minded his Ps and Qs. He was in the ring for only one
purpose, regardless of the face in front of him. He was there to
make a statement to Michael Grant, the WBC's No. 2 contender and
the man Ruiz has challenged to a big-money fight on HBO to settle
the matter of who is the top heavyweight contender.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, John Ruiz made as strong a case for himself as
he could.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Larry Donald easily stopped journeyman Jeff Lally
(23-17-1), dropping him three times in the second round before the
fight was stopped at 2:15 of the round. The victory lifted the
(WBA) No. 3-rated Donald's record to 36-1-1 with his only loss
coming against two-time heavyweight champion Riddick Bowe . . .
Three undefeated fighters kept their strings intact when
welterweights Andrew ``Six Heads'' Lewis (18-0-1) stopped Damone
Wright (13-14-1) in the third round, Kofi Jantuah (14-0) stopped
Gerald Reed (16-28-3) at 2:59 of the third, and featherweight
Daniel Seda (13-0, 11 KO) stopped Steve Trumble (8-6) at 1:43 of
the fourth roun
</P>
</TEXT>
