<SLUG> BC-BBN-BELTRE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL PARTIES AWAIT BELTRE RULING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Gene Orza, associate general counsel of the
players association, said a grievance would only be filed on behalf
of Los Angeles Dodgers third baseman Adrian Beltre if baseball
doesn't issue a ruling by the end of next week.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alderson, executive vice president of baseball operations
for the Office of the Commissioner, said last week a decision on
Beltre's status would come by Friday. Orza said that would be fine.
</P>
<P>
   But Orza said if the situation remains unresolved in the days
leading up to the Christmas holiday, the players association would
intervene. Also, if Beltre isn't granted free agency, Orza said
it's likely a grievance would be filed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't decided whether we would formally intervene,'' Orza
said before leaving the winter meetings Saturday morning. ``It's
pretty clear Beltre was signed prior to a time when he could be
(legally) signed under baseball rules. . . . If we don't hear
something sometime before Christmas, maybe then we would
intervene.''
</P>
<P>
   Orza said it appears the Dodgers knowingly signed Beltre at the
age of 15 rather than waiting until he was 16. Documents in
Beltre's personnel file, which the club turned over to Beltre's
agent, Scott Boras, contains documents that show Beltre was 15 when
he signed. In addition, Boras said Beltre was signed before July 1,
violating major-league rules.
</P>
<P>
   However, Orza said there was a scenario in which Beltre, 20,
could remain with the Dodgers, though he added he didn't think such
a scenario applied to this case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suppose he knew five years ago, but he's (not) saying
something because he's waiting until he's a major-leaguer,'' Orza
said. ``But my understanding is he was not aware of the rule until
recently _ this past season.''
</P>
<P>
   Orza said he is also hoping the league allows the Dodgers to
negotiate with Beltre if baseball declares him a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think (baseball) should'' keep the Dodgers from
signing him, Orza said. ``Having him taken out of (the Dodgers')
system is a penalty enough. It's their decision, but I would think
that would be extreme.'
</P>
<P>
   __ Extra bases: Charlie Strasser, the Dodgers' head trainer the
past four seasons, was re-assigned to coordinator of medical
services, the club announced. Strasser, who first worked in the
Dodgers' organization in 1972 and has spent 24 years with the club,
will now be involved in all medical aspects of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant general manager Bill Geivett said the Dodgers might
promote Stan Johnston to head trainer. Triple-A Albuquerque trainer
Matt Wilson could be promoted to work with the Dodgers. . . .
Baltimore scout Don Welke, highly regarded throughout baseball, is
expected to be hired by the Dodgers soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
