<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS HOLD OFF VENGEFUL MONTREAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The old Forum has been gone awhile and the old heroes
now only hang in the rafters. But to say Saturday night's 4-2 Los
Angeles Kings victory over the Canadiens was just about two points
in the standings was like taking a whack at old Rocket Richard
himself.
</P>
<P>
   There is bad blood between these two teams and you only needed
to see the brace around the neck of Montreal's Brian Savage to know
why. The last time these two met was a month ago at the Staples
Center when Ian Laperriere cracked three vertebrae in Savage's back
on a vicious check.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Canadiens say the hit was clean, but that didn't matter
Saturday when both sides started fighting 20 minutes !ital!before
the opening faceoff, during pregame warmups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't even in the middle of that, I was way off in the
corner,'' said Laperriere. ``But that was the kind of night it was
going to be. You just knew they were never going to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Kings took a 3-0 lead into the third period and
appeared to be heading for Tuesday's game in New Jersey 1-1 on this
four-game trip.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal, which is last in the Northeast Division, came back
with two goals in the first three minutes of the period and
suddenly the silent crowd of 19,250 at the Molson Centre came to
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew there was tension in the air,'' said Len Barrie, who
was part of the pregame fight when he mixed it up with Montreal's
Shayne Corson. ``It was payback time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings, who actually lost the Nov. 20 game 5-3, certainly
could have been vulnerable after Friday's listless 3-1 loss in
Detroit. They were playing without three of their best _ captain
Rob Blake, leading scorer Ziggy Palffy and top center Jozef
Stumpel.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy and Blake might be back Tuesday against the Devils, but
others had to fill in on Saturday. After turning back a penalty
shot by Martin Rucinsky just six minutes into the game, the Kings
scored three times, including two on the power play and the first
of two goals by Brad Chartrand.
</P>
<P>
   The first came with just 10 seconds left in the first by Bryan
Smolinski and that set the tone. Garry Galley, who had a power play
goal Friday in Detroit, got another only 1:29 gone in the second.
Seven minutes later it was Chartrand and his goal chased Montreal's
starting goalie Jeff Hackett from the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost to them badly in L.A. because they forechecked like
crazy and we never got to move our legs,'' Kings coach Andy Murray
said. ``We wanted to push the action tonight and get behind their
defense. We did that.''
</P>
<P>
   But still the Canadiens came back. Jim Cummins, who got a
five-minute fighting major with Steve McKenna, scored just 1:34
into the third. One minute, 16 seconds later, Sergei Zholtok made
it one-goal game.
</P>
<P>
   Dainius Zubrus took the puck away from Sean O'Donnell and fed
Zholtok, who beat Kings goalie Jamie Storr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did we think it was over? Maybe a little,'' said Storr, who
faced 27 shots. ``But Tampa Bay scored twice on us at the end to
tie us (Dec. 4). You don't want that to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially against the team that was looking for a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Murray called a timeout, attempting to regroup. But it wasn't
until a television timeout several minutes later that the Kings
caught their breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``From there I felt we regained control,'' Murray said. ``It was
an emotional night, but we didn't want to lose what we had worked
so hard to get.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, Laperriere was not booed during pregame
introductions. The Canadiens, however, were not so kind.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second, Arron Asham went after Laperriere and both
received five minutes for fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he had to do it,'' Laperriere said. ``Guys on their
team told me they knew the hit (on Savage) was clean, but you don't
let things like that happen to one of your best players. I accepted
that. But it would have been hard to accept losing this game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
