<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPP-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRINCE LEADS PEPPERDINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOLETA, Calif. _ Tommie Prince dribbled the ball twice and
looked at the rim. But he was also peering into the future.
</P>
<P>
   Prince was right where he wanted to be, at the free-throw line,
trying to cinch a win for the Pepperdine men's basketball team. But
he also was in a situation he hates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like close games, they give me a scare,'' said Prince,
a senior forward, who nonetheless made two free throws with 31
seconds left to help the Waves nip UC Santa Barbara 68-64 Saturday
night at the Campus Events Center.
</P>
<P>
   Prince entered the game as a 67 percent free-throw shooter in
the young season, but he calmly canned these two with the Waves
holding a 65-63 lead and the raucous, student-dominated crowd
yelling in his ears, almost all of the 1,971 fans pleading with him
to miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know you're going to have a hostile crowd when you're
shooting crucial free throws,'' he said. ``I'm stepping up, because
I'm a senior. I tried to just go ahead and knock those free throws
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine (6-2) rallied from a sluggish start _ the Waves made
just three baskets in the game's first 10 minutes _ to win its
third consecutive game. Sophomore guard Brandon Armstrong embodied
the Waves' effort, starting 3 of 11 from the floor but making five
of seven shots in an important stretch in the final seven minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to maintain my focus,'' said Armstrong, who scored
a game-high 20 points and tied for the team-high with seven
rebounds. ``I felt like (the game) was going to come to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong made two 3-pointers in a 2{-minute span to help the
Waves lead 63-58. But the Gauchos (1-5) stayed close, and Mark
Hull's two free throws with 43 seconds left cut the lead to 65-63.
Hull, a redshirt freshman from Hoover High, had a team-high 19
points for UCSB.
</P>
<P>
   His free throws set the stage for Prince, whose foul shots
forced the Gauchos into desperate shots in the final half-minute.
David Lalazarian made a free throw with six seconds left to provide
the final score.
</P>
<P>
   Five of Pepperdine's wins this season have been by five points
or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had our share of close games, and we've had a lot of
experience there,'' Waves coach Jan van Breda Kolff said, perhaps
soothing Prince's fear. ``We do have a lot of confidence in close
games. At least I do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-99 0127EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991212.0011 </DOCNO>
