<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARKLEY WAS MORE THAN A GREAT PLAYER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We all watched in sadness Wednesday as Charles Barkley's NBA
career ended when he ruptured a quadriceps tendon in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   That's too bad, because there will never be another
athlete//entertainer//comic//actor like Barkley. Never.
</P>
<P>
   That's because today's pampered superstar athletes always take
the political route whenever the media asks them a tough question.
They won't ruffle feathers, because they fear repercussions from
the big, bad bossman.
</P>
<P>
   Not Sir Charles.
</P>
<P>
   You always knew where you stood with Barkley. And that includes
the guys who were signing his paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   When he was playing for Philadelphia, Barkley had a
well-publicized feud with Sixers general manager Gene Shue in 1992.
No way was Shue going to win a war of words with Barkley, because
no one wins war of words with the Round Mound of Rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gene Shue is a clown whose only ambition is to caddy for
\Rex-Sixers owner\S Harold Katz,'' Barkley said in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The next season, Barkley was playing for the Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley was never one to mince words. That's why he was always a
media darling, and always made the league's all-interview team.
</P>
<P>
   When the original Dream Team didn't stay in the Olympic Village
with the rest of the athletes during the 1992 Olympics, Barkley's
reasoning was simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got God on our team,'' Barkley said, referring to
Michael Jordan. ``We're going to stay where God wants us to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley was often shaking hands with fans during a deadball, and
often had running conversations with fans while games were in
action. He understood that the NBA is entertainment, and had a
unique sense of style.
</P>
<P>
   Today's money-grubbing athletes should take note.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley averaged 22.2 points and 11.7 rebounds, and shot 54.1
percent from the field during his stellar 16-year career. He knows
he could have averaged more, had he gotten in tip-top shape every
year.
</P>
<P>
   But Barkley was a party animal. He played hard, and he partied
hard.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley doesn't take any NBA championship hardware into
retirement. He departs with his dignity intact, and with the
knowledge that no one prevented him from speaking his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing but 16 years of great memories,'' Barkley said.
``I've been all over the world. I've met the best actors in the
world, the best athletes in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've met Presidents, met Bishop \RDesmond\S Tutu. I've met
regular people who made a great impact on my life. I've exceeded
all my expectations. I never expected to accomplish all the things
I did the last 16 years. I have no sadness in my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Barkley, it is us who have sadness in our hearts. Thanks for
the memories.
\Nsubheds:Rodman a Sonic? Not Seattle SuperSonics general manager
Wally Walker laughed when he was told a German sports magazine
reported that Dennis Rodman was going to sign a contract with the
Sonics next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's absolutely nothing to that,'' Walker said. ``I can't
believe German Internet has me answering questions about Dennis
Rodman.''
</P>
<P>
   The only source cited in the story was Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to Seattle, playing for the SuperSonics in the
NBA,'' Rodman said. ``I already had a meeting with Sonics owner
Barry Ackerley and general manager Wally Walker. We have an
agreement in principle.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, this is the same Rodman who, in September, said he had
a deal with the Milwaukee Bucks. Before that, he said deals were
supposedly in the works with the Los Angeles Clippers, Miami, New
Jersey, Dallas, Houston and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe next, Rodman will have a deal with the WNBA's Houston
Comets. \Nsubheds:Expensive popcorn During a recent Indiana game at
Utah, Pacers point guard Mark Jackson went to his bench and grabbed
a $5 bill.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   Jackson felt bad when he slapped a box of popcorn out of a fan's
hands after he received a technical foul. Delta Center fans booed
Jackson, but he apologized to the fan and later gave the fan $5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let him know it was all in fun,'' Jackson said. ``He didn't
want to take the money, but I gave it to him.'' \Nsubheds:Austin
solves Wizards The Washington Wizards took a six-game losing streak
into the weekend, and center Isaac Austin is not happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   Austin did not clarify whether he was talking about Wizards
owner Abe Pollin, general manager Wes Unseld or coach Gar Heard.
However, he said the Wizards' problems directly begins with
management.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always starts at the top,'' Austin said. ``It always starts
with the organization and it filters all the way down. I think it's
something that's always been here.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Austin's first season with the Wizards. So, after six
weeks, he figures he's got this organization figured out.
Eric Gay Although he was already an elite scorer, Grant Hill of the
Detroit Pistons has made his jump shot even more deadly.
Hill perfects jump shot as he awaits MVP status
It might be six years late, but Grant Hill is quietly looking like
he can unseat Michael Jordan as a bonafide scoring machine.
</P>
<P>
   In the past six games, the Detroit Pistons forward has averaged
a whopping 31.3 points per game. That includes a 39-point effort
against the Denver Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Hill has already scored at least 30 points 10 times
this season. He only accomplished that feat eight times last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Hill has been on such a tear that Pistons coach Alvin Gentry is
mentioning him as a candidate to win the league's most valuable
player award. But as long as the Pistons are hovering around the
.500 mark _ they're currently 10-10 _ Gentry knows Hill won't be
winning any MVP honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were more successful and we had a 14-3 or 14-4 record,
everybody would be talking about him for MVP,'' Gentry said.
``Obviously you have to win games to get a guy to MVP status.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's played as well as anybody in the NBA. He worked very
hard on improving his jump shot, and that's what's made him almost
impossible to guard _ the extra confidence he has in that shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill was still working on improving his jump shot four days
before he married pop singer Tamia, over the summer. Now he has an
entire offensive package to throw at defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the offensive end, I'm mixing it up a little bit with the
jumper, the drive and the post-ups, and I'm making it difficult for
the defenders,'' Hill said. ``I try to do it a lot of different
ways as opposed to just one way every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the pull-up was consistent early on this season,
but this last week, it's just been a nice rhythm. Now I have to not
do too many pull-ups and not drive all the time. You don't want to
fall in love with one or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill's teammates have noticed how his game has flourished this
season. That's because it has enabled them to get some open looks
at the basket, since Hill is drawing more defensive attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost impossible to stop him,'' Pistons guard Lindsey
Hunter said. ``Once he faces up, you've got to get up on him, but
you can't get too close to him because he'll go around you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, it's hard not to say that he's the best right now. He
can do it all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
