A6547 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-NBA-NEXT-TEX     12-12 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-NEXT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA'S GENERATION NEXT: A PARTY OF FIVE WITH GAME AND THE HYPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The future of the NBA is 22.8 years old with seven
years of college experience and 12 pro seasons. He wears the
jerseys of the Toronto Raptors, the Los Angeles Lakers, the
Philadelphia 76ers, the Sacramento Kings and the Minnesota
Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   A league that in recent years has been reduced to crybabies,
chokers, cross dressers and Chuck finally is in good hands. Forget
Scottie Pippen, Latrell Sprewell, Dennis Rodman and Charles
Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   He is Vince Carter. He is Kobe Bryant. He is Allen Iverson. He
is Jason Williams. He is Kevin Garnett.
</P>
<P>
   Generation Next has arrived to save face for the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, Bryant, Iverson, Williams and Garnett have skills and
appeal. They are the high-flying, slam-dunking, fun-loving fellas
who have inherited the future of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're young guys,'' Bryant said. ``We work very hard, and
we're pretty talented.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all different. We all have certain things we do. We all
bring a certain amount of flavor to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, they are five of a kind.
</P>
<P>
   They are popular with women, who want for a phone number. They
are popular with youngsters, who live for an autograph. They are
popular with rappers, who wear their jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David Stern has seen the ``prototype of the new
millennium.'' Carter, Williams, Bryant, Iverson and Garnett are it.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Duncan might have a ring, but his name doesn't sing quite as
sweetly on the street.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, Williams, Bryant, Iverson and Garnett are hip hop from
their sloppy street clothes to their hair styles to their earrings
and their tattoos. They all have million-dollar smiles, money-lined
pockets, peach-fuzz faces and gee-whiz looks.
</P>
<P>
   They are Sega. They are ``GQ''. They are BET. They ``are'' the
NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different era,'' said Raptors forward Charles Oakley,
who is in his 15th season. ``Fans are into the hype. They're into
individuals. The whole league is changing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Children are the league's defense against a
post-Michael letdown, though they guard against being called ``the
next Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's tough. That's tough, man,'' Carter said. ``I don't
really think anybody can do what Michael can do. You see flashes of
Jordan in probably every player in the league. It's tough to really
live up to him, because he did it for what, 14-15 years? Most of us
are only just beginning in this league. We're trying to make our
own identities.''
</P>
<P>
   The legends of Bryant, Carter, Williams, Iverson and Garnett are
on a fast break. Just check out ``SportsCenter''. They do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a fan of the NBA,'' Bryant said. ``I like watching those
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   If their moves don't get you, their personalities will.
</P>
<P>
   Carter is The Ambassador. He has a ``Vinsanity'' Web site. In
the past two months, his face has appeared on boxes of Kellogg's
Cocoa Frosted Flakes and the cover of SourceSports. He is a human
highlight reel.
</P>
<P>
   His stature is growing in 48-inch vertical leaps and bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dream,'' said Carter, the league's rookie of the
year last season. ``This is what you always think about. Every time
you say, `Well, when I get in the NBA, I'm going to be a star. I'm
going to be one of the best players.' When it actually happens,
it's a whole different situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is The Wild Child. He twice tested positive for
marijuana at the University of Florida, which got him dismissed
from the team. He has a dragon tattoo on his right arm, a panther
on his left arm and an eyeball on his chest. Rapper Sean Puffy
Combs sports his jersey.
</P>
<P>
   He is basketball on caffeine. The Rebel without a pause.
</P>
<P>
   His magnetism increases with every behind-the-back, no-look
pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody thinks a skinny white kid can play,'' said Williams, an
NBA All-Rookie choice last season. ``I try to make each game a
highlight.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant is The Kid. He is 21 going on his fourth NBA season. He
has been compared to a fine wine. He took Brandy to his high school
prom. He has million-dollar deals with Sprite and adidas. He is
fluent in Italian and in the crossover dribble.
</P>
<P>
   His profile expands with every poster-perfect dunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I studied videotapes when I was growing up,'' said Bryant, the
NBA's slam dunk winner in 1997 and an All-Star in '98. ``Magic
Johnson's backdoor moves. Hakeem \ROlajuwon\S's postup. Michael
Jordan's quickness. I just try to take bits and pieces of everybody
and add it to my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson is The Answer. He is cornrows. He is mega jewelry. He
carries the 76ers on his shoulders and wears his feelings on his
tattooed-covered arms. If you ask him, he should have been an
All-Star his rookie season and the MVP a year ago. Who can argue?
</P>
<P>
   His growing status is all that can keep up with his drive to the
basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe God gave me my talent and gifts,'' said Iverson, who
led the league in scoring last season. ``I've just taken advantage
of it and made myself better. When I play, I feel just like I did
when I was a kid in the park. I feel the energy of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Garnett is Da Kid. He arrived in Minnesota as a 19-year-old
rookie and now is known as the $125 Million Dollar Man. He played
Wilt Chamberlain in a movie. He jams to Jay Z and has his own
clothing line _ OBF (Official Block Family). His tattoo reads
``Sky's the limit.''
</P>
<P>
   His potential is as long as his tentacle-like arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great players are always distinguished on how their teams
played,'' said Garnett, a two-time All-Star. ``What really
distinguished Michael, Larry \RBird\S and Magic \RJohnson\S was
that their teams won, and they were great parts of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson, Bryant, Williams, Garnett and Carter are the new stars
of the NBA. And they have arrived just in time.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:STYLE FOR SUBSTANCE The NBA has embarked on a journey
into its future without Michael Jordan. The next generation of NBA
superstars has burst onto the scene, and has brought with them a
flair and style that defines their play.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Generation Next
The fashion style: It is defined by tattoos, cornrows, rappers and
Raptors. It is about money, movies and music. The play style: It is
space-age and fast. There are definitely no squares here. No more
triangles either. Dunk ... Dunk ... Dunk ... Style setters:
Anything to get on ``SportsCenter''. Jason Williams'
behind-the-back passes and Vince Carter's Heir Jordan dunks get
them as much face time as anybody.
\Nsubheds:Generation Air
The fashion style: Nikes and baggy shorts are in. So are bald
heads, wagging] tongues and the triangle, no bull. The play style:
Anything showtime or Showtime. The Pistons won with fists and
flops. The Lakers won with style and Magic tricks. The Bulls won
with Jordan. Style setters: Magic, Bird and Jordan did it their
way. Everyone else tried to follow.
\Nsubheds:Generation Hair
The fashion style: It is about red, white and blue basketballs,
Converse Chuck Taylor high-tops, short shorts and big hair. It is
about peace signs and protest marches. The play style: The game
finally goes on the offensive. It shoots and scores with fans.
Style setters: Jordans gets most of the credit, but it is Dr. J who
turns the NBA into a high-flying art form. He invents playing above
the rim and dunking from the free-throw line.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
