<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUSHING LMU DOESN'T REVEAL MUCH ABOUT USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's getting tough to tell just where USC stands
this season. The Trojans have lost to national powers Duke and
North Carolina, then along comes a weakling like Loyola Marymount
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   USC handed the lowly Lions their worst home defeat in school
history, a 96-55 drubbing before 2,112 at Gersten Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Considering Loyola Marymount's lone victory was against Cal
Baptist, even USC's players were a little befuddled over what the
win meant for the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really can't say where we are right now,'' said shooting
guard Jeff Trepagnier, who scored 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   If he is unsure, Trepagnier need only ask USC coach Henry Bibby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know where we stand,'' Bibby said. ``Nothing changes. It's
glaring. We got beat off the dribble just like against Duke. And
we're not taking charges like we want.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a true coach, but even Bibby found plenty of
positives as USC (5-4) won back-to-back games for the first time
this season. The biggest news was that point guard Brandon
Granville finally snapped out of his shooting slump and scored a
game-high 20 points, making 6-of-8 shots, including three
3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Granville entered the game shooting just 23 percent from 3-point
range.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always told Granville that we give him the green light,''
Bibby said. ``He can shoot it. He needs to work on his mechanics.
But hopefully, one game will give him the confidence to have a
breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   Granville didn't realize his shooting percentage had dropped so
low, and said he didn't feel any different against the Lions (1-5),
except for the fact he finally starting making some shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel any better or worse than in the past,''
Granville said. ``I don't get discouraged. Coach is telling me to
shoot it. It's kind of getting to me in practice though, I can't
lie. But I'm still shooting, regardless of my confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone was making shots for the Trojans in the first
half, when they shot a season-high 58.3 percent and led 56-23. The
lead grew so big that Bibby cleared the bench.
</P>
<P>
   That meant Frank Evanisko, a 5-foot-10 walk-on who isn't on the
roster and didn't have his name on his jersey, played one minute
and scored one point.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't bad, but we knew if we did what we were supposed
to do we would win by at least 20,'' Trepagnier said.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when Granville _ USC's primary outside shooter _ gets
hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said from the beginning of the year, Brandon is the key to
this team,'' forward Brian Scalabrine said. ``If he has a good
game, then we'll play well.''
</P>
<P>
   In an encouraging sign for the Trojans, freshman guard Nate Hair
also made two 3-pointers and scored a career-high nine points.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: Freshman center Kostas Charissis fouled out in just
nine minutes of action. He also fouled out in nine minutes against
UC Santa Barbara. . . . Brian Scalabrine had a career-high seven
assists, and a double-double (16 points, 10 rebounds) for the
second time in his career. . . . Former USC forward Greg Lakey, who
transferred to Loyola Marymount last summer, was in street clothes
on the Lions bench. ``I saw a lot of my friends, but tonight they
were the enemy,'' Lakey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
