<SLUG> BC-FBN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAGLIABUE LESS THAN POPULAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On January 18 in New York, the robber barons of professional
athletics the NFL owners have scheduled a most unusual meeting that
has combustible overtones.
</P>
<P>
   It is being billed as an ``Owners Only'' session, meaning it is
excluding such usual attendees as league publicists, league
attorneys, league executives and, most significantly, the league
commissioner, Mr. Paul Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the reason for this unusual pre-Super Bowl gathering is
to discuss the serious charges that the owner of the Oakland
Raiders, Al Davis, lodged against the Tagliabue regime at a recent
Atlanta meeting.
</P>
<P>
   While this isn't considered a palace revolt among the lodge
brothers that could bring down Tagliabue, it is the first time that
the NFL owners have ever met alone to discuss Tagliabue's
deportment and scrutinize his omniscient power.
</P>
<P>
   What has incurred Davis' wrath and has a few other owners not
joined at the hip with Tagliabue grumbling is the mysterious
financial manipulations believed to be orchestrated by Tagliabue,
namely the creation by the NFL's finance committee of something
called the ``executive compensation fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis and the five other spoilsports who are aligned with him
those owners in Dallas, Buffalo, Cincinnati, Detroit and Miami
believe the basis of this fund is to enrich the private coffers of
Tagliabue and his highest-ranking aides.
</P>
<P>
   And since the fund reportedly is in the $100 million range, it
doesn't take a doctorate in mathematics to figure out a lot of
executives are benefiting handsomely from such a staggering
largesse.
</P>
<P>
   It's known Tagliabue's salary alone now exceeds $6 million a
year, and there are those who think he's making twice as much from
the ``executive compensation fund'' that reportedly has made a lot
employees in Tagliabue's office at 280 Park Avenue wealthy beyond
their wildest ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   It's not surprising the NFL owners voted 28-0 (Davis and Dallas'
Jerry Jones abstained and Seattle was absent at the time of the
balloting) not to pursue a formal investigation of Davis' charges,
since none wanted the spectacle of a high-profile lawsuit and its
ensuing negative publicity and immense cost.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue and his league lackeys have peddled the public
perception that the 28-0 vote was a total rebuke of Davis, but that
apparently isn't the case.
</P>
<P>
   There are several owners who think there might be credence in
Davis' accusations, and that the entire mess is a reflection of the
mighty empire Tagliabue has built for himself through his shrewd,
billion dollar television contract negotiations that have tripled
the value of NFL franchises in recent years and through his sly
back room, trading-for-favors machinations that have resulted in
many NFL owners being beholden to him.
</P>
<P>
   There are owners who think that this ``executive compensation
fund'' is nothing more than a Tagliabue-instigated gimmick to make
himself and his top hirelings a lot of extra money and that
Tagliabue has fallen prey to Lord Acton's celebrated dictum,
``Power tends to corrupt and absolute power corrupts absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   There are owners who think that Tagliabue needs to be reined in,
and that there has to be a greater accountability on his part for
the dispersal of the millions of dollars that have been flowing out
to the beneficiaries of the ``executive compensation fund.''
</P>
<P>
   The mere fact that the NFL owners have called for an exclusive
meeting is an indication of their growing discontent, but it's
doubtful that Paul Tagliabue is in serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that the NFL has prospered incredibly with
Paul Tagliabue, under whose stewardship the league has had an
unprecedented glut of community-subsidized stadiums built and also
a record amount of franchise shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue isn't in danger of being defrocked because he has
cleverly maneuvered to have the owners of 17 franchises Carolina,
Atlanta, New Orleans, Houston, Chicago, Arizona, Kansas City, San
Diego, Denver, Jacksonville, Pittsburgh, Tennessee, Baltimore,
Cleveland, Indianapolis, New England and the New York Giants firmly
in his corner.
</P>
<P>
   Those straddling the fence in regard to Tagliabue can be found
in St. Louis, San Francisco, Tampa Bay, Green Bay, Minnesota,
Washington, Philadelphia, Seattle and the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Tagliabue figures to survive that Jan. 18 tete-a-tete among
NFL owners, but he might come out of it with some of his power
diminished and might not be so brazen in the future as to promise
league money to potential expansion cities, as he did with Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   If there is anything those multimillionaire NFL owners detest
more than giving seven-figure signing bonuses to first-round draft
picks, it would be the ungodly spectacle of their own hand-picked
caretaker doing what he damned well pleases with their money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
