<SLUG> BC-BKN-ALONZO-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOURNING QUOTES RILEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW BAGGARLY  
 c.1999 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The first signs came last season, after the Miami
Heat rudely had been tossed from the playoffs by the New York
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Alonzo Mourning stood in front of the microphones and tried to
explain how the top-seeded Heat had lost. He couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   But he came up with this nugget of wisdom: ``Adversity
introduces a man to himself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning didn't cite the quotation. But most observers knew it
had a familiar ring. It was one of Miami coach Pat Riley's favorite
maxims.
</P>
<P>
   There were more signs as training camp opened this season; more
confidence, more echoed statements. Mourning had become more than
Riley's star player. He had become the coach's disciple.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-10 center was runner-up behind Karl Malone for league
MVP honors last season. He had transformed himself from spoiled
multimillionaire to level-headed superstar.
</P>
<P>
   He found direction in his professional life, hit the weight room
with a determined stare and conditioned himself into becoming a
better player. And it was Riley who stood watch, pushing him to go
further.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it this way,'' Mourning said. ``This is my
livelihood. If I don't feel the need to work at it and refine it,
why am I playing the game?
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure I work two to three hours a day and then I'm done.
I've got the rest of the day. There aren't too many jobs like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley and Mourning get on each other in practice, challenge each
other, fight like a middle-aged couple. But more than anything,
they believe in each other.
</P>
<P>
   Riley believes Mourning is the player that will lead him to
another NBA title, something Patrick Ewing couldn't accomplish
during Riley's New York years.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Mourning almost blindly follows Riley, exudes the same
self-assured glow, believes that the Heat is destined for greater
riches.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been times when Mourning's burning desire to win
hasn't mixed well with Riley's cool resolve.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, when Miami started quickly out of the gate,
Riley said in a postgame radio interview that he envisioned 20-25
losses this season.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning heard it, and boasted that the team wouldn't lose 10.
They tanked the next game at Atlanta, and Riley reportedly was
furious.
</P>
<P>
   But as they always do, Mourning and Riley hashed out their
differences.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a relationship that has defined the Heat this
season and has given it a championship feel that is unique in its
conference. The only real beast in the East, Miami appears a heavy
favorite to sweep its way to the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Who's gonna stand in their way? The Hornets? The Raptors?
</P>
<P>
   The temporary loss of Tim Hardaway notwithstanding, it doesn't
look like adversity will be introduced to the Heat anytime before
June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to take every team seriously,'' Mourning said.
``That's home and away. East or West. Every team has pride, and
none of them want to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but how many teams have a top-flight center like Mourning?
If you count San Antonio's Tim Duncan as a power forward, then the
answer is one: the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   But even Shaquille O'Neal can't do for the Lakers what Mourning
does for the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning catches the ball under the basket and scores. He
catches from 10 feet out and scores. He catches from the top of the
key, the three-point line _ and he slashes to the basket like a
guard.
</P>
<P>
   His post moves are reminiscent of a younger, more mobile Hakeem
Olajuwon. And he has the league's best head fake.
</P>
<P>
   He can go left or right off the dribble, shoot with either hand,
hit the medium-range jumper with consistency.
</P>
<P>
   And Shaq, get this: He works on his free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be an 80-percent shooter, but I've been closer to 65
this year.'' Mourning said. ``That's something I've been
disappointed in.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of complaining about the NBA's new rules, Mourning
worked on ways to use them to his advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing both ends of the floor like a madman,'' P.J.
Brown said. ``He's passing the ball a lot better. His ability to
find the open man has been the biggest key for us this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Riley: ``He's not settling for jumpshots. He's driving,
creating, pushing himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one making everything work for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
