<SLUG> BC-BKN-BAGGAR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAREWELL TO BARKLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW BAGGARLY  
 c.1999 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He threw a 5-foot-2 man into a plate-glass window. He spat on
children. He elbowed an Angolan player in a friendly international
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when he was given every opportunity to apologize, he
refused.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley gave us every reason to despise him. So why are
we so sorry to see him go?
</P>
<P>
   Why, days after he ruptured a tendon in his knee and announced
his retirement from the NBA, do we have a twinge of nostalgia? Why
do we wish he'd won that championship ring?
</P>
<P>
   Why will we miss Charles Barkley?
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't like he was a role model. He wasn't an advertisement
for clean living or unselfishness or team achievement.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have Julius Erving's grace or Kareem Abdul-Jabbar's
poise or Willis Reed's toughness.
</P>
<P>
   And he certainly did not have Michael Jordan's singular will to
win. Barkley finished his career without a championship, one of the
requirements for lasting greatness.
</P>
<P>
   But Barkley had something else, something that allowed the rest
of us to identify with him. He had charisma. Charm.
</P>
<P>
   You could have a drink with Barkley. He was approachable.
Fun-loving. The life of the party.
</P>
<P>
   We admired his fearlessness. Barkley stood up for himself. He
wasn't afraid to discuss controversial subjects or blast a referee
who wasn't up to snuff _ league fines and columnists' barbs be
damned.
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase Jordan, Charles said the things most other NBA
players were thinking _ and presumably, were too afraid to state
publicly.
</P>
<P>
   We admired his determination. We are fascinated by the underdog,
and at 6-foot-5, Barkley certainly was that at his power forward
position. He backed his way into the lane, using that sizable
posterior for leverage. He used that same rear end to box out on
the boards.
</P>
<P>
   And off the court, no question, Barkley could make an ass of
himself. He was involved in three separate barroom scuffles _ all
of which he quieted by settling out of court.
</P>
<P>
   He was booed roundly when he attempted to spit on a heckler,
instead hitting a 10-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   And he typified the ``Ugly American'' to the international
sporting world when, as a member of the Dream Team, he delivered a
forearm shiver to the chest of an Angolan player _ during the
waning moments of a blowout U.S. victory.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly class or sportsmanship. But that was Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   So you could understand why, in his veteran years, rookies
didn't offer him the same respect they gave Hakeem Olajuwon.
Barkley recommending a code of conduct was akin to taking golf
lessons from him. (If you've ever seen the hitch in his swing from
one of those televised celebrity pro-am tournaments, you know what
we're referring to.)
</P>
<P>
   Sir Charles knew it was time to get out of the game. He already
announced this season would be his last. The injury just moved the
process forward.
</P>
<P>
   Given Barkley's turbulent career, the abrupt end isn't a
surprise. Nothing ever went quite to script. The happy ending never
seemed to be destined for him.
</P>
<P>
   But he has two Olympic gold medals, five all-NBA first-team
selections, a league MVP award, 23,577 points, 12,545 rebounds, and
he was named one of the NBA's 50 Greatest Players.
</P>
<P>
   Was he a role model? No, but as he often pointed out, he never
signed up to be. Parents are role models, he often said. Teachers.
Police officers. Community leaders. The clergy.
</P>
<P>
   He was unabashedly unapologetic for the way he thought and acted
and played and lived. Who, really, did he have to apologize to?
</P>
<P>
   Barkley was not a champion, but he was the life of the party.
And as is often the case with merrymakers, they take the revelry
with them.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Maybe the party's going to the Alabama governor's
office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
