<HEADLINE>
ZEILE RECONSIDERS, SIGNS WITH METS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; ANAHEIM, Calif. _ After agreeing to a deal with the Texas
Rangers, free agent Todd Zeile agreed to a three-year, $18 million
contract with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Zeile, a former Los Angeles Dodger and UCLA Bruin,
agreed to a three-year deal worth $16 million earlier in the day
with the Rangers and told Rangers general manager Doug Melvin he
wanted to talk to his wife and agent over dinner before signing the
contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who entered the Zeile sweepstakes late in the week,
countered with their deal. Former Dodgers catcher Mike Piazza
helped seal it by talking with Zeile. With Robin Ventura at third
base, Zeile will play first base for the Mets, replacing John
Olerud.
</P>
<P>
   A source said the Dodgers talked about a three-year deal that
would have paid Zeile $12 to $15 million, but the club couldn't
offer a contract until the Adrian Beltre situation is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, the Dodgers were never a serious
consideration,'' said Zeile, who hit .293 with 24 homers and 98 RBI
with the Rangers last season. ``I never really looked at it
realistically because I knew there was unfinished business with
Adrian Beltre and I was not in a position where I wanted to or was
able to delay things just to see if that opportunity presented
itself.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
