<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6565 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-OLIVER-MILLER-TEX     12-12 2010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-OLIVER-MILLER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESS IS MORE FOR A SLIMMED-DOWN OLIVER MILLER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Oliver Miller has finally stopped growing, and started
growing up.
</P>
<P>
   And the difference between Old and New is more than just
skin(ny) deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans mock your weight problem, toss a Twinkie onto the court
as you step to the free-throw line. Do you:''
</P>
<P>
   O) Save the Twinkie for a postgame snack, then scream ``I'm
gonna eat this Twinkie, then kick your butt for dessert!''
</P>
<P>
   N) Chuckle _ because, admit it, it's kinda funny _ then calmly
sink two free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Gorilla mascot who last year spoofed you in the old
pillow-under-the-shirt routine breaks his ankle during a freak
fall. Do you:''
</P>
<P>
   O) Laugh hysterically at the news and show up for the next game
on crutches, exacting revenge on that ``baboon-faced blockhead.''
</P>
<P>
   N) Call the mascot at home to wish him well, because, after all,
``what's in the past is in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After a coldblooded release from your hometown team three
years ago in which the general manager relayed the news through
your mother, you're asked to comment about your upcoming return. Do
you:''
</P>
<P>
   O) Vow to ``make those idiots pay for the biggest mistake of
their life, '' after an obscenity-laced tirade during which you
almost choke a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   N) Calmly state that ``I'm going to take this game very
personally,'' then thank the reporter for the interview.
</P>
<P>
   If you answered O, you probably got a kick out of the
mischievous, Old Big O.
</P>
<P>
   If you answered N, you're going to love the mature, New Oliver
Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've finally realized that when my weight is down and mouth is
shut, things go much smoother,'' said Miller, the Southwest High
School legend and former Mavericks player who returned to Reunion
Arena last night as a relatively svelte, genuinely happy reserve
for the Phoenix Suns. ``I'm busting my butt to get back on track
because I've struggled for six years. My mom always told me, `You
learn as you live,' and I've found that out the hard way.''
</P>
<P>
   With his fifth team in seven years, Miller's dream of being an
All-Star center has been devoured by a big mouth that let in too
much food and spit out too much venom. Now, after a wasted decade
spent overweight and undermotivated, Fort Worth's all-time best NBA
player must dig in to the main-course challenge of being measured
no longer by a produce store scale but rather by hefty
contributions on the basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   Once with so much potential that Charles Barkley predicted he'd
make multiple All-Star teams, Miller now says he is, in order:
devoted father, loving son, and a 6-foot-9, 315-pound _ 60 pounds
less than his NBA weight of a year ago _ backup just trying to
salvage a career.
</P>
<P>
   Last call for Miller time.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as basketball, he knows he's about to run out of
options,'' said best friend James Gales, who used to have his
diapers changed by Miller's mom, Annie, and was among Miller's
support group of around 30 last night. ``You can see he's changing
as a person. He used to fly off the handle at little things. Now,
his main concern is that his kids have a father figure he never
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, whose father, Oliver Sr., left the family when Oliver
Jr. was 4 and is now in prison for murder, credits his recent
awakening to a heart-to-heart talk with his former head coach at
Arkansas, Nolan Richardson; a responsibility to sons Xavier, 8, and
Amman, 2; and the motivation to shed actions that made 'N Sync look
sage and a body that made Santa look positively Ally McBeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RRichardson\S just told me, `Look, you're always complaining
about how so-and-so did you wrong. It can't always be the other
guy's fault','' Miller said relaxing in the stands of the Compaq
Center before a game against the Houston Rockets last weekend.
``I've swallowed some pride and admitted I gotta make changes. But
what's in the past is in the past. I've got a chance to play for a
playoff team and be close to my sons. That's an opportunity I can't
mess up.''
\Nsubheds:Home sick Though he's still a few smirks this side of
humble and often responds to authority about as well as the Mars
Polar Lander, Miller's new milder manners have already helped him
deal with taunting from fans, similar to the Twinkie incident from
Duke crazies when the Razorbacks played at Cameron Indoor Arena in
1991. It also moved him _ at least publicly _ to take pity rather
than pride in the Suns' Gorilla being sidelined six to eight weeks
after last week's accident.
</P>
<P>
   And it helped Miller soften _ though certainly not erase _ his
wrath toward Mavericks coach/GM Don Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still the worst thing that's happened to me in
basketball,'' Miller said. ``Every time we play the Mavericks I'm
going to do my best to bang them in the head.''
</P>
<P>
   In February '97, Miller was a backup on a decaying Mavericks
team coached by Jim Cleamons. After a loss to the Denver Nuggets in
which he played five minutes, Miller responded ``I don't care
anymore,'' to a question about his limited role. Miller claims he
meant he didn't care how much he played because, whatever his role,
he would abide by Cleamons' decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, though in his new job only two hours, cut Miller
immediately upon reading the quotes in local papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of GM cuts a player before even meeting him?'' said
Miller, informed of the move by his mother. ``He's like the
Godfather of basketball that way. It wasn't fair, but he's not man
enough to admit he made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Annie Miller: ``Was it unprofessional? Let's just say it
happened exactly that way and let people make up their own minds. I
was relieved when they released him, because looking at the
Mavericks, no mother wants her child to be in that type
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he only told Miller's mother because he wasn't able
to notify Miller himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was on the road driving and we had to inform somebody,''
said Nelson. ``I don't plan on talking to him \Rlast night\S, but I
do wish him the best. I sincerely hope he has things turned
around.''
\Nsubheds:Final answer? Despite a tact that hits you with all the
subtlety of Morganna, Miller has always had that eye-popping
talent.
</P>
<P>
   A point guard trapped in a nose guard's body, Miller's enormous
hands are soft and sneaky, his huge eyes inquisitive with
incredible peripheral vision, and he not so much runs but rather
bounces gracefully on the balls of his feet. With uncanny passing,
a feathery touch and a 7-3 shot-blocking wingspan, he led Southwest
to the '88 state title and Arkansas to three consecutive finishes
in The Associated Press top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always the best dancer on our team,'' said Richardson.
``He's got the best hands I've ever seen, and he could throw a
football 70 yards on a sparrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Those natural skills made him the 22nd selection in the 1992
draft, but after Big O' Mistakes in Phoenix, Detroit and Toronto,
Miller landed in Dallas in '96 playing for the league minimum.
After two more failed stints with Toronto and Sacramento, he showed
up back in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Through five agents, five teams and a lockout stint in Greece,
Miller is back where he started, but a long way from where he
began.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been around the track and I think he realizes he's had a
lot of good chances and blown them all,'' Suns chairman Jerry
Colangelo said. ``He wants to start over. So far, so good.''
</P>
<P>
   The cartoon combination of Fat Albert and Bart Simpson, the Big
O is more than earning his one-year, non-guaranteed, $510,000
contract. Almost 60 pounds lighter than last year when he played
only four games with the Kings, Miller is averaging seven 5.6
points and 4.6 rebounds per game and is usually on the court
instead of Luc Longley in crunch time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oliver knows this is the end of his rope,'' Suns coach Danny
Ainge said. ``He's an incredible talent and, to me, he's worth the
trouble. He's finally being accountable for his actions. He's
screwed up a lot and he knows it. It seems like he may have turned
the corner.'' \Nsubheds:Two kids, no seconds Along with the
nauseating feel of the noose tightening around his career, Miller
also has two little bundles of motivation and a rededication not to
eat himself into early retirement. Though his relationship with his
ex-wife remains distant, he sees his children, Xavier and Amman,
who live in Phoenix, every other day and on weekends, often taking
them to practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like seeing their eyes light up when I pick
them up from school,'' said Miller, sporting huge gold loops in
each ear and a tattoo of ``Amman'' on his right biceps. ``I want
them to have the dad I never got to have. I want to be there for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Annie, who drives to see her son play in Houston and San
Antonio, bristles at the mention of Oliver's father. Miller hasn't
spoken to his father since posting his bond and paying for his
lawyer before the murder trial in '95. Neither claims to know _ or
care _ where he is. And Oliver Sr. isn't due for parole until 2010
for being convicted of walking into a Fort Worth office and
shooting Emmett ``Pete'' Allen, the man who pushed for the city to
declare an ``Oliver Miller Day'' when he was drafted by Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might try to contact him, but I don't know,'' Oliver Jr.
said softly. ``I just know how difficult it was growing up in a
one-parent household and I'm not going to let that happen to my
boys. Thankfully, I had a strong mom. She's my everything, my best
friend. Without her I'd be in jail or on drugs or dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important to Miller's renovation is his new-found
waist management, founded upon not ordering every dropped chalupa
to ``get in my belly.'' Last year in Sacramento, his 375 pounds led
to debilitating back spasms. Once so big he had to be weighed by
the Suns on the big scale at a produce store, Miller said he is on
medication for an overactive thyroid and is being more sensible
about what and how much he eats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not as much fried stuff or sweets,'' he said. ``And when I'm
thirsty I drink water instead of root beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Suns guard Jason Kidd, a firsthand witness to Miller's
shenanigans in Dallas, believes in this Story of O.
</P>
<P>
   ``He almost ate himself out of the league, and I think that hit
home,'' Kidd said. ``The work ethic is there now. He's not late for
the bus, he listens in meetings. He used to find ways to take all
the shortcuts and he paid the price for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Written off by the Suns, Pistons, Raptors (twice), Mavericks and
Kings, only a few people _ like Annie and Continental Basketball
Association owner Isiah Thomas _ kept faith in Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the tragic plight of Mavericks rookie Leon Smith,
Thomas said Miller should be applauded for succeeding despite a
father-less environment that can easily promote failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd jump in a foxhole with Oliver,'' said Thomas, Raptors
president during Miller's turbulent stop. ``If I had bought a team
last summer, he'd be on it. A lot of kids with his situation turn
to drugs or crime. Maybe we should be thankful he instead turned to
food.''
</P>
<P>
   And Miller's just thankful that he has two chances:
</P>
<P>
   Slim and none.
\Nsubheds:TALE OF THE TAPE Former Southwest High School star Oliver
Miller is with his fifth NBA team in seven seasons. A look at each
of his previous stops and the pitfalls he hopes to avoid with his
more mature approach to the game and life:'' Years Team Weight
Comment '92-94 Phoenix 320 Charles Barkley predicts multiple
All-Star appearances. '94-95 Detroit 330 Coach Doug Collins: I
wouldn't trade a warm six pack for him. '95-96 Toronto 315 Best
season ruined by bad decision to pass up $9 mil extension. '96-97
Dallas 340 Cut immediately by new GM Don Nelson his first day on
the job. '97-98 Toronto 340 Suspended for insubordination by coach
Butch Carter '98-99 Sacramento 375 Sidelined by back spasms;
Spoofed by Gorilla mascot '99-00 Phoenix 315 Serviceable backup
playing 20 minutes for playoff team
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
