<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-ZEILE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZEILE STUNS RANGERS, TAKES DEAL WITH METS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The New York Mets swept in at the last minute
and stole third baseman Todd Zeile from the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers thought yesterday they had a deal in place with
Zeile for three years at $16 million, but the Mets signed him late
last night for three years at $18 million to replace John Olerud as
their first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I'm disappointed,'' Rangers general manager Doug
Melvin said. ``I had talked to Tom Hicks earlier today, and I
thought we had the deal done.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said the Rangers will consider rookie third baseman Mike
Lamb, but they have also discussed pursuing free agent Tony
Fernandez, who was an all-star for the Toronto Blue Jays last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin met with Zeile and his agent, Seth Levinson, for one hour
last night. After agreeing on the length and the terms of the
agreement, Zeile told Melvin he wanted to have dinner with his
agent and his wife, Julianne, before making a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   When Melvin found out just before midnight that Zeile had gone
with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always that fear that someone will come in at the last
minute,'' Melvin said. Pitching on hold The Rangers' quest for
another starting pitcher will remain on hold until Chuck Finley
decides where he wants to pitch next year. The Rangers are no
longer on Finley's list, but his decision could determine if they
end up with Aaron Sele or Kenny Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Sele and his agent, Adam Katz, seem to be waiting for Finley to
make up his mind, and the Cleveland Indians offered the former
Angels left-hander a three-year contract yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   If Finley decides to pitch in Cleveland, the Rangers would
likely be competing with the Seattle Mariners for Sele's services.
Sele has expressed a desire to return to the Rangers, but he's from
the Seattle area and makes his home there.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mariners are more interested in Finley, and if he
accepts their three-year offer, the Rangers would have the inside
track on Sele.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a holding pattern right now,'' said Katz, who has yet
to counter the four-year contract proposal made by the Rangers a
month ago. ``I expect things to pick up in the next week or so.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers continue to talk with Rogers' agent Scott Boras as a
possible backup if they lose Sele. But Boras said Rogers, 35, will
command a four-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's interest on both sides,'' Boras said. ``I've talked
with Doug, and we'll continue to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said to this point the Rangers have waited on Sele, but
he may need to pursue other options soon.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers met with the Minnesota Twins yesterday and asked
about pitcher Brad Radke. But the Twins are still hoping they can
sign him to a long-term contract before he becomes a free agent
after next season. Briefly The Rangers are interested in Giants
outfielder F.P Santangelo, a switch-hitter who hit .260 last year.
He could be the Rangers' fourth outfielder, but he can also play in
the infield.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets and the Rangers met yesterday to discuss first baseman
Lee Stevens, but a deal isn't likely. Melvin said the two teams
don't appear to be a match.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers trainer Danny Wheat went to Houston last week to check
on Justin Thompson and his rehabilitation program for his left
shoulder. The Rangers aren't saying if Thompson will be ready for
Opening Day, but Wheat said, ``He's doing a great job. He couldn't
be more farther along than he is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers signed Japanese minor-leaguer Koichi Taniguchi, 26,
to a minor-league contract. He is 19-21 in 138 appearances over
eight minor-league seasons.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
