</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE-PREVIEW12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Front-runner can call the shots on debatesBy Scott S.
Greenberger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Before they gathered in a New Hampshire
television studio to discuss education and taxes, Republican
presidential candidates argued about apple crates.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, who is 5-foot-6, wanted to stand on one during the
debate so he wouldn't appear much shorter than his competitors. But
if Bauer was going to stand on an apple crate, the other candidates
wanted crates, too.
</P>
<P>
   Modern televised debates are heavily scripted, with campaigns
haggling with each other and television sponsors over seemingly
trivial details such as camera angles and microphones, as well as
weightier ones such as how the questions will be organized and who
will ask them. Because the candidates trailing in the polls are
desperate for media exposure and a chance to challenge the
front-runner, the leader _ in this case, Texas Gov. George W. Bush
_ has a lot of leverage when it comes to how the debates are
structured. The format helps determine whether voters will get the
information they need to compare candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Like any front-runner, Bush has little to gain and much to lose
from a free-for-all debate format that leaves him vulnerable to
opponents' attacks or unexpected questions. And while the Bush
campaign denies it, some of the governor's campaign rivals say he
has used his front-runner status to make the last two debates
stiff, stilted and virtually useless to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It strikes me that in the debate negotiations they seem to
want them to be as structured as possible. It leaves me to wonder
what they're trying to protect the governor from,'' said Jeff
Flint, an aide to Sen. Orrin Hatch, (R-Utah). Flint was alluding to
the perception that Bush doesn't have a firm grasp of policy
specifics.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Scott McClellan called the idea that
Bush is dictating debate terms ``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate formats are up to the debate organizers. We simply
want to make sure that all the candidates have the opportunity to
fully express their ideas in a fair process,'' McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Dec. 2 debate in Manchester, N.H., the
candidates met in Phoenix last week. They will gather again in Des
Moines on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush has been trying to shape the last two debates _ the only
two he has attended _ the strategy hasn't helped him much. Even
some of his supporters say his noted affability hasn't come through
on television, and while he hasn't made a major mistake, he hasn't
shined either. In recent days, the governor has fallen behind Sen.
John McCain (R-Ariz.) in the New Hampshire polls, although it isn't
clear whether the change is connected to his debate performance.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch has proposed that the candidates tour New Hampshire and
Iowa together and engage in more open debates in the style of
Abraham Lincoln and Stephen Douglas, when both were campaigning in
1858 for election to the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's leave our spinners, our handlers and the strategists
behind, and the six of us get on a bus together and campaign
directly with the American people,'' Hatch said at the conclusion
of the New Hampshire event.
</P>
<P>
   But the forums so far resemble joint news conferences, with
limited opportunities for the candidates to actually debate each
other. Part of the problem is that with six candidates running for
the GOP nomination, it's difficult to spark the substantial,
one-on-one sparring that would give voters a better opportunity to
compare candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In the New Hampshire debate, two reporters fired separate
questions at each of the six candidates. A candidate could use his
limited response time to address the policy positions or statements
of another, but the GOP contenders did not debate each other
directly.
</P>
<P>
   The second debate on Dec. 6 in Phoenix added a twist. Although
it also featured reporters asking questions, part of the program
allowed the candidates to question each other. But most of the
candidates, including Bush, used the opportunity to tout their own
views or accomplishments and then ask another candidate to comment
on them.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hannon, political director for Phoenix debate sponsor CNN,
said that was unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can try to devise clever formats and tricky schemes to try
to turn the debate into a pro-wrestling match, but ultimately it's
up to the candidates to present themselves and decide what they
want to say,'' Hannon said. ``Voters are smart, and they can tell
if someone's relying on memorized answers or giving self-serving
speeches.''
</P>
<P>
   When the candidates meet againMonday night in Des Moines, they
will be able to question one another in a more freewheeling format
than the one in Phoenix, according to Joe Mahoney of debate sponsor
WHO-TV. In addition to their own questions, the reporters will ask
questions that citizens submitted to the station's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney said the Bush camp didn't exert undue influence on
Monday night's format. But Bill Dal Col, the campaign manager for
publisher Steve Forbes, thinks otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course they tell you that,'' Dal Col said. ``But when it
appears that Bush came to them with the date and set it up, I
guarantee there was a conversation about `this is the format we
like.' Anyone who thinks otherwise is naive.''
</P>
<P>
   Dal Col claims that Bush agreed to the Phoenix debate because he
thought that Forbes and McCain, his two closest competitors,
wouldn't be able to make it. When Forbes accepted, Dal Col said, he
got a call from a surprised Bush staffer who said he thought Forbes
wouldn't be there. McCain, who was campaigning in New Hampshire,
participated via satellite.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of format, Dal Col says, the Bush camp has tried to
make sure that candidates aren't asked the same questions. ``If
everybody had the same question, his answer could be compared to
the other candidates, and in that case he'd be in serious
trouble,'' Dal Col said. ``Unless it's a scripted, prearranged
question you know is coming, like education or tax relief, he
definitely comes out as less than outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   McClellan dismissed Dal Col's charges. ``It's totally ridiculous
to think we can tell the likes of Tom Brokaw, (Fox News Channel's)
Brit Hume, (New Hampshire anchor) Karen Brown and the gang at CNN
what questions to ask and how to ask them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hannon of CNN said Dal Col's assertions ``are typical of
campaigns that are running behind in the polls and in
fund-raising.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In every cycle, there's a debate about debates,'' he said.
``The lower you are in the polls, the more aggressive you are in
pushing debates. The higher you are, the more cautious you are and
the more circumspect.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hannon also noted that depending on their standing in the
polls, candidates have ``varying degrees of leverage'' in hashing
out the format.
</P>
<P>
   Diana Carlin, a professor of communication studies at the
University of Kansas who serves on the national advisory board on
presidential debates, said that ``any front-runner is going to call
more of the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they aren't happy with it, they're not going to show up.
And people aren't going to watch the other candidates if the
front-runner doesn't show up,'' Carlin said.
</P>
<P>
   TUNE IN FOR GOP DEBATE
</P>
<P>
   Monday's Republican presidential debate in Des Moines, Iowa,
will be broadcast on MSNBC from 8 to 9:30 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
