<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reversal of Miranda seems historically inappropriate
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Joe, you probably didn't go out looking for this
fellow with the purpose of shooting him. My guess is, however, that
you expected something from him and that's why you carried a gun.
You knew him for what he was _ no good. Then when you met him, he
probably started using foul, abusive language and he gave some
indication that he was about to pull a gun on you, and that's when
you had to act to save your own life. That's about it. Isn't it,
Joe?
</P>
<P>
   _ 1962 law enforcement manual on criminal interrogation and
confessions
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials used to be instructed to obtain
admissions of guilt by offering such scenarios. In the widely used
Inbau &AMP; Reid manual (quoted above), the interrogator also was
advised how to eliminate any possibility of a self-defense argument
after getting Joe to ``confess.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled in Miranda v. Arizona that
an individual taken into custody must be warned of his right to
remain silent and his right to an attorney _ and, if indigent, to a
state-paid one. The court said Miranda warnings were
constitutionally required. But in 1968, Congress approved an
exception: If a prosecutor can show that a confession was given
voluntarily when a suspect was arrested and that the individual's
rights weren't violated by police, the confession ought not be
excluded solely because the Miranda warnings weren't given
beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the first time in 30 years, a case based on the use of
that statute will be heard by the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Association of District Attorneys voted last week to
support a friend-of-the-court brief asking the Supreme Court to
overturn Miranda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put me down in the column of folks who would like to see
Miranda changed,'' says Bob Keller, Clayton County district
attorney and member of the state Prosecuting Attorneys Council. J.
Tom Morgan, DeKalb County's district attorney, feels the same way.
</P>
<P>
   That's disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when Georgia, like most states, has increasing numbers
of immigrants who, like Ernesto Miranda more than 30 years ago,
don't understand the basic rights the Constitution guarantees every
person _ rich, poor, citizen or not _ the rule seems more necessary
than ever.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that law enforcement has come a long way since the
Miranda ruling was handed down. Back then, the Supreme Court had
evidence of police trickery, lying and physical abuse in extracting
``voluntary'' confessions. Prosecutors today are far more
professional, although Morgan concedes that trying to get a
confession prior to taking a suspect into custody is still a useful
tool. (Miranda warnings are required only after an arrest.) ``We
teach our people to interrogate and then arrest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Emory law Professor A. Morgan Cloud says the Miranda rule hasn't
ended confessions, and he sees no reason to toss the rule away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a huge success in terms of educating the public,''
he said, noting that Miranda warnings are part of popular culture,
re-enacted in movies and television shows. Some prosecutors are
criticizing the Clinton administration for not defending the 1968
post-Miranda law, but no administration _ from Nixon to Carter to
Bush _ has done so.
</P>
<P>
   Cloud says there are so many ``procedural peculiarities'' in
Dickerson v. U.S. (the current case before the court) that he's not
sure the justices will even reach the constitutional issue. But if
they do, he worries that it could be a close call. Justice Antonin
Scalia has openly questioned whether Miranda is constitutionally
required, and Justice Sandra Day O'Connor said 15 years ago that
she wouldn't have voted for it _ although she may feel differently
today.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, prosecutors have found that too much reliance on a
confession can stand in the way of a complete investigation.
</P>
<P>
   With a panoply of new truth-getting tools at their disposal,
it's hard to understand why prosecutors still oppose
constitutionally guaranteeing Miranda safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they should go back and read the words of Chief Justice
John Marshall in 1821. The rights guaranteed in the Fifth and Sixth
amendments, he said, were secured ``for ages to come, and designed
to approach immortality as nearly as human institutions can
approach it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
