</P>
<P>
   MENTAL-HEALTH (Washington) _ (Exclusive. Not for release to News
Service.) About 20 percent of Americans experience mental disorders
in any given year, and about half of all Americans have such
disorders at some time in their lives, but a ``majority of those
who need mental health treatment do not seek it'' because they do
not realize that effective treatments exist or they fear
discrimination because of the stigma still attached to mental
illness, the Clinton administration says in a major new report.
(Report to be issued Monday by U.S. surgeon general.) By Robert
Pear.
</P>
