<P>
   McCain is not unfunny himself _ he cracked the best joke of the
first debate, about his obsessive admiration for Alan Greenspan at
the Federal Reserve _ yet his campaign persona could hardly be more
different.
</P>
<P>
   He has the straight-backed stance of a soldier, a soldier's
directness of gaze: he does not hesitate to use words like
``heroism,'' ``honor'' and ``sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   Without necessarily reliving his prisoner-of-war years in
Vietnam, his speeches are suffused with that experience.
</P>
<P>
   He has so much gravitas of such an old-fashioned variety that
his audiences _ attuned, even in New Hampshire, to the fluff and
tinsel of modern campaigns _ can find his persona as disconcerting,
in its way, as the capers of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally enough, these different world-views translate into
very different approaches to foreign policy. Bush, famous now for
his failure to get places and names straight, still gives the
impression that foreign policy is alternately a game and a chore.
</P>
<P>
   His advisers have helped him to map out a path in which the
preservation of American sovereignty is uppermost (a popular
theme), and in which interventions abroad are kept to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   How different from McCain, who sees America as the preeminent
force for good in the world, and who thinks America should be
prepared not only to intervene when necessary, but to take
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Does all this suggest that McCain is The Economist's Republican?
Not necessarily, for in terms of domestic politics the strengths
tilt to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The front-runner has laid out detailed manifestoes for governing
that suggest a busy incrementalist: tending to fiscal incaution,
perhaps, but skeptical of government, sharp-eyed on social problems
and unafraid to experiment with such things as charter schools and
church-based welfare systems.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, McCain has linked most of his thinking about domestic
policy to the probably unattainable Holy Grail of campaign-finance
reform; and, unlike Bush, he has not prepared himself for the
presidency by running the country's second-biggest state.
</P>
<P>
   He has also not prepared himself by learning how to work with
others. Where Bush is famous for bringing Texas Democrats around to
his way of thinking, McCain is equally famous for having alienated,
both with temper and aloofness, his own colleagues in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   His penchant for plain speaking and maverick thinking
(refreshing, on its face, in a president) may be hazardous to his
political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   So too may be his stance as an ``outsider.'' Bush used to stress
his own outsider status, cowboy boots and all. But he has now put
that quietly aside in favor of being effective, and it does not
seem to have damaged him.
</P>
<P>
   Could the answer be a Bush-McCain ticket, Light and Heavy
together? Probably not, for McCain hardly has the self-effacing
emollience required of a vice-president.
</P>
<P>
   Americans _ and not a few foreigners _ can only regret that the
best parts of these two are not combined in a single candidate. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
