u f BC-SUNDAY-TV-TALK-NYT &LR;      12-12 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-TV-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC IS IN COMMAND OF SUNDAY MORNING TALK SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the campaign for the presidential election of 2000
gears up, so does the race among the Sunday morning political
discussion programs on television. And this race has a clear
front-runner: NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   In almost a direct reversal of the competitive status of the
Sunday programs in the last two presidential election years, ``Meet
The Press'' is now the definitive, dominant leader, while ABC's
``This Week,'' once the hottest show, has slid backward. It is now
being challenged for second place in the ratings by ``Face The
Nation'' on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   While their overall number of viewers is not large, the Sunday
talk programs are considered extremely important inside the network
news divisions and network corporate offices. As Andrew Heyward,
the president of CBS News, put it, ``they are terribly important
aspects of a news division's presence in Washington. They are
furiously competitive in terms of booking guests. And, frankly,
there is a lot of money to be made on them.''
</P>
<P>
   In election years, the programs take on importance even beyond
their profit figures. Booking candidates and having them make news
on the programs becomes a primary goal. The ratings edge of ``Meet
The Press'' is clearly an advantage in booking guests, network
executives said.
</P>
<P>
   One indication is next Sunday's scheduled joint appearance by Al
Gore and Bill Bradley on ``Meet The Press,'' in what its moderator,
Tim Russert, calls ``as close to the Lincoln-Douglas debate format
as we're likely to see in this campaign.'' ABC notes that it has
both those candidates on ``Nightline'' on Thursday in a town
meeting format.
</P>
<P>
   Network executives cited numerous reasons for NBC's success, but
they mainly focused on the addition of one personality, Russert, to
``Meet the Press'' and the subtraction of another, David Brinkley,
from ``This Week.''
</P>
<P>
   Russert is widely credited with reinventing the venerable (it is
52 years old) ``Meet The Press,'' changing it from a sleepy
encounter between reporters and Washington newsmakers into a taut,
in-depth, issue-dense interview program that usually pits the
bulldog style of Russert against the newsmaker of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's ``This Week,'' meanwhile, is widely described as having
drifted since the departure of Brinkley in 1997 _ though Russert
was nosing ahead even before then. ABC's formerly heralded
``roundtable discussion'' _ now including the well-known political
reporters Sam Donaldson and Cokie Roberts, and the commentators
George Will, George Stephanopoulos and William Kristol _ has
apparently lost some of its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In the November sweeps, ``Meet the Press'' scored a 3.4 rating
to a 2.4 for ABC and a 2.1 for CBS. (Each rating point represents
just over 1 million homes.) More ominously for ABC, CBS' program
beat or tied ``This Week'' among viewers between 18 and 49, the
category that matters most to advertisers on news programs.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most telling statistic is where the programs have
moved since November 1991. At that time, ``This Week'' had 3.9
million viewers. ``Face The Nation'' had 2.85 million, and ``Meet
the Press,'' 2.81 millions. This November the numbers were: ``Meet
The Press,'' 4.1 million viewers, or a 46 percent increase; ``This
Week,'' 2.8 million viewers, down 27 percent; and ``Face the
Nation,'' 2.5 million, down 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Two other competitors, ``Fox News Sunday'' and ``Late Edition''
on CNN, have smaller numbers of viewers but have also become
factors in the competition, both showing some growth in total
viewers over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   While executives at NBC, ABC and CBS describe their programs as
profitable, NBC has usurped the position of leader in terms of
profits. One industry executive said that NBC was making about $40
million in annual profit on ``Meet The Press,'' much more than its
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The competitiveness of an election year is one reason why David
Westin, the president of ABC News, wants ``This Week'' to make
significant changes by the end of the month. ``We are not at all
where we need to be with the show,'' Westin said of ``This Week.''
``Improving the bookings and the focus of the show are the things
we need to do. I want to see us come out of the box in January with
something different.''
</P>
<P>
   Something different might start with some way to separate the
program more convincingly from its past. The program became so
associated with David Brinkley that more than two years after his
departure, ``This Week'' is routinely referred to inside ABC News
as the Brinkley show.
</P>
<P>
   Under Brinkley, ``This Week'' became the first Sunday program to
expand to an hour. From its start in 1981, it towered over the
competition, until Russert arrived in December 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to take advantage of the election of 1992, he asked NBC
to temporarily expand ``Meet the Press'' to an hour. The program,
reformatted to emphasize Russert's one-on-one interviews, quickly
made news that year, especially in interviews with Gore and Ross
Perot.
</P>
<P>
   Now his interviews are considered something of a watershed
challenge for candidates. When Bush decided to sit down with
Russert, it became a widely reported part of his campaign coverage
that he had managed to get through the interview without seriously
stumbling.
</P>
<P>
   The panel section of the program has been reduced under Russert.
Some competitors have suggested that this reflects Russert's desire
to make ``Meet the Press'' more the Tim Russert show. Russert said
he shifted from the panel questioning both to give the program more
flexibility (he has gone as long as 27 minutes without a
commercial) and because contemporary candidates are so
sophisticated and good at managing the media that only a totally
focused interview can ``get through all the gobbledygook.''
</P>
<P>
   Heyward of CBS News said that Russert's style works because ``he
is very clearly seen as the audience's surrogate, not as an
ideologue.''
</P>
<P>
   He argued that CBS' anchor for ``Face The Nation,'' Bob
Schieffer, was similarly regarded. Heyward added, ``Look at the way
Russert looks. He looks like Everyman.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Clinton administration figures felt that Russert's
personal views took over during his pursuit of the Monica Lewinsky
episode, saying he was openly hostile. Russert said he had been
fair, noting that he took on Clinton enemies like Rep. Dan Burton,
R-Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Westin said he believed that the Lewinsky
coverage had badly damaged ``This Week.'' ``We have five people on
the show who more or less came out in the same place,'' he said.
``When you have a story that goes on for over a year, that gets
tedious after a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he intends to remake ``This Week'' more in the image of
``Meet The Press,'' Westin said more one-on-one interviews were
likely. Asked if the program might shift to a single main anchor,
he said, ``There is not any plan to go to that in the near
future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
