<HEADER>
A6650 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-SYRIA-COX     12-12 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SYRIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SYRIAN MINISTER'S COMMENTS FIRE UP ISRAELI ANTICIPATION
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM Predictions by Syria's foreign minister Sunday that
his country could make peace with Israel in ``a few months'' has
raised Israeli expectations for the peace talks scheduled to start
this week
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a very important moment in the history of the
peace process,'' Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk Sharaa told
reporters in Damascus. ``We think we can achieve genuine results
within a short time if all the parties have the good intentions.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharaa said he is optimistic that the two countries, which have
been officially at war since 1948, could conclude a deal in ``a few
months.''
</P>
<P>
   They were the first official comments from Syria about the talks
since they were announced by President Bill Clinton last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   This Wednesday, Sharaa will meet with Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak in Washington. The meeting, scheduled for two days, will
be the first time negotiators for the two countries have met
formally in more than three years and they are the highest contacts
between the two countries ever.
</P>
<P>
   Though their heavily fortified borders have been quiet since the
1973 war, the two countries have been officially at war for
decades. Syria has lead the block of Arab countries that have
refused to open relations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Spokespeople for Barak said the prime minister had no comment
about Sharaa's remarks. However, Israel was buzzing with
speculation after four days of rapid developments that have left
many shocked, pleased or both.
</P>
<P>
   Moshe Maoz, Syria expert at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem,
warned that there were also times of optimism during the failed
negotiations of that took place between 1994 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said Sharaa's comments were indicative of the
current Syrian mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's right. There are not many issues left to be discussed,''
Maoz said. ``This is also the line in Damascus.''
</P>
<P>
   The key issue for both sides is ownership of the Golan Heights,
a plateau about the size of Rhode Island. Syria used it to shell
Israeli towns until Israel captured it in the 1967 war. Syrian
leaders say they will make no deal unless all the Golan is
returned.
</P>
<P>
   Though most governments do not recognize the area as Israeli
land, Israel has settled about 17,000 people there. It is
considered by many as strategic high ground, but some analysts and
government ministers say its importance has dwindled in the age of
missile warfare. They say returning the Golan could end Israel's
war in Lebanon, a country basically controlled by Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Barak will speak to the Israeli parliament Monday, which is
expected to vote on some kind of statement about his trip.
Meanwhile, Barak has promised to hold a public referendum on any
deal with Syria and Israelis were already beginning to debate a
possible peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion is split, but some analysts believe it will be
hard for Israelis, ultimately, to turn down a deal with one of
their oldest enemies.
</P>
<P>
   In the Golan Heights town of Katzrin, officials moved up the
opening of a new subdivision in order to make their point that they
don't plan on leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Golan is our homeland. We are not moving from the Golan,''
Avi Zeira, head of the Golan residents committee told Israel radio.
</P>
<P>
   Zeira's group planned a large protest outside the parliament
Monday. But some in Katzrin said they would be willing to abandon
their town in exchange for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it's about time that Barak and (Syrian President
Hafez) Asad will sit together and we know the price,'' said Yoav
Tsur(cq), a 22-year Golan resident and member of a group backing a
peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   Tsur said he had been shocked by the announcement of the talks
and the Syrian and Israeli optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, I prefer its going to be fast,'' Tsur said. ``The worst
situation we have here is not knowing what is going to happen
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Kaplow's e-mail address is LarryK(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Material from The Associated Press was used in this article.
</P>
