<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Dec. 13, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Potent thunderstorms will erupt in portions of the Southeast as
humid air streaming north from the Gulf of Mexico intercepts a jet
stream disturbance passing overhead. An area of showers and
thunderstorms will march eastward from Alabama on Monday morning,
reaching the western Carolinas by afternoon. To the west, a broken
line of very strong thunderstorms will ignite over eastern
Mississippi, likely affecting Alabama by afternoon. Winds shifting
direction with increasing altitude will induce a few of the
thunderstorms to rotate. These storms, called supercells, are
capable of spawning tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and isolated thunderstorms will also occur from Arkansas
to the lower Ohio Valley as low pressure moves northeast from the
lower Mississippi Valley. Generally overcast and mild conditions
will cover the remainder of the East, except in Florida and along
the Southeast coast where there will be a few intervals of sun.
Moistening breezes from the Atlantic will cause a few light showers
near the east coast of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy snow will fall in the Wasatch Mountains of Utah as moist
air ahead of a cold front is forced to ascend the higher terrain.
Lighter snow showers will also pepper many of the west-facing
mountains of the northern Rockies. Windswept rain will lash the
Washington and northern Oregon coasts as a moist disturbance
arrives from the Pacific. Heavy snow will occur later today in the
Cascades. Ample sun and mild weather will cover much of California
and the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Atmospheric Memory
</P>
<P>
   This month, several storms have taken similar paths through the
southern Plains. In parts of southern Kansas, the spate of storms
has brought exceptional wetness over a relatively narrow zone.
Wichita has already had 3.95 inches of precipitation making the
month its third wettest December. The wettest December was in 1984
when 4.88 inches of precipitation fell. Some areas near Wichita
have had up to a foot of snow. The tendency for unlikely events to
recur in the same area has been dubbed ``atmospheric memory,'' but
its scientific underpinnings are not well understood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
