<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   GIRLS-SPORTSEQUITY _ ATLANTA _ In 1972, the year when women
first were allowed to serve as FBI agents and the Equal Rights
Amendment was passed by Congress, something called Title IX became
federal law. It mandated that school athletics programs for boys
and girls be given comparable support. More than 27 years later,
gender equity still is not the standard in most Georgia high
schools. Not even close. (Fish/Milliron, Atlanta Journal
Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   EQUITY-GHSA _ FORSYTH, Ga. _ Seated around a horseshoe-shaped
conference table, the executive committee of the Georgia High
School Association gathers twice a year to wrestle with everything
from the date of the first football practices to judging criteria
for dramatic interpretation and public speaking. Much like the high
schoolstudents whose extracurricular activities they influence, the
committee tends to break into cliques: a large group of football
coaches and athletics directors at one end of the table,
African-Americans in another section and the two women committee
members across from them, side by side. In 50 years, at least 2,500
persons have served on the committee, which governs after-school
functions involving 200,000 Georgia boys and girls. Five of them
have been women _ two-tenths of 1 percent of the committee's total
membership. To critics of the GHSA, that gender gap speaks volumes
about the attention the organization gives to girls sports in high
schools. (Fish/Milliron, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EQUITY-BOX _ Favorship facts about the lack of gender equity.
(Fish/Milliron, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
