<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RCN Planning to Acquire Small Local Phone Carrier
</P>
<P>
   Expanding its communications footprint from the East Coast to
the Midwest, RCN has agreed to acquire 21st Century Telecom Group,
a small local communications carrier based in Chicago, for about
$260 million in stock, executives close to the talks said. The deal
is expected to be announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   RCN, based in Princeton, N.J., and so far operating mainly in
the corridor between Boston and Washington, is the biggest company
competing against the regional Bell companies for residential
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Polls Show Little Year 2000 Concern
</P>
<P>
   With the days winding down until the new year, each new survey
or poll seems to add to the evidence that Americans are confident
that Year 2000 computer glitches will not have much effect on their
lives. The results add up to a challenging climate for many
entrepreneurs, particularly those who expected that disruptions and
public concern would be in full swing.
</P>
<P>
   A Century of Powerful Advertising
</P>
<P>
   Madison Avenue did not assume its familiar form until this
century, when mass-produced, name-brand products began to be
promoted through mass media. So in the spirit of summing up a
century, it only makes sense to designate the 100 most powerful
corporate and product brands of the 20th century, which must
include McDonald's, and predict which brands will be powerful in
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Web Helps Lift Newspaper Stocks
</P>
<P>
   The stocks of newspaper companies jumped last week as the
industry's numbers seemed to please both those who care about
cyclical trends and those enamored of Internet highfliers. Company
by company, executives reported at a media conference that the
cyclical business was thriving. And they also said that revenues
from their Internet properties were growing exponentially.
</P>
<P>
   GM to Run Plants at Full Speed
</P>
<P>
   Despite slowing sales and bulging inventories of unsold cars,
General Motors announced that it planned to continue running its
North American factories at close to full speed through the first
quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
   WTO to Discuss Future at Meeting
</P>
<P>
   Struggling to recover from the conference in Seattle that
collapsed in failure, the World Trade Organization plans a special
meeting on Friday to decide how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise Line Predicts Rosy Outlook
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Norwegian Cruise Line, who have rejected a $1.7
billion takeover bid by Carnival, predicted a rosy financial
outlook in what analysts said was an appeal to shareholders tempted
by the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Book of `Millionaire' Final Answers
</P>
<P>
   Since Walt Disney's Hyperion moved in last month with its
corporate cousin, ABC, the television network and the publisher
have become extremely cozy. Hyperion just hit the lottery with a
$10.95 official handbook to ABC's popular quiz show ``Who Wants to
Be a Millionaire.'' The show's writers helped to develop the book,
which has answers to perilous questions, and the game's host, Regis
Philbin, did his share by holding up the handbook during one of the
shows.
</P>
<P>
   New Directions Seen for `Moesha'
</P>
<P>
   UPN wants ``Moesha,'' the biggest comedy hit in the brief
history of the network, to veer off into what one network executive
called ``new creative directions'' _ and the show's new executive
producers are willing to do it.
</P>
</TEXT>
