<SLUG> BC-CRENSHAW-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE SONGS THAT ANCHOR THOSE STORM-TOSSED AFFAIRS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JON PARELES   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Songs that sound clear and easy don't get much
respect in the 1990s. Rock and hip-hop bands swathe their tunes in
noise; ballad singers pour on melismas and huff and puff through
crescendos. Many pop and country songs bulk up with booming drums
and synthesizers. Surrounded by overstatement, Marshall Crenshaw,
who performed at the Bowery Ballroom on the night of Dec. 9, is
more than ever a songwriter defying his era.
</P>
<P>
   When he started making albums in the '80s, he ignored the peppy
angularity of new wave rock to hark back to Buddy Holly and the
Beatles. Since then he has quietly annexed surf rock, bossa nova,
folk rock, old-fashioned country music and other pre-'70s styles
that put melody first. His tunes pretend to roll off the guitar,
though they conceal asymmetries and sly chord changes. And his
winsome tenor voice stays gentle and earnest, sliding ahead of the
beat and smoothing the corners of every phrase.
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw almost always sings about love, from the first sparks
of infatuation to domestic complications to betrayals and breakups.
While he has the voice of a nice guy, the lyrics can tell other
stories. Songs from his new album, ``No. 447'' (Razor and Tie),
face the aftermath of cheating from both sides. In ``Television
Light'' he's overcome with regrets, while in ``Tell Me All About
It'' he confronts a straying partner, then decides he doesn't
really want to know the details.
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw respects the verities of intro-verse-chorus-bridge; he
also toys with them. True to pop classicism, his songs rely on the
contrast between the stability of song form and the volatility of
the relationships he sings about. Onstage he raised that tension,
as Diego Voglino's drumming brought out the offbeats, tugging
against the rhythm of Crenshaw's guitar and vocal lines. In
``Laughter,'' with forlorn lyrics about a couple's happier
memories, Crenshaw and Chris Cunningham on guitars sent modal lines
rippling and echoing around the beat, making Crenshaw sound even
more bereft.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the night's set he juxtaposed yearning songs with
disillusioned ones. But he held on to pop's deep-seated optimism,
hoping the next romance would be as sure-fire as an uplifting tune.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Rigby, who shared the bill, recently moved to Nashville,
where her smart, funny, twang-driven songs like ``20 Questions''
could be turned into country hits. But she has more to reveal than
her cleverness. Her well-turned folk-rock and country-rock songs
portray two endless struggles: one simply to get by, another
between lust and common sense.
</P>
<P>
   She keeps falling for bad guys who exasperate her but thrill
her, too; her voice often started out wry and ended up furious.
``Let's leave reality of this, shall we?'' she suggested in one
song, knowing better but succumbing all the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
