<SLUG> BC-MARKETPLACE-NEWSPAPERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON WALL STREET, NEWSPAPER COMPANIES MAKE A COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y., Ill., Va.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine what would happen if the people who made the old Miller
Lite commercials tried their magic on newspaper stocks. The script
might go something like this:
</P>
<P>
   (Two hotshot analysts are arguing.)
</P>
<P>
   ANALYST A: Newspapers are a stodgy cyclical business!
</P>
<P>
   ANALYST B: Newspapers are a sexy Internet business!
</P>
<P>
   ANALYST A: Stodgy!
</P>
<P>
   ANALYST B: Sexy!
</P>
<P>
   (Enter soothing portfolio manager.)
</P>
<P>
   PORTFOLIO MANAGER: Relax, folks. Newspaper companies are stodgy
and sexy. They're two, two, two stocks in one.
</P>
<P>
   That more or less describes events last week, when newspaper
companies' stocks jumped 10 percent or more. The numbers seemed to
please both those who cared about cyclical trends and those
enamored of Internet highfliers.
</P>
<P>
   Company by company, the executives reported to investors at
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette's media conference that the stodgy
cyclical business was thriving. And company by company, they
reported that revenues from their Internet properties were growing
exponentially and indicated levels of investment in online
properties that reflected their commitment to the new online
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's reaction could be seen in the way the stock prices
climbed in the week. Dow Jones &AMP; Co. ended the week with its stock
price at $69.0625, a gain of 42 percent since the beginning of
January and 10.5 percent for the week. The New York Times Co.'s
stock closed on Friday at $46.4375, up 12 percent for the week and
35 percent for the year. And the Tribune Co.'s stock closed at $57,
up 14 percent for the week and 71 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line on 1999 for newspapers is that the Internet
has gone from a negative to a positive,'' said Douglas Arthur, an
industry analyst with Morgan Stanley. Pointing to the dot-com
advertising bounty in newspapers, he said the Internet was driving
ad revenues. ``It's reaffirming the role of newspapers as an ad
medium,'' he said, ``and the franchise value of the content that
newspapers have.'' A year ago, he added, ``there was this really
negative karma around the newspaper stocks, even though business
was good.'' Not now.
</P>
<P>
   Just to underline the point, the Standard &AMP; Poor's newspaper
publishing index, which in the first quarter languished while
Internet stocks soared, no longer moves in a different direction
than do the indexes of online stocks. The newspaper index has
climbed 31 percent since the beginning of the year, and last week,
when it gained 7.3 percent, it was moving roughly in tandem with
TheStreet.com's index of Internet stocks, which moved up 9.8
percent last week.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the new synchronicity between newspaper and Internet
stocks reflects the Internet advertising. ``These dot-coms take
this money, and they don't build factories, they build audiences,''
said Douglas Arthur, an analyst with Morgan Stanley. ``They have to
build them through mass media. So newspapers are re-emerging on a
secular basis as a very effective mass media in local markets.''
</P>
<P>
   USA Today, the Gannett Co.'s flagship, which now has the highest
circulation in the industry, ``is getting the highest share of
print dot-com spending,'' Lauren Rich Fine, an analyst for Merrill
Lynch, wrote. That newspaper's advertising revenue through November
was up 16 percent, compared with a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But other industries were spending on newspapers as well.
Financial advertising helped push advertising volume in Dow Jones'
Wall Street Journal up 30.5 percent in November, compared with the
1998 month.
</P>
<P>
   For the first 11 months of the year, the Journal's advertising
volume was up 15.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising revenue at The New York Times was up 20.7 percent in
November, compared with November 1998, and 10.6 percent for the
year to date. USA Today has brought in 16 percent more revenue in
1999 than it did for the comparable period in 1998. At The Los
Angeles Times, owned by the Times Mirror Co., ad revenue increased
an average 9 percent in October and November over the comparable
1998 period.
</P>
<P>
   And at Knight Ridder's San Jose Mercury News, one of the
industry's most disturbing trends _ the loss of high-margin
help-wanted classified ads, apparently to competing Internet sites
_ reversed itself in the second half of 1999. Help-wanted revenues
were up 25 percent in October and 21 percent in November, compared
with those months in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   So there is good news from a cyclical point of view. But for
those who use Internet math, which counts increasing revenues as a
plus (for obvious reasons) and increasing losses as a plus (because
they reflect a degree of commitment to new technologies and new
markets), the numbers were even better.
</P>
<P>
   Knight Ridder executives announced that it would consolidate its
Internet properties into a unit called KnightRidder.com, to be
managed separately from its newspapers and may compete with them
for advertising. Dow Jones executives indicated they expected
online businesses to generate $150 million in revenue this year.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett executives said they expected $40 million in Internet
revenues in 1999, and said that 15 of its sites, including
usatoday.com, the most-visited newspaper Web site, were running
profits for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Co.'s online unit, Times Company Digital, is expected
to post revenues of $29 million to $31 million in 1999 and to incur
operating losses of $20 million to $22 million. Next year,
executives said, revenue is expected to reach $49 million, and
losses $40 million to $60 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
