<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AILEY-BALLET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HIGH-ENERGY FEVER IS REVISITED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bill T. Jones sent dancers off on a new trip through
an old swamp last Friday night. The expedition proved worth
watching.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983 Jones choreographed a dance called ``Fever Swamp'' for
the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater. Last Friday the company
offered a work of that same name at City Center. But it wasn't
really the same dance, even though both productions were virtuosic,
high-energy pieces performed to a recording of a cheerfully
chugging composition by Peter Gordon called ``Intervallic
Expansion.''
</P>
<P>
   What made the old ``Fever Swamp'' odd as well as exciting was
that its energy had an edge of seemingly unmotivated melodramatic
tension that made it difficult to determine what Jones intended his
choreographic tone to be. There is no such aesthetic murkiness in
the new production. It's all feverish fun.
</P>
<P>
   In staging his revised version, Jones was aided by a creative
team that included Bjorn Amelan as producer and Janet Wong as
assistant. It began with a bang as dancers hopped and kicked their
way in, then ran and bounced about the stage. At one point they
vanished behind shimmering silver curtains designed by Bill Katz,
only to explode through them back into view again. Later those
curtains rose into the air, making the stage seem a vast expanse,
glowing with lighting designed by Robert Wierzel.
</P>
<P>
   One fascinating difference between the old and new productions
involved casting. The 1983 version was entirely for men. Although
the new one had five men (Matthew Rushing, Glenn A. Sims, Jeffrey
Gerodias, Clifton Brown and Richard Witter), there was also a
woman, Dwana Adiaha Smallwood. Yet Jones' choreography set up no
rigid distinctions between specifically male and female types of
movement. All the people in this swamp were equals, performing the
same steps with the same vitality and wearing similar loose-fitting
costumes by Liz Prince. As the dancers clapped and hopped happily
in circles in the work's final moments, one knew that Jones' second
thoughts about ``Fever Swamp'' were good ones.
</P>
<P>
   The evening was also notable for Renee Robinson's interpretation
of ``Cry,'' Alvin Ailey's tribute to the indomitability of black
women. There were times when the archetypal figure Ms. Robinson
portrayed in this solo was bent to the earth in sorrow. But Ms.
Robinson convincingly revealed that this woman was capable of
rising up with courage and determination.
</P>
<P>
   The program also included repeat performances of ``Lettres
d'Amour'' and ``Revelations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
