<HEADLINE>
XEROX IS CLAMPING DOWN ON COUNTERFEIT SUPPLIES 
NEW RATINGS SITE TAKES SPELLING ERROR IN STRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Pa.)  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Step aside, Magnum. Make way for Xerox, private investigator.
</P>
<P>
   Seems the problem of counterfeit supplies _ cartridges, toners,
all those deliciously high-margin items that users of printers and
copiers must replace again and again _ has escalated badly of late.
A big factor is the ease with which counterfeiters can sell their
wares on the Internet. And Xerox does not cotton to counterfeiters.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been devoting ``significant time and resources''
to ferreting out people who make illegal copies of its copier
products, said William Steenburgh, vice president for Xerox's
consumable supplies business. Acting on tips from outsiders as well
as on information developed by its own security specialists, Xerox
has been running makeshift sting operations throughout the country,
buying products it suspects to be counterfeit and testing them in
its labs.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, they turn out to be the genuine article, distributed
through the hated but legal gray market. But often, they turn out
to be phonies, at which point Xerox pulls in local police officials
and even federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, one such operation in Milwaukee turned up
47,000 cardboard boxes, complete with Xerox's packaging codes and
logos, that could have held $8 million worth of products. The
packages were seized, as were the box maker's equipment.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Xerox and police officials presided over the
prearranged surrender of Robert Leonard, president of Alberta
International, a wholesale computer supplier in Pittsburgh whose
records showed he had sold $30,000 of phony Xerox cartridges. Xerox
now has a sting operation on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   A lot is at stake. According to William Duffy, president of the
Imaging Supplies Coalition, an industry group formed to battle
counterfeiting, the supplies business has quintupled in the last
decade, to $25 billion worldwide. He figures the combination of
counterfeiting, fraudulent telemarketing and trademark infringement
is costing Xerox and other document processing companies nearly $1
billion a year. ``Two years ago it would have been half this,''
Duffy said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Claudia H. Deutsch
</P>
<P>
   NEW RATINGS SITE TAKES SPELLING ERROR IN STRIDE
</P>
<P>
   Judge not, lest ye be judged.
</P>
<P>
   A new shopping-comparison site called EWonders.com started up
last week. The site is meant to guide online shoppers by rating
e-tailing Web sites on various characteristics, like prices,
product selection and, of all things, spelling and grammar.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, the EWonders Web site misspelled ``grammar'' _
writing it ``grammer.'' EWonders fixed the mistake, after a
reporter pointed it out.
</P>
<P>
   Masood Faisal, an EWonders vice president, said the misspelling
occurred when the site transferred material from an affiliated
site, RatingWonders.com. ``It was spelled correctly on that site,''
he said, ``but somehow it was changed in the transmission.''
</P>
<P>
   Faisal took the incident in stride, noting that the the new site
had been developed in a mere 17 days. When EWonders scans the text
of other sites, he said, his company will use a spell checker.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
