<SLUG> BC-NORWEGIAN-CRUISE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORWEGIAN CRUISE LINE SAYS OUTLOOK IS GOOD
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Officials of the Norwegian Cruise Line, who have rejected a $1.7
billion takeover bid by the Carnival Corp., disclosed a rosy
financial outlook on Friday in what analysts said was an appeal to
shareholders tempted by the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating their contention that the bid was too low, the
officials called it ``totally opportunistic.'' They said, however,
that they were open to an alliance or even a higher offer, if not
from Carnival then from another suitor.
</P>
<P>
   And in response to a question during a teleconference from Oslo,
the corporate headquarters of NCL Holding ASA, Norwegian Cruise
Line's parent company, they said they had held talks with other
interested parties, including Star Cruises of Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   NCL declined to name the other suitors or to elaborate on talks
with Star.
</P>
<P>
   Since Carnival made its surprise offer last week, which NCL
management and major stockholders promptly rejected, NCL shares
have risen from 24.9 kroner, or $3.12, to 33.6 kroner, or $4.21.
</P>
<P>
   Its American depository receipts closed up 12.5 cents, to
$16.875 Friday on the New York Stock Exchange, Carnival shares were
unchanged, at $46.25, also on the Big Board.
</P>
<P>
   NCL executives, including Geir Aune, its chief executive, and
Kristian Semb, its chairman, said in the telephone conference that
NCL's financial position was strengthening.
</P>
<P>
   Pretax profit next year, the company said, is projected at $92
million, up from $40 million this year. That projection, they said,
is ``the reason Carnival is rushing ahead with this offer'' before
others know about it.
</P>
<P>
   The company also forecast an operating profit before
depreciation and charter operations of $236 million and a profit
before tax of $92 million. Its forecasts, it said, are based on
strong advance bookings for next year and higher revenue per
available passenger day _ $75 for the first quarter of 2000,
compared with $65 for the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   But a report six weeks ago by Lezard Freres &AMP; Co. projected
NCL's pretax income next year at $65.4 million and its net income
at $47.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Carnival, the No. 1 cruise line with a market share of 40
percent, said last week that it would not raise its offer for
Norwegian Cruise, the fourth-largest cruise company. Sunday, it
said it had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   But Joyce Minor, the cruise industry analyst with Lehman
Brothers, said, ``Investors need to know whether there's a real
alternative bid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is,'' she added, `` and it's on the table, Carnival
will have a chance to respond.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-99 1746EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991212.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6694 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SIDE-SHOW-ACTORS-NYT &LR;      12-12 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIDE-SHOW-ACTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SIDE SHOW' TWINS REUNITE IN `THE DEAD' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Emily Skinner and Alice Ripley can be excused for
sharing a bit of an identity crisis. It's not that they look alike,
sound alike or even dress alike. Ms. Ripley has honey blonde hair,
while Ms. Skinner's is closer to sunshine. And though both women
have blue eyes, you'd never think their genes had jumped from the
same pool.
</P>
<P>
   Still, almost every day someone, somewhere, calls one of them by
the other woman's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you never call me Emily,'' Ms. Ripley announces to a
reporter, ``you'll be my favorite person ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Such confusion is not inexplicable. After all, it was just two
years ago that Ms. Skinner and Ms. Ripley burst onto Broadway
literally connected at the hip.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion, of course, was ``Side Show,'' the ill-fated
musical about Daisy and Violet Hilton, conjoined twins and
Depression-era vaudevillians whose physical deformity failed to
hide their humanity or, apparently, their deep urge to belt out a
tune. The actresses earned a joint Tony nomination for playing
Daisy and Violet, side by side.
</P>
<P>
   It was, as they say, a bonding experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did we get to know one another?'' Ms. Skinner said with a
smile. ``When you have your backside plastered to another girl's
for eight hours a day, it's sort of natural.''
</P>
<P>
   Though ``Side Show'' lasted only seven weeks, the Broadway
community's mental connection between Ms. Skinner and Ms. Ripley
has endured. And that association is likely to intensify now that
the two find themselves on Broadway again in ``James Joyce's `The
Dead,''' the musical adaptation of the Joyce short story that
begins a limited engagement at the Belasco Theater on Tuesday
night..
</P>
<P>
   The end result of which is that the former twins are once again
sharing a dressing room, albeit with a little more room to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' said Ms. Skinner, pointing to Ms. Ripley's
left cheek. ``I've only ever seen that side of her face.''
</P>
<P>
   The roles the women play in ``The Dead'' are a far cry from
their ``Side Show'' personae. Ms. Ripley plays Miss Molly Ivors, a
spunky Irish lass whose flirtation raises the body temperature of
Gabriel Conroy, the play's central character, played by Christopher
Walken.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Skinner, meanwhile, is Mary Jane, a kindly niece whose
Christmas celebration sets the scene for the play. The two
characters never speak directly to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the two women see themselves, as actresses, falling
into distinctly different categories. Ms. Skinner said that Ms.
Ripley was a ``classic young leading lady'' with high, angular
cheekbones and a bright, brassy voice that recalls Barbara Cook or
Shirley Jones. (This description elicited a large ``Awwww'' from a
grateful Ms. Ripley.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Skinner, meanwhile, is the more rosy-cheeked of the two, the
possessor of a beaming smile and a voice that Ms. Ripley described
as ``like a warm reed instrument.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beautiful,'' Ms. Ripley said. ``I envy her.''
</P>
<P>
   The two have put their voices to work in two albums of duets and
solo versions of songs drawn from Broadway shows.
</P>
<P>
   The latest, ``Unsuspecting Hearts'' (Varese Sarabande), was
released in September and features 15 songs, including ``She's
Gone,'' which was cut from ``Side Show,'' and the album's title
song, which was drawn from the astoundingly unsuccessful musical
version of ``Carrie.''
</P>
<P>
   Their first album, ``Duets'' (Varese Sarabande), was released in
1998 and is the label's third-highest-selling Broadway album ever.
</P>
<P>
   Both recordings were presented in a way that seemed geared to
cash in on their Siamese past. The cover of ``Unsuspecting Hearts''
shows the two women wrapped in a seamless red blanket, their
shoulders nearly blended together. For ``Duets,'' their faces are
pressed cheek-to-cheek.
</P>
<P>
   Still, their appearance together in ``The Dead,'' which is
transferring from Playwrights Horizons, was almost accidental. Ms.
Ripley's part was one of the first cast, said the producer, Gregory
Mosher, while Ms. Skinner's was one of the last.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I realized the whole `Side Show' connection, I thought,
`Wow, what a brilliant idea,''' Mosher said. ``Then I thought, `Oh,
no, do they like one another?' I mean, sharing a body part could
breed the greatest of friends or someone you really, really don't
want to see a lot of.''
</P>
<P>
   The reminders of their shared past are constant. Casting agents
call for one, wanting the other. Schedule changes are called in to
Ms. Skinner and expected to be passed on to Ms. Ripley. Neither set
of parents has slipped yet, but it seems only a matter of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've warned my husband,'' Ms. Ripley said.
</P>
<P>
   The two actresses have become good friends, though they say a
deeper, more normal friendship blossomed only  &UR; after  &LR; the pressure
of ``Side Show'' had faded.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used to ask us, `So do you guys hang out together?'''
Ms. Skinner said. ``I mean, the last thing we want to do after
being stuck together is be like, `Hey, want to get our nails
done?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ripley continued, ``What's nice about `The Dead' is that it
lets us actually get to know one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Skinner added: ``That's lovely you felt that way, but I felt
I knew you before. I knew everything I should know, and everything
I shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The women do display an uncanny, almost sisterly talent for
finishing each other's sentences, and enough spunk to tease each
other into laughter. Asked how they became actresses, Ms. Skinner
and Ms. Ripley answered like this:
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Skinner: ``I've never really had any other life dream or
plan than to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ripley: ``Good thing it worked out for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Skinner: ``I know. Really.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ripley: ``You could've ended up working at the 7-Eleven.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Skinner: ``Easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Skinner, a native of Richmond, Va., who said she was born to
two ``very normal people,'' was a child actress who earned her
Equity card, a badge of professionalism, at the age of 12. She has
one sister, Eliza.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ripley, meanwhile, comes from a large family, 11 children in
all, and spent her childhood in several cities in Ohio. Her
professional training came at Kent State University. After working
as an actress in San Diego, she moved to Nashville to pursue a
singing career. Instead she found her husband, Shannon Ford, a jazz
and rock drummer.
</P>
<P>
   Both women arrived in New York in 1992 and quickly found work,
with Ms. Skinner landing in a workshop of ``Jekyll and Hyde'' and
Ms. Ripley taking an understudy role on Broadway in ``The Who's
`Tommy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Their collective break came in 1996, when ``Side Show,'' which
was then called the ``The Song of the Siamese Twins,'' was in
workshops. Ms. Skinner had played Daisy in several early readings,
but her Violets kept wilting away. Finally the creative team
brought in Ms. Ripley for an audition. The effect of their voices
together _ ``the blend,'' as Robert Longbottom, the director, put
it _ was immediate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really finished each other,'' Longbottom said.
``Everybody in the room just knew: there it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite good reviews and the Tony nomination, ``Side Show''
proved to have less presence than Ms. Skinner and Ms. Ripley. Since
then Ms. Ripley has done a stint as Fantine in ``Les Miserables,''
while Ms. Skinner has had roles in regional theater productions of
``Jesus Christ Superstar'' and ``Working.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the name switch and identity blend may get a little
tiresome, Ms. Ripley and Ms. Skinner say, in their own way, that
they enjoy each other's company.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ripley: ``I'm sort of like, I'm to the point, it's
like....'' Ms. Skinner: ``There could be worse people to be linked
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ripley: ``Exactly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
