<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6697 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-McMURTRY-BOOK-REVIEW-     12-12 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-McMURTRY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WALTER BENJAMIN AT THE DAIRY QUEEN': A SEMINAL MOMENT AT A TEXAS
DRIVE-IN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(lb) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writing is not often a profession passed down from generation to
generation, especially not in immigrant, raw-boned America, where
it took a long time for the cultural accretions to build to the
point where literature was a major activity. Perhaps for that
reason explanations of how writers became writers often involve
stories of long distances traveled from origin to fate.
</P>
<P>
   But even in a land of long distances, not many have traveled
quite as far as Larry McMurtry, the prolific author of two dozen
novels and books of essays, including ``The Last Picture Show,''
``Lonesome Dove'' and ``Terms of Endearment.''
</P>
<P>
   McMurtry's new memoir, ``Walter Benjamin at the Dairy Queen,''
makes much of distances _ psychological as well as geographical _
as he explains how he abandoned the cowboy life in Texas, where he
grew up, and became, as he puts it, a herder of words.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Benjamin, the German-Jewish literary critic and essayist
whose origins were as different from McMurtry's as they could
possibly be, plays the role of cultural foil here. He never went to
the Dairy Queen in Archer City, Texas, where McMurtry first read
him in 1980. But McMurtry's meeting with Benjamin's mind in the
Texas flatlands is emblematic of the mysteriousness of personal
outcomes, and in that way Benjamin serves as an evocative point of
departure for McMurtry's examination of his own literary itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   This is an engaging idea, and McMurtry is an engaging writer.
Still, his memoir is not easy to get a bead on. It meanders; it
picks up themes and then picks up other themes, but it often
doesn't get to a point.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin, as McMurtry well knows, was fascinated by the flaneur,
the person who browsed through the Parisian shopping arcades that
for Benjamin epitomized urban commercialism. McMurtry is a sort of
flaneur through the arcades of his own life and career.
</P>
<P>
   This has its charms, and occasionally, as with McMurtry's riffs
on the very brief, mostly mythic history of cowboys in American
life, it is more than charming; it is illuminating. But McMurtry's
memoir never sheds its quality of drift, and it leaves the reader
longing for a stronger theme, greater narrative punch.
</P>
<P>
   McMurtry begins with his first reading of Benjamin at the Dairy
Queen while groups of working-class locals ``formed and reformed,
like drifting clouds.'' The particular essay that caught McMurtry's
eye was ``The Storyteller,'' in which Benjamin offers his
explanation for what McMurtry calls the ``diminution of the power
of oral narrative in our 20th-century lives.''
</P>
<P>
   McMurtry quotes several passages from Benjamin (passages whose
meaning is elusive) and goes on to react to those passages. He
wonders, for example, what Benjamin, who came from the culturally
dense environs of Europe, would make of the ``unpeopled horizons,''
the vast emptiness of Texas where McMurtry's grandparents came as
pioneers in the late 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``My question to Walter Benjamin would be, what kind of stories
arise in a place where nothing has ever happened except, of course,
the vagaries and vicissitudes of individual life?'' McMurtry
writes. He goes on to weave some recollections of the spare
tragedies that the loneliness of Texas produced and that McMurtry
remembers from childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Then he returns to Benjamin: ``The birthplace of the novel is
the solitary individual, who is no longer able to express himself
by giving examples of his more important concerns, is himself
uncounseled, and cannot counsel others.'' From there McMurtry asks,
``Does mere human memory, the soil that nourishes storytelling,
still have any use at all?''
</P>
<P>
   All of this relates to McMurtry's larger question, namely how
someone like him, growing up in a place where ``nothing of
historical or cultural consequence had ever happened,'' became a
novelist. It is a good question, and McMurtry goes on to recount
the stages in his career. But this to-ing and fro-ing from obscure
shards of literary theory to the barrenness of Texas has a whiff of
genial pretentiousness about it.
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be some deeper point here than the mere fact that
being from Berlin and being from Archer City, Texas, are different,
but what that profounder point is exactly remains buried in
McMurtry's epigrammatic browsings.
</P>
<P>
   He tells some savory tales as his memoir proceeds, and these
provide the best passages in this slender book. His memories of his
grandparents, of his parents and of his boyhood life as an
unenthusiastic and lackluster cowboy have a flavorful and resonant
quality, as do his reflections on the persistence of what he sees
as a Western myth.
</P>
<P>
   ``What rodeos, movies, Western art and pulp fiction all miss,''
he writes, ``is the overwhelming loneliness of the westering
experience.'' He continues: ``Somehow the outlaw came to stand for
this solitary Westerner _ the man who has no ties because he kills.
More common was the man who had no ties because he would rather
work and keep working.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Walter Benjamin at the Dairy Queen'' has in general more
drift than purpose. McMurtry intersperses his charming biographical
reflections with more mediocre philosophizing: on his view, for
example, that ``real curiosity now gets little chance to develop _
it's smothered with information before it can draw a natural
breath.''
</P>
<P>
   He warns us in a meandering chapter on his career as a used-book
dealer that the subject might be interesting only to readers who
share McMurtry's antiquarian fascination, and this essay indicates
that the warning is justified.
</P>
<P>
   McMurtry ends with a chapter titled ``The End of the Cowboy _
The End of Fiction,'' in which he reflects variously on Benjamin
again, on the dizzying rapidity of change in the West and,
elegiacally, on growing old as a writer in American today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is all sparks, yet the sparks rarely produce a steady
flame,'' he writes about Benjamin. It is a perceptive dollop of
literary criticism, but it is one that applies to McMurtry's
memoir, which has its aphoristic and conversational moments but
remains too casually fragmentary to produce the needed unwavering
beam of light.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WALTER BENJAMIN AT THE DAIRY QUEEN'
</P>
<P>
   By Larry McMurtry
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 204 pages. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-99 1802EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
