u e BC-PERLE-TRIBUTE-NYT &LR;      12-12 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERLE-TRIBUTE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 THE WORKS OF COMPOSER GEORGE PERLE COME OF AGE  (jw) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Too few composers live to enjoy the kind of respect
and acclaim that fell to George Perle last week at Merkin Concert
Hall in Manhattan. Perle turns 85 next year, and this was an early
tribute. Seven fine pianists, ranging in age from 21-year-old
Steven Beck to Beck's teacher, Seymour Lipkin, 72, played eight of
Perle's formidable works for solo piano.
</P>
<P>
   True, many of Perle's colleagues and other musical people were
in the audience last Monday night. But the enthusiastic response
seemed a genuine expression of excitement about the music, not an
obligatory gesture. Larger public acclaim for Perle's music, at
once challenging and appealing, is starting to happen. Perhaps his
time has arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Perle was one of the first American composers to become
enthralled with the music of the Second Viennese School:
Schoenberg, Webern and Berg. But he has never been a strict 12-tone
composer. He uses the 12 tones in a way similar to the Serialists,
often devising rows and pitch patterns. The notes zigzag in his
pieces and discombobulate the ear, just as in 12-tone works.
</P>
<P>
   But his language is grounded in his own equivalent of tonality,
with harmonic touch points, recurring uses of thematic intervals
and repetition of rhythmic patterns, which combine to give the
listener something to hold on to. Perle has never believed that
complexity must be synonymous with obscurity. There is a wonderful
lucidity about his music, even at its most complex. And unlike the
Viennese forefathers, he is no angst-ridden heavy. Rather he is an
optimistic urban American and his music abounds in snappy rhythmic
energy and wit.
</P>
<P>
   In Six Celebratory Inventions (1995), played brilliantly by
Russell Sherman, Perle revealed his ability to evoke character. For
example ``Gunther Schuller at 70'' is pensive and rigorous;
``Leonard Bernstein at 70'' is full of streets-of-New York
exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   Every piece played was rewarding. Esther Budiardjo gave a
compelling performance of the Ballade (1981), a rhapsodic work in
homage to the 19th-century Romantic piano music. Beck gave an
invigorating account of the spirited Toccata (1976). Lipkin was
impressive in the Short Sonata (1964), which, though not long, is
packed with materials. Eliza Garth gave a sensitive, supple reading
of the imaginative Suite in C (1970). Michael Boriskin played
dazzling renditions of the Six Etudes (1976) and the Six New Etudes
(1984).
</P>
<P>
   Leon Fleisher gave the first performance of ``Musical
Offerings'' (1998), for left hand alone, musical portraits of three
friends of the composer-pianist from their days at the Tanglewood
Music Center: Richard Ortner and Dan Gustin, who were
administrators there, and the pianist Gilbert Kalish, who was
chairman of the faculty. The piece now seems an homage to three
people who were casualties of Seiji Ozawa's controversial shake-up
of that summer training institute two years ago, when Fleisher was
its artistic director. Fleisher and Kalish resigned in protest
after Ozawa's changes.
</P>
<P>
   Those thoughts were banished, though, by Fleisher's elegant
performance of Perle's riveting short works, delivered with a
palpable sense of purpose. The occasion warranted it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
