<SLUG> BC-POP.COM-CHAIRMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTERTAINMENT INTERNET VENTURE GETS A CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD, Dec. 12 _ Kenneth P. Wong, former president of Walt
Disney Imagineering, Disney's technology research and development
unit, has been named chairman and chief executive of Pop.com, the
recently announced collaboration between Dreamworks SKG and Imagine
Entertainment to create and distribute entertainment on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Pop.com, which is expected to begin in the spring, will offer
three- to-six minute segments that it calls ``pops,'' a combination
of digital films, animation, live events and interactive games.
Because it was formed by prominent Hollywood artists and executives
_ Steven Spielberg, Jeffrey Katzenberg and David Geffen of
Dreamworks and Ron Howard and Brian Grazer of Imagine _ and because
it is being largely financed by Paul G. Allen's Vulcan Ventures,
Pop.com fast became one of the most visible attempts in Hollywood
to come to terms with entertainment in the digital age.
</P>
<P>
   Wong recently left Disney after an eight-year career that saw
him rise from senior vice president at the Disney Development Co.
to executive vice president of the Imagineering division in 1995
and its president in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   As head of the division, he oversaw such projects as Disney's
recently opened Animal Kingdom in Florida, its Times Square
Studios, Tokyo DisneySea, Disney's California Adventure and two
Disney cruise ships.
</P>
<P>
   Wong was ``the architect of unprecedented growth at
Imagineering,'' Katzenberg said, ``and we are excited to work with
him to build Pop.com into a successful enterprise in the exploding
Internet marketplace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
