<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-NORTHAMERICA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM TO KEEP PLANTS RUNNING AT FULL SPEED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Despite slowing sales and bulging inventories of
unsold automobiles, General Motors Corp. announced Friday that it
planned to continue running its North American factories at close
to full speed through the first quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
   GM said that it planned to build 1,501,000 cars, sport utility
vehicles, pickup trucks and vans during January, February and March
next year, compared with 1,506,000 during the first three months of
this year. Paul Ballew, GM's market analysis director, insisted
that the company could sell all the vehicles it planned to make
without resorting to the deep discounts that automakers have
traditionally used to clear out dealerships clogged with unwanted
models.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no need for us to open the floodgates on incentives,''
Ballew said. While the total number of vehicles is little changed,
GM plans to produce slightly more full-size pickups and sport
utilities, which have sold briskly for most of the last several
years, and slightly fewer cars, he added.
</P>
<P>
   But the industry's sales of full-size pickups and sport
utilities fell in November, possibly because of higher gasoline
prices, which make these vehicles more expensive to operate. Auto
analysts were skeptical that GM could sell so many vehicles in the
first quarter without cutting prices or increasing rebates and
cut-rate loans. Other manufacturers would be likely to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ward's Automotive Reports, a weekly industry
newsletter, the number of automobiles in GM's inventories rose 5.8
percent last month, and was up 25.6 percent from late November last
year. DaimlerChrysler's inventory climbed only 8.2 percent over the
last 12 months while Ford's inventory was up only 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Robinet, an auto production forecaster, said that GM's
output plans, while ambitious, could have been even more ambitious.
GM's capacity is slightly higher now than it was earlier this year
because fewer assembly plants are operating at partial capacity as
workers learn to build new models.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
