<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6702 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ASIA-POLL-cox     12-12 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-POLL-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    YO, ASIA! WHERE ARE YOU?
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ How many Americans do you think would know which
body of water separates the United States from Asia?
</P>
<P>
   In a survey released Sunday by the Asia Society, 810 adults and
1,012 college-bound high school students were offered four answers:
Atlantic Ocean, China Sea, Pacific Ocean and Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that 68 percent of the adults and 74 percent of
the students correctly named the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   But 32 percent of adults and 26 percent of the students got it
wrong
</P>
<P>
   On the other 15 questions on a quiz to test their knowledge of
Asia both adults and students fared even worse. Most of the adults
missed half of the questions and most of the students were wrong on
nearly two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public lacks in-depth knowledge about Asia,'' concluded
the Asia Society, a nonprofit American organization based in New
York. It had hired Penn, Schoen &AMP; Berland Associates, which polls
for the White House, to administer the multiple-choice exams over
the phone in August and September. The poll's sampling margin of
error was 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A dinner Sunday was the first gathering of members of a new
commission formed by the society to design and supervise a $5
million campaign to increase Americans' knowledge of Asia through
``improvements in standards, lessons, teacher knowledge and
textbooks.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission of more than 30 educational, philanthropic,
corporate and state leaders is led by three co-chairs: Gov. Jim
Hunt of North Carolina, high school teacher Charlotte Mason of
Newton, Mass., and former Berkeley chancellor Chang-Lin Tien.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our kids know more than enough about Nintendo, the world's
largest selling video game, and far too little about India, the
world's largest democracy,'' said Hunt in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the test-takers thought the United States was the
largest democracy, although India has more than twice times as many
people.
</P>
<P>
   Those taking the multiple-choice phone test scored highest when
they were asked which of four countries _ India, Great Britain,
Philippines, United States _ ``has never elected a woman as head of
the government.'' But 79 percent of adults and 77 percent of
students who correctly chose the United States simply may have been
showing knowledge about their own country's presidents, rather than
Asian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Six out of every 10 in both groups knew that the ying-yang
symbol (that circle with an S-shaped curve separating the black and
white halves) symbolizes ``harmony of opposites.''
</P>
<P>
   The same number knew that it was was Gandhi, rather than Nehru,
Confucius or Pol Pot, who had strongly influenced civil rights
leader Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The Asia Society said the test groups did worst when asked which
of four countries _ China, United States, India, France _ ``has the
largest film industry in the world.'' Perhaps reflecting a U.S.
cultural emphasis upon exports and box-office grosses, only 8
percent of adults and 4 percent of students chose India, which in
most years produces more feature-length movies in more languages
than any other country.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the pollsters didn't even expect their own
phone-callers to know much about Asia. The script for the
questioners included this question: ``What is the capital of
Indonesia? Oo-lan bah-tore, Bang-cock, Ja-carta, Ma-nill-a?'' Sure
enough, even with those helpful pronunciations of Ulan Bator,
Bangkok, Jakarta and Manila, only 33 percent of adults and 22
percent of students picked Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   Just before taking the test, the respondents showed that
mediocre scores wouldn't surprise them: 45 percent of the adults
and 32 percent of the students admitted to being ``not very'' or
``not at all'' knowledgeable about Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Nor would the mediocre scores surprise the respondents, who
consisted of a sample that is probably within five percentage
points of correctly reflecting all adults and college-bound
students in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Would Asians do better than Americans on a test about Asia?
Probably. Yet three years ago, the newspaper Asahi Shimbun asked
2,307 Japanese what they mean by ``Asia.'' It turned out that 56
percent felt that India, Pakistan, Iran, Turkey and Saudi Arabia
are outside Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, computers wouldn't have aced the test either.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet site which offers to answer factual questions
(www.askjeeves.com) was asked the toughest of the 16 questions:
``Which of the following best characterized the Tokugawa period of
Japanese history? Fortified castle towns, many wars with China,
large navy, extensive network of foreign relations.''
</P>
<P>
   The first answer from AskJeeves was: ``I'm not sure I understood
your question correctly. Would you like me to check your
spelling?''
</P>
<P>
   The second answer provided a link to a site about Central Asia,
which is on the other side of China from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is AndyM(at)Coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
