<DOCNO> NYT19991212.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6704 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AIRLINE-POLICIES13-CO     12-12 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-POLICIES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Airlines ready to launch improved service policies
 &HT;    By Gary Hendricks
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the holiday season approaches, the nation's major
airlines are promising to treat you with a little more kindness.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from Congress, which had threatened legislative
action, the air carriers came up with their own customer service
policies and asked lawmakers to give them a chance to win back the
affection of the public. The new policies will begin Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines promise to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Inform passengers of the lowest fare available on every
flight.
</P>
<P>
   _ Give early notification of delays and cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Respond to complaints within 60 days (Atlanta's dominant
carrier, Delta Air Lines, is promising action within 30 days).
</P>
<P>
   _ Increase the lost baggage liability limit from $1,250 to
$2,500.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines' version of the much-discussed airline passenger
``bill of rights'' will not abridge their freedom to put as many
people as they can onto the same airplane nor guarantee a traveler
the right to a speedy arrival time. In other words, don't expect
airliners to be any less crowded or timely.
</P>
<P>
   But, airline officials say, the policies will better inform
Hartsfield International Airport passengers about flight delays and
why they are happening.
</P>
<P>
   Delta will allow passengers to shop for better fares until
midnight the next day from the time they book their flights. That
exceeds the industry standard of 24 hours, said Vicki Escarra,
Delta executive vice president of customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocate and Atlanta Journal-Constitution columnist
Clark Howard cited fare shopping and the increased lost baggage
limit to $2,500 as the true benefits of the customer initiatives.
``Most of (the rest of it) is corporate PR,'' Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   Experienced passengers are skeptical of the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they are going to act until they are forced to
act,'' said Mike Bilton of Smyrna, a frequent flier. Delays,
overbooking and lost baggage will continue to be the norm, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bunch of lip service,'' Bilton added.
</P>
<P>
   Horror stories _ passengers trapped for hours without food,
drink or restroom access on airplanes grounded by snowstorms _
recounted at congressional hearings early this year set off a
threat of a federally imposed passenger bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines, through the Air Trade Association, asked Congress
and Clinton administration regulators to not force-feed them a new
set of regulations. The airlines won a reprieve this summer on the
condition they regulate themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Customer service complaints are especially severe at major hub
airports like Hartsfield, which last year became the top passenger
airport with 73.5 million travelers. In a national poll this year,
54 percent of Americans said late flights were a big problem.
Fifty-one percent were irked by long lines at airports. The
Time/CNN poll of 1,021 adults was conducted Nov. 10-11, with a
sampling effort of 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Each airline has adopted specific guidelines on improved
customer service, and officials say travelers should contact their
airline or check out their Web sites for details. Delta, which
along with subsidiary Atlantic Southeast Airlines, accounts for
some 80 percent of passenger volume at Hartsfield, has published a
12-point initiative the airline says exceeds industry standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing you will see,'' said Delta's Escarra, ``is
that we will notify you as soon as we can'' at home or office when
flights are canceled.
</P>
<P>
   The airline also is promising to keep passengers at the gate or
on planes informed about the causes of delays and to update that
information every 15 minutes, Escarra said.
</P>
<P>
   Escarra said, however, the customer service initiatives are
``nothing sexy'' and won't be fully implemented without the
nation's air traffic control system cooperating by supplying the
airlines with the information required to keep passengers informed.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government now invests $2.2 billion annually in
technological upgrades for air traffic control, said Dennis
Koehler, FAA Southeastern regional division manager for air
traffic. The FAA is bringing new systems on line as quickly as
safety permits and will be able to meet the demands of the airlines
and the public, Koehler added.
</P>
<P>
   But ``it isn't a big bang,'' Koehler said. ``We will make
changes methodically and incrementally.''
</P>
<P>
   Improvements can't come fast enough for some, however. Late last
week, Betty Brown of Albemarle, N.C., on a shopping trip to New
York with her husband, were blindsided making connections in
Atlanta, although their reservations were made six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns' flight from Charlotte, N.C., was late, and stand-bys
were given their seats, she said looking at what was supposed to be
her plane as it backed from the gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to get there,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
