<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley vows not to settle for status quo
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Vice President Al Gore is a candidate with small
ideas, lacking the vision that would ``move humanity a few feet
forward,'' Bill Bradley said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people who say we cannot do big things anymore,
that we can tinker around the edges and do a few little things here
and there,'' Bradley told some 2,000 delegates at the Florida
Democratic Party State Convention. ``Democratic leaders do not
settle.''
</P>
<P>
   Using Social Security, Medicare and civil rights as examples,
Bradley said, ``We've been the party of big ideas and big
achievement.'' Then in an apparent reference to Gore, Bradley said,
``I find it so dismaying that one Democrat can attack another on
these issues that are an article of faith in our party. If we are
united in anything we have to be united on these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has begun to sharpen the contrast between him and Gore
as the presidential candidates enter the final six weeks of
campaigning before the Iowa caucuses and New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   In a 45-minute speech, the former New Jersey senator attempted
to portray himself as the candidate with the understanding,
compassion and vision who would use the presidency to reach ``the
untapped potential'' in neighborhoods to bring about change in
society.
</P>
<P>
   It was his first campaign appearance since checking himself into
a California hospital Friday because of an irregular heartbeat.
Bradley made no mention of his health.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley sought to make an impression after President Clinton
wowed the delegates and gave a ringing endorsement to Gore on
Saturday just hours before the vice president himself appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and Gore are in a tight race in Iowa and New Hampshire
and several other early primary states. Bradley, who noted that he
started his campaign a year ago Saturday, has gone from long shot
to surprise contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is just an incredible guy,'' said Mike Abrams, a Miami
attorney and former state legislator who worked for Sen. Ted
Kennedy's 1980 presidential campaign. ``He is intelligent and
thoughtful and really cares about people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's star quality was evident at the convention. The former
New York Knicks basketball forward drew enthusiastic crowds
wherever he went, posing for pictures and signing autographs on
basketballs.
</P>
<P>
   Before his speech, the campaign showed a 12-minute biographical
video. Bradley was introduced by Duval County Sheriff Nat Glover,
the state's first black sheriff, who accused Republicans of trying
to use the strong economy to ``spiff up the first class
accommodations on the prosperity train instead of adding more
passengers.''
</P>
<P>
   With his reading glasses perched on his nose, Bradley continued
that theme saying, ``We cannot rest in this country and say we have
a good economy unless more and more people are reaching higher
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying he wants to ``be the protector of the natural
environment,'' Bradley said he frequently visits Florida and, ``the
Florida that I know is a Florida of beautiful Everglades, a
coastline that is incredible'' and a place that must be preserved.
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to sell himself as a candidate of high ideals,
Bradley said, ``if neither morality nor world leadership convince
you of my ideas, then try self-interest.'' He then explained that
with expected population trends in the next decade, ``the economic
future of children of white Americans will depend more on the
economic future of nonwhite Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming back to what has become a new theme for the campaign,
Bradley did a medley of ``I'm not prepared to settle,'' statements:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not prepared to settle for anything less than making
access to health care available to all Americans. I'm not prepared
to settle for anything short of registering and licensing all
handguns in this country.'' he said. ``I'm not prepared to settle
for anything less than bringing all children out of poverty. I'm
not prepared to settle for anything less than getting money out of
politics with public financing of campaigns. I'm not prepared for a
retreat on affirmative action. I'm not prepared to settle for
anything less than the best public schools in the world with public
money for public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore supporter Janet Stroth said she was impressed by Bradley's
performance but doubted if he could win the presidential
nomination. ``I think he has some good ideas but I don't think he's
really saying anything that different from Al Gore. I think Gore is
a better candidate and will have a better chance of defeating the
Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, Bradley attended a luncheon where he expected
to raise about $100,000. The campaign also plans to have a
fund-raising event in West Palm Beach later this month.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
