<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EQUITY-BOX13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Favorship facts
 &HT;    By David A. Milliron
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   FAVORING FOOTBALL
</P>
<P>
   The GHSA has established many rules and regulations that appear
to favor football over other sports. Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   _ Football officials are paid $63 per game, more than all other
sports. The rates in some other sports are $45-$55 for soccer, $42
for baseball, $40 for basketball.
</P>
<P>
   _ All GHSA activities must be completed by 11:30 p.m., except
varsity football games between schools in the same classification.
</P>
<P>
   _ Only football coaches are allowed input into the assignment of
game officials during the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Only football is allowed out-of-season practice.
</P>
<P>
   The association also places limitations on other sports. For
example:
</P>
<P>
   _ Volleyball coaches are forbidden to have spring skill-building
clinics in their feeder middle schools.
</P>
<P>
   _ Players on basketball teams that lose in the state semifinals
may not attend the championship game for free. Retired athletic
administrators receive lifetime passes entitling them entry.
</P>
<P>
   _ Basketball teams are forbidden to have a two-team scrimmage
the weekend before the season starts.
</P>
<P>
   TROPHY TROUBLE
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Track Club executive director Julia Emmons was stunned
upon learning that all six individual awards given at the girls
state track meet are named for men. ``Oh, you're kidding,'' Emmons
said. ``Nobody brought that to our attention.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true. Not a Gwen Torrence or a Wyomia Tyus in the bunch.
</P>
<P>
   The boys state meet in Jefferson has 20 individual trophies, all
named after former male athletes or coaches pre-dating school
integration, such as the Spec Towns Trophy in the 110 hurdles. They
are profiled in a 60-page glossy program sold at the boys meet,
while the only print materials available at the girls meet in
Albany are daily heat sheets.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Track Club pays for medals to the third- through
eighth-place finishers in both state meets. The GHSA provides
medals to the winners and runners-up.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT MUST BE EQUAL?
</P>
<P>
   Title IX requires that male and female athletes receive the same
benefits of athletic participation, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Equipment, uniforms, supplies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Access to weight room and training room.
</P>
<P>
   _ Practice facilities.
</P>
<P>
   _ Size and quality locker rooms and competition facilities.
</P>
<P>
   _ Access to practice and games during prime time.
</P>
<P>
   _ Quality coaches.
</P>
<P>
   _ Opportunity to play quality opponents.
</P>
<P>
   _ Awards and banquets.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cheerleaders and band performances.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about Title IX and how you can make sure
your school is following federal law, call the Women's Sports
Foundation (800-227-3988) and ask about the publication, Playing
Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Women's Sports
</P>
<P>
   Foundation
</P>
<P>
   YOU MAKE THE CALL
</P>
<P>
   Two rival schools are playing a big Friday night football game.
Can the host school sell standing room-only admission?
</P>
<P>
   No. The GHSA requires schools to provide a seat for every ticket
sold _ and an available seat is defined as 18 inches in width.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
