<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS ELECTIONS NEAR, RUSSIAN POLITICIANS EXPLOIT A POPULAR WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAVKAZ CHECKPOINT, Russia _ The refugees were nowhere to be
found. But that did not fluster Sergei Shoigu, Russia's minister
for emergency situations and the leader of a Kremlin-backed party
in next weekend's parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   Zipped up in a natty red jacket, Shoigu led a caravan of
journalists from this checkpoint on the Chechnya-Ingushetia border
to a small town near the outskirts of Grozny, the Chechen capital.
</P>
<P>
   The ostensible purpose was to inaugurate a new humanitarian
corridor for the thousands of civilians trapped in the city, which
Russian forces have pounded for weeks. But after an unsuccessful
search for fleeing refugees, Shoigu indulged in a news conference
in which he pledged his undying efforts to help save civilian
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ready for contact with anyone who can help,'' he said.
That part of the trip was a success: The visit was prominently
featured in the evening news.
</P>
<P>
   With public support for the war running high, Russian
politicians have been making pilgrimages to the war zone to
demonstrate their concern for the Russian troops and bask in the
Russian television coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Chernomyrdin, the leader of the party called Our Home Is
Russia, and a former prime minister, swung through Chechnya on
Friday on a fact-finding mission.
</P>
<P>
   And Anatoly Chubais appeared in Gudermes, Chechnya's
second-largest city, three weeks ago, swathed in a full-length
black leather coat, to announce that the electricity would soon be
turned back on for the long-suffering population.
</P>
<P>
   Chubais, a former Kremlin aide who runs the nation's electrical
monopoly, is backing Right Cause, the pro-free-market party, which
is struggling to secure a toehold in the parliament. He is still
unpopular with many Russians because of his role in ushering in the
nation's untamed version of capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   The electricity was restored, but has since been plagued by
regular outages, Gudermes residents say. Still, the trip may have
helped rehabilitate Chubais' image at home. ``Russians hate Chubais
slightly less thanks to Chechnya,'' the newspaper Izvestia
observed.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Vladimir Putin, the intelligence officer turned prime
minister, who has reaped the greatest political advantage from the
war in Chechnya. His poll ratings have soared not only because he
has ordered a military campaign against the Islamic militants, but
also because he has stood up to the Western governments that have
criticized it.
</P>
<P>
   Putin visited the Russian-controlled areas of Chechnya in
October and also donned a flight suit at a nearby Russian military
base for a ride in an Su-25 plane, one of the principal aircraft
used by the Russian air force to blast targets in the breakaway
republic.
</P>
<P>
   It is not easy for Shoigu to match that military bravado. But he
is no slouch when it comes to generating publicity.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The new spokesman for his party is Mikhail Margelov, a former
advertising executive and the director of the Russian government
center set up to organize news coverage of the war. With
parliamentary elections scheduled for Dec.19, Margelov took a brief
leave of absence from his government post to work full time for
Shoigu.
</P>
<P>
   Shoigu's party, Unity, was set up with Kremlin support just a
few months ago to siphon away support from Yevgeni Primakov, the
former prime minister, and Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov. The other
leading figures on the Unity ticket are Alexander Karelin, an
immensely popular former wrestler, and Alexander Gurov, a
mafia-fighting former Interior Ministry official.
</P>
<P>
   Their television campaign ad shows news clips of each in action
and with no commentary. The political message seems to be that they
are men of action who can save Russia. And here at Kavkaz
Checkpoint life imitated art, or at least advertising.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Shoigu's mission was to open a new humanitarian corridor leading
from the embattled city of Grozny to Alkhan-Yurt, southwest of the
capital. The desperate refugees who made it through the escape
route would be placed on trucks and buses and taken away to safety.
</P>
<P>
   The operation began at this checkpoint, one of the main routes
to Ingushetia for Chechens who have fled the fighting in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling in a four-wheel drive vehicle and wearing a bright
blue cap emblazoned in English with the appellation ``Emercom,''
for emergency committee, Shoigu led a procession of seven gleaming
white trucks, five buses, an armored personnel carrier and
associated cars and vans.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything, however, went according to the script. As the
caravan raced along the main Caucasian highway toward Grozny, it
passed a small town that had been flattened by Russian firepower.
The photographers who had been brought along to document Shoigu's
intrepid journey into Chechnya snapped photos of the destruction.
Russian military spokesmen later sought to persuade the press that
the village had been occupied by rebels and devoid of civilians
when it was clobbered.
</P>
<P>
   The Shoigu procession throttled along the highway until it
reached a tree that lay across the road, the apparent dividing line
between Russian- controlled and rebel-controlled territory and the
site of a new checkpoint that the minister was commissioning.
</P>
<P>
   But there were no refugees. Apparently, the people in Grozny had
not been informed of Shoigu's press event.
</P>
<P>
   So Shoigu took out a satellite telephone and tried to call the
Chechen rebels in Grozny to hammer out an agreement that would
facilitate the evacuation of the civilian population. He never
reached the rebels there, so he tried to call Aslan Maskhadov, the
president of the breakaway Chechen republic, who apparently is not
residing in the capital; again he had no success.
</P>
<P>
   Grozny's mayor later denounced Shoigu's trip as an election-year
publicity stunt. But Shoigu insists that his concern for Grozny's
civilians transcends politics.
</P>
<P>
   After failing to find the refugees, he gave a news conference in
which he affirmed that he was ready to negotiate with the devil
himself if it would help the civilians get out of Grozny. He gave
out two telephone numbers that the rebels could call.
</P>
<P>
   Then he headed back to Ingushetia. The seven trucks that were to
haul away the refugees also returned _ empty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
