<HEADER>
A6739 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-LAGOS-URBAN-MIGRANTS-     12-12 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAGOS-URBAN-MIGRANTS-925(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LAGOS, THE MURKY LAGOON IS THE LIFE FOR MANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria _ ``If I lived over there,'' said Jeremiah Faton,
gesturing vaguely toward the skyscrapers across the lagoon here in
West Africa's largest city, ``where would I put my boat?''
</P>
<P>
   Faton, 65, is a fisherman in Lagos. He lives on one of the
countless islands in Lagos lagoon, trolling its murky waters with
his dugout canoe during the fishing season, ferrying passengers to
the mainland during the low season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where would I fish?'' he continued cheerfully to a visitor who
had sought shelter from a cloudburst inside his shack, and had
asked him whether he had ever considered moving to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   The rain rattled the zinc roof over Faton's two rooms erected on
stilts, held together with clapboard and driftwood. Three small
girls giggled in the darkness of the main room, one of them
carrying on her back a boy with glassy eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Cracks on the floor showed goats snuffling below the shack,
lured by the refuse the low tide had left behind. A big pig stood
on a mound of garbage just outside the door, triumphantly somehow,
as it scratched its belly with a hind leg.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of people like Faton live in the shadows of
Lagos, squatting on bridgeless islands or, sometimes, on the lagoon
itself inside huts built on stilts. If the ever widening ripples
from Lagos and other cities are changing the rhythm of traditional
rural life in Africa, Faton and the other inhabitants of the lagoon
must surely rank among the most singular of urban migrants.
</P>
<P>
   Nomadic fishermen, they have replicated their traditional way of
life in the unlikeliest of places, Lagos, the megalopolis whose
official population of 8 million is considered a gross
underestimate _ Lagos, the loud, harried, urban giant who heaves to
life every morning, always with the risk of collapsing under its
own weight by noon.
</P>
<P>
   Like many African cities, Lagos often seems less like a city
than a collection of villages inhabited by different ethnic groups,
each clinging to its particular way of life amid the most
inhospitable of conditions.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner of the lagoon, three fishing shantytowns rise
above the stinking black water. A maze of raised flimsy planks,
linking hundreds of shacks perched on stilts, rests on a cesspool.
Children swim, bathe and play in the stagnant water. In the huts,
women smoke fish inside large clay pots, as the burning smell wafts
through one town called Makoko.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our custom,'' said one man, Abraham Messou. ``We build on
water since we are fishermen.''
</P>
<P>
   At dusk, as the sun set on the lagoon and cast an eerie orange
glow on Makoko, the town sank under the thickening haze from the
smoked fish. Canoes returning for the day passed under the Third
Mainland bridge, past a tiny island where the locals dig up clay
for their pots and bury their dead infants. The boats entered the
labyrinth, gliding on waters putrid from the day's wastes,
continuing their Stygian descent into Makoko.
</P>
<P>
   People were more prosperous in the next town, Sogunro Iwaya,
where sections have been filled with land. Kids played at a pool
table; others at Super Mario Brothers on a Nintendo running on the
lone generator.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can say that Nigeria is like the France of Africa,'' said
Pierre Kodja, 49, explaining that most of the townspeople were from
the neighboring country of Benin. Kodja, a fisherman, tailor and
traditional healer who had left Benin in 1977, was sitting in the
courtyard of a two-story house belonging to the chief, Moise
Messou, and his brother, Abraham Messou.
</P>
<P>
   As far back as the 1950s, poor fishermen from Benin began
gravitating to Lagos lagoon, where they found more customers able
to pay more money for their catch, they said. Over the years, more
and more Beninese immigrants settled in the lagoon and had children
here. And yet their lives here has changed little from their
village in Benin, so little that few today speak English, Nigeria's
official language, and many more understand French, the language of
Benin's former rulers.
</P>
<P>
   The town's one practitioner of Western medicine, Dr. Pierre
Denakpo, walked up to the chief's house. The doctor had also come
from Benin, 15 years ago, to treat his own people here. The
illnesses here never changed: diarrhea, malaria, cholera. Faton,
the fisherman, said five of his 11 children had died over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am returning to Benin next year,'' the doctor said, adding
that he had a clinic in another town in the lagoon, where many more
of his people had settled. One had to take a boat there, he said,
but go by way of Lagos first. Life on the ground in Lagos, so
chaotic, frenetic and seemingly lawless, was even beyond the
control of the generals who ruled Nigeria until half a year ago.
That may be one reason why they moved the capital to Abuja, in the
sparsely populated center of the country, a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patience is bitter, but its fruit is sweet,'' read a window
sticker on an orange public bus as it hurtled down the highway to
the city port, its tires bald, its rear lights a distant memory,
its inside so crammed with passengers that half the body of a young
man dangled out of an open side door. On a footbridge alongside the
highway, a man hung laundry on the guardrail.
</P>
<P>
   Bridges have turned into places of fear in Lagos, especially
since the police caught a deranged man living under Toyota Bridge,
so named after the nearby car dealership, several months ago. The
madman had lured his victims under the bridge and eaten them,
according to the police who found human remains there.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With man-eaters stalking the streets at night and lurking under
bridges during the day, who wouldn't choose to live on an island
without bridges?
</P>
<P>
   At the port, hidden from the main road, a narrow entrance
between two buildings opened on a gutter, where three women were
washing clothes, and on a foot-wide edge running alongside one of
the buildings. The edge led to the lagoon, where fishermen paddled
their pirogues for a fee to Sogbokoji, the village where Denakpo
ran his clinic.
</P>
<P>
   But the doctor was away.
</P>
<P>
   The village children pointed to another clinic nearby, where an
excitable and cheerful man answered the door. He showed a visitor a
crumpled business card, but held on to it:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. A.S. Theophilus, M.D. Christ Clinic.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside a small room with no electricity, Theophilus
Ahouandjenou, 44, and his wife, Valerie, 36, a nurse, said they had
come from Benin a few years ago and opened the clinic two years
ago. He waved at the small bottles of medication he kept on his
desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here don't understand the value of medicine,'' he said,
complaining that he earned only about $2 a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catholic nuns taught me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ahouandjenou received his training from the Red Cross, he said,
showing an old identification card from 1990. Under his name, the
ID from the Red Cross of Benin declared his profession:
``Cuisinier.'' Cook.
</P>
<P>
   He smiled. A Nigerian doctor had toured the lagoon villages
three years ago and taught him all about medicine. And so
Ahouandjenou, a cook since age 22, had been inspired to switch
careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Continental dishes, that's what I used to prepare,'' he said.
``Pastries! I specialized in pastries!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-99 1855EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
