<DOCNO> NYT19991212.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6748 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-EQUITY-GHSA13-COX     12-12 2473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EQUITY-GHSA13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia organization perpetuates gap in gender equity
 &HT;    By Mike Fish and David A. Milliron
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORSYTH, Ga. _ Seated around a horseshoe-shaped conference
table, usually at the Holiday Inn off Interstate 75, the executive
committee of the Georgia High School Association gathers twice a
year to wrestle with everything from the date of the first football
practices to judging criteria for dramatic interpretation and
public speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Much like the high school students whose extracurricular
activities they influence, the committee tends to break into
cliques: a large group of football coaches and athletics directors
at one end of the table, African-Americans in another section and
the two women committee members across from them, side by side.
</P>
<P>
   In 50 years, at least 2,500 people have served on the committee,
which governs after-school functions involving 200,000 Georgia boys
and girls.
</P>
<P>
   Five of them have been women _ two-tenths of 1 percent of the
committee's total membership.
</P>
<P>
   To critics of the GHSA, that gender gap speaks volumes about the
attention the organization gives to girls sports in high schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your aim is to have 50 percent of the participants being
women, then you can't just have two women on the board,'' said
Lucia Norwood, DeKalb County athletics director. ``You don't have
equal representation, for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, women's sports are experiencing exponential growth
at college and professional levels, fueled by such high-visibility
successes as the world championship victory by the U.S. soccer
team. The excitement generated by those successes and the lure of
$200 million annually in college athletics scholarships for women,
have heightened interest in sports among younger girls.
</P>
<P>
   A catalyst for that makeover in women's college athletics is a
27-year-old federal law, Title IX, that requires boys and girls
sports programs be treated equally at schools that receive public
funds.
</P>
<P>
   But in Georgia, an Atlanta Journal-Constitution investigation of
sports funding, participation and coaching suggests that many
schools' boys and girls sports programs are not equal.
</P>
<P>
   Boys coaches commonly are paid significantly more, for example,
and the ratio of students per coach is lower for exclusively boys
sports than for exclusively girls sports, the investigation showed.
</P>
<P>
   Local school districts know there is a federal law and what it
says, state School Superintendent Linda Schrenko said. ``They are
probably in violation of that federal law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't give you a number to go with that,'' she said. ``I can
only tell you that everywhere I go, it seems the predominant sports
are the boys sports, and it seems that the gate receipts go toward
enhancing those sports that are making money. So it's a perpetual
cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very difficult for girls to break into the system.''
</P>
<P>
   The GHSA's critics argue that the association has played an
aggressive role in perpetuating that cycle. They suggest that the
GHSA is first and foremost a defender and proud standard-bearer for
the state's high school football teams. It is also the
organization's biggest revenue producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know where their profit lies,'' Schrenko said.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the GHSA has been quick to respond to anything its
leadership perceives as a threat to its premier program or its
authority.
</P>
<P>
   The association led opposition in 1994 to a state bill intended
to encourage gender equity in Georgia high school athletics. It
initially fought against the no pass/no play rule intended to put
academics first. It has opposed attempts to eliminate spring
football practice. And, counter to the wishes of the U.S.
Department of Education's Office for Civil Rights, the GHSA
continues to count cheerleading as a competitive sport.
</P>
<P>
   Records show it began including cheerleaders shortly after a
Title IX challenge in Oconee County focused attention on sports
participation rates for boys and girls. Counting cheerleaders
inflated the girls participation rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to upset my friends, but I think they have addressed
the racial part a lot better than they have addressed the gender
issue,'' said Don Hight, a former state Department of Education
representative to the GHSA. ``The mentality probably hasn't changed
to the degree it should.''
</P>
<P>
   GHSA BROUGHT ORDER TO STATE
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia High School Association has existed in some form
since 1905, but it came of age in 1946 with the hiring of Sam
Burke, its first full-time executive director. Since then, the
association has had two other directors.
</P>
<P>
   When Burke came on board, high school sports were a mess. Age
and grades meant nothing for eligibility. The GHSA helped create
order.
</P>
<P>
   Regionally, the GHSA has drawn praise for its strict enforcement
of eligibility standards and for maintaining control of its
private-school members. That is in contrast to Tennessee, where
recruiting battles among private schools are notorious.
</P>
<P>
   Its executive committee decides everything from whether a body
microphone can be used in one-act play competitions to how wide a
spectator's seat must be for hosting a state championship football
or soccer game _ 18 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Although its name might suggest it is a state agency, the GHSA
is a private, nonprofit organization, answerable only to itself. As
such, it is similar to associations set up to serve similar
functions in most other states.
</P>
<P>
   The GHSA is headquartered in a building once used as a dry
cleaner in Thomaston. The association's executive director is Tommy
Guillebeau, a soft-spoken former football coach at Warren County
High School and Americus High School who also was an athletics
director and an administrator in three other school systems.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Guillebeau persuaded Schrenko's state Department
of Education to surrender its control over the eligibility of state
athletes to the GHSA. The move put control of a student's
eligibility firmly in the hands of a private organization, which
already was insulated from parents who might balk at decisions
because of policies that allow only GHSA member schools to appeal
decisions. Parents have no direct access to the organization.
Schrenko maintains that her department's decision to give up its
authority to the GHSA was the right move for the state because it
was duplicating the GHSA's eligibility enforcement efforts.
</P>
<P>
   When Guillebeau negotiated the agreement, GHSA attorney Alan
Connell warned against language implying that the association was a
state agency and possibly subjecting it to the Open Meetings Act.
Connell said that such designation would ``seriously impair the
ability of the GHSA to carry out its function.''
</P>
<P>
   The GHSA is run by Guillebeau, its officers and the executive
committee. The president for the past two decades has been Gary
Holmes, a retired basketball coach and administrator from Glynn
County. The vice president is Walter Wade, a retired football coach
and athletics administrator from the Atlanta city schools who first
joined the executive committee 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   There are no term limits for committee membership, according to
Guillebeau.
</P>
<P>
   Qualifications for being on the committee?
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to be a person,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Guillebeau's executive committee is made up of members elected
from the state's 32 regions, plus seven at-large appointed
positions. The regional members, according to those involved in the
process, are chosen in a loose election process by local athletics
directors, principals and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ORGANIZATION THRIVING
</P>
<P>
   Of the 37 men _ and two women _ on the GHSA executive committee,
three-quarters have football coach on their resume and seven still
pace the sidelines on Friday nights.
</P>
<P>
   During the course of Guillebeau's tenure, the GHSA not only has
increased its authority over high school sports, it has fattened
its coffers. In the past five years, the association has generated
almost $10 million in total revenues, while net assets have
increased 265 percent. It earns $1.5 million a year from high
school tournaments and playoffs, collecting 40 percent off the top
of the state basketball playoffs. It takes what amounts to a
sanctioning fee before expenses from host schools, many of whom
struggle to fund athletics programs. It has sold marketing rights
to Wilson Sporting Goods and designated the MUSCO Co. as an
official lighting company of the GHSA.
</P>
<P>
   Guillebeau concluded a 2-minute director's reportin October by
saying, ``Financially, we're strong, and I think we'll continue to
be strong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an awfully lot richer kingdom than I thought,'' said
DeKalb lawyer Richard Foxworth, who has assisted in filing Title IX
complaints against two GHSA member schools. ``With that kind of
money, they could hire somebody for $50,000 a year to go out and
explain gender equity to the schools.''
</P>
<P>
   To gauge attitudes about gender equity, the GHSA and how the
administration of high school sports are viewed by those closest to
it, the Journal-Constitution surveyed school principals,
superintendents, GHSA executive committee members and coaches.
Ninety-three percent of superintendents, 92 percent of the
executive committee, two-thirds of the state's 323 principals and
936 coaches participated.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the survey showed that the GHSA committee members
reflected the opinions of the folks who elected them. More than 80
percent of principals and more than 90 percent of superintendents
said that female athletes in Georgia schools would not be better
served if there was a state gender-equity law that would allow for
monitoring by the government. Eighty-two percent of GHSA committee
members felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the committee members also saw no point in increasing
the number of women on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every child is being represented fairly,'' said six-year
member Ronald Dixon, principal of Jeff Davis High School. ``I don't
know how any additional women could enhance the process, but I'm
certainly not against additional women being on there.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't sit well with all member schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems the Georgia High School Association controls
everything, and I think that's a huge issue because it is a
self-perpetuating board,'' said Anne Harper, vice president of the
Atlanta School Board. ``I'm shocked to find that Walter Wade, who
doesn't even work for Atlanta public schools anymore, is GHSA vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely an old football coach from Atlanta, and I
don't think he has a bone in his body that would be thinking about
girls sports.''
</P>
<P>
   NOT ALL COACHES LIKE STATUS QUO
</P>
<P>
   In the varsity coaching ranks, opinions about the GHSA might
best be characterized as lukewarm support. Forty-six percent of
coaches who were surveyed said they were satisfied with the
organization. Thirty-seven percent graded the GHSA's performance as
fair, and 17 percent were dissatisfied with the association.
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of the comments from coaches:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The GHSA has become too powerful and is football/South
Georgia controlled.'' _ a basketball coach
</P>
<P>
   _ ``They are too dictatorial, with no appeal process. God does
not live at GHSA headquarters.'' _ a track coach
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I would form a rival governing body if I thought it had a
prayer.'' _ a soccer coach
</P>
<P>
   Although they included few comments about the GHSA, football and
golf coaches gave the association the highest grades. More than 27
percent said they were very satisfied with the job done by the
GHSA. ``Very professional,'' said one football coach.
</P>
<P>
   In the survey of the GHSA's executive committee, members viewed
their organization as being supportive of gender equity but not in
any way responsible for assuring it. The organization does not
employ a gender-equity coordinator. It sponsors mandatory rules
clinics for coaches _ imposing $50 fines on those who fail to
attend _ but no clinics on how to assure that boys and girls sports
programs are organized equitably.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a role in that,'' Guillebeau said.
</P>
<P>
   More than a third of the 52 state associations surveyed by the
Journal-Constitution, including Washington, D.C., and a separate
all-girls association in Iowa, claim to either monitor or enforce
gender-equity policy. Almost 60 percent said the state education
department monitors or enforces policy in their states, which is
not the case in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that state high school athletic associations certainly
would be a source of where one would expect that there would be
some guidance in terms of compliance, as well as individual high
school districts themselves,'' said Mary Francis O'Shea, Title IX
coordinator for the U.S. Department of Education. ``I know a number
of state high school associations have gender requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   STATE'S HANDS TIED
</P>
<P>
   Georgia School Superintendent Linda Schrenko confirmed the
state's minimal involvement, saying that since funding for
athletics and other extracurricular activities comes from the local
level, and not the state, she is without a stick to enforce
compliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we don't fund it, we can't police it, per se,'' she
said. ``We could, but with what authority? I can go tell them you
ought not to be doing that. But if you can't withhold money or have
some sort of sanction against them, you really have no effect. So
it gets down to that money at the local level.''
</P>
<P>
   And at the local level, the football tradition runs deep. The
surveys offered a glimpse of how deeply the sport is woven into the
administrative fabric of Georgia's public schools. At least
one-third of the state's superintendents reported they previously
had served as football coaches. No other sport or extracurricular
activity came close. An even higher percentage of principals _ 36
percent _ have football coaching backgrounds, the survey showed.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, the GHSA weathered a significant media storm
over gender equity. The lack of female representation on its
executive committee attracted the attention of some mothers and
fathers of girls who played high school sports. One was WSB-TV news
anchor Monica Kaufman, who has an athletic daughter. The newswoman
was among parents concerned about whether girls sports got a fair
shake in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   She brought a camera crew to the GHSA headquarters in Thomaston
and asked Guillebeau, the executive director, why no women (at that
time) had ever served on the board in its 87-year history.
</P>
<P>
   She said Guillebeau told her he felt it was a problem and ``they
were planning on doing something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   And he did. Soon after, the GHSA appointed two women to its
executive board.
</P>
<P>
   From that day to this one, that seemed like enough.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
