<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6749 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-FLORIDA-POLITICS-800(     12-12 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-POLITICS-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GORE AND BRADLEY, A GENTLEMANLY DUEL IN FLORIDA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif., N.Y., Ohio)  (jw) 
 By JAMES DAO with KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla., _ Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill
Bradley, the Democratic candidates for president, opened a spirited
competition for Florida voters during the weekend, delivering
dueling speeches before the state Democratic convention that, in
gentlemanly language, sharply contrasted their records, styles and
visions for the country.
</P>
<P>
   In a forceful speech before 2,000 party stalwarts Sunday,
Bradley suggested that the vice president would ``shrink back'' and
``tinker around the edges,'' while his own ``bold'' ideas would
rekindle the spirit of three Democratic icons: Woodrow Wilson,
Franklin D. Roosevelt and Robert F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, `Now is not the time to settle,''' Bradley said,
testing a new refrain in his 35-minute address. ``I'm not prepared
to settle for anything less than making access to health care
affordable to all Americans. I'm not prepared to settle for
anything short of registering and licensing all hand guns in this
country. I'm not prepared to settle for anything less than bringing
all children out of poverty in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats,'' he concluded, ``do not settle.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Gore delivered a 45-minute speech that toned down
his usual sledgehammer attacks on Bradley, apparently out of
respect for Bradley's health after the former senator went to a
California hospital on Friday suffering from a bout of irregular
heart beats.
</P>
<P>
   But without naming his opponent, Gore suggested to his audience
that Bradley's positions on Social Security, education, the budget
and Medicare, the government health care program for the elderly,
were out of sync with traditional Democratic values.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted against those Reagan-Bush budget cuts,'' Gore said,
omitting his usual criticism of Bradley for supporting them in
1981. ``I fought against the Newt Gingrich Republican Congress,''
he added, invoking questions about Bradley's party loyalty for
retiring from the Senate in 1996, after Gingrich came to power as
speaker.
</P>
<P>
   In another implicit jab at Bradley, Gore said, ``I have never
been afraid to take on the big pharmaceutical companies,'' a
reference to Bradley's repeated Senate votes for measures supported
by the pharmaceutical industry. New Jersey is home to many of the
nation's largest drug companies, and several of them contributed
heavily to Bradley's Senate campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's irregular heartbeats, a chronic condition known as
atrial fibrillation for which he takes daily medication, forced him
to cancel several West Coast events on Friday and Saturday. But his
doctors, who say the condition is not serious, said the
palpitations stopped spontaneously on Friday, without treatment.
Sunday, the candidate look relaxed and energetic. His aides said he
would maintain a busy campaign schedule this week.
</P>
<P>
   The appearance of the two candidates in Florida, the fourth
largest state, underscored the potential importance of its March 14
primary, which falls one week after the primaries in California,
New York, Ohio and several other Northern states. Both men will
have to campaign selectively in March, and this weekend's
convention indicated both are likely to target Florida.
</P>
<P>
   For the Gore camp, Florida offers an important opportunity,
along with other Southern states, to knock Bradley back if he does
well on March 7. The vice president, from Tennessee, is viewed as
the front-runner here and across the South, having locked up
endorsements from many top Democratic state officials like State
Attorney General Bob Butterworth, and the largest unions, including
the 442,000-member state AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley campaign officials assert that they can compete with
Gore in Florida more effectively than in other Southern states
largely because of its many transplanted New York and New Jersey
residents. Bradley represented New Jersey in the Senate for 18
years and played basketball for the New York Knicks for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   In wooing Florida voters now, the two candidates also reflected
a growing concern among many Democrats that the eventual Democratic
nominee might have trouble winning here in November because Gov.
Jeb Bush of Florida is the brother of the Republican presidential
front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton won the state in 1996, but several polls have
shown George W. Bush leading both Democrats here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their coming here sends a signal that Florida is still viable
for the Democrats,'' said Charles Whitehead, the chairman of the
state Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehead said Sunday he thought that Bradley faced ``an uphill
battle'' in Florida. But he said he thought the former senator was
gaining support, adding, ``I would guess that 75 percent of
Bradley's supporters in the room today were committed to Gore
before the convention. He was very well received today.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gore's chief message here was to Florida's legions of retired
people, reassuring them that he would stand fast on protecting
Social Security and Medicare, programs he had said Bradley would do
little to defend and might even undermine.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also traded unabashedly on his partnership with Clinton,
who remains popular in Florida and who spoke warmly of Gore to the
conventioneers earlier on Saturday. Gore reminded the audience of
the economic boom of the Clinton years and that Florida supported
the Clinton-Gore re-election in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton and I came in and, with Democratic votes alone,
we changed the policy of our country, and we reordered the
priorities,'' Gore said. ``This kind of progress is not something
that we should just casually toss aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley gave his usual stump speech Sunday, but spiced it with a
stronger assertion than usual of his support for Social Security,
Medicaid, Medicare and civil rights protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there anybody who questions our belief in Social Security,
civil rights, Medicare?'' he asked. ``That's why if find it so
dismaying that one Democrat can attack another on these issues. On
issues that are articles of faith for our party. If we are united
on anything, we have to be united on these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates made strong appeals to black voters, voicing
their support for affirmative action, which has become a hot topic
here. Opponents of the policy are trying to place an initiative on
the ballot that would end the use of racial preferences by state
government and public universities.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates said that they supported giving a visa to the
father of a 6-year-old Cuban boy, Elian Gonzalez, who was rescued
off the Florida coast while escaping to the United States aboard a
boat last month. The boy's mother died on the trip, and he has
become the focus of a battle between his father, who says he wants
him returned to Cuba, and Cuban Americans in Florida who want him
to remain here.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley said the father should be allowed to travel to
the United States so that he can, free of possible coercion by the
Cuban government, express his desire for the return of his son.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
