<HEADLINE>
LLOYD RODWIN, 80, AUTHORITY ON URBAN STUDIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ind., Calif.)  (lb) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lloyd Rodwin, an internationally influential authority on urban
studies and planning, died on Tuesday at Massachusetts General
Hospital in Boston. He was 80 and lived in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was congestive heart failure, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodwin retired in 1988 as Ford International professor of urban
studies at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, where he
taught for four decades and was chairman of the department of urban
studies and planning for several years.
</P>
<P>
   At the MIT-Harvard Joint Center for Urban Studies, which he
co-founded in 1959, he worked with Daniel Patrick Moynihan before
Moynihan became a Democratic senator from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Rodwin ``was hugely influential,'' the senator recalled on
Thursday, and his chief impact on his field of expertise was that
``he redefined the study of cities, defined them in terms of the
people who lived there rather than the buildings in which they
lived.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a great teacher of professors,'' Moynihan said, who
``broke the iron hold of urban studies,'' as it had been defined,
in terms of ``laying out a grand city, or a grand suburb.''
</P>
<P>
   The main impetus for that earlier way of thinking came from the
Columbian Exposition of 1893 in Chicago, the senator said. The
fair's splendid grounds featured grand vistas and buildings
reminiscent of ancient Rome. It embodied the style of urban design
called the City Beautiful movement.
</P>
<P>
   But ``by the time we had the joint center going, the cities
weren't all that beautiful, and never had been,'' Moynihan said,
and the subject of urban planning ``was still abstract and quite
removed from any of the realities of urban life in the second half
of the 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   Another MIT urbanist, Bernard Frieden, said: ``Lloyd really
changed the field from city planning to urban studies. He
emphasized research on how cities work. Lloyd made the field much
broader and extended it to the Third World.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodwin and Kevin Lynch, also of MIT, wrote in a 1961 essay:
``Men are attracted to the metropolis by real values _ choice,
freedom, privacy, opportunity, culture, entertainment. How can we
ensure the realization of these ends? More importantly, what are
the possibilities for metropolitan life that are as yet undreamed
of? And what kind of power, knowledge or guidance must be applied
to achieve them? The spirit of hopeful intervention should prove at
least as effective as the desire to escape present discomfort.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodwin was known for his studies of regional and urban
quandaries in the developing world. According to the journal
Planning, an entire city in Venezuela, the port complex Ciudad
Guayana, ``was planned with the assistance of a group of North
Americans led by Lloyd Rodwin'' in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   He was also an adviser to the United Nations and the author,
co-author, editor or co-editor of 10 books.
</P>
<P>
   Born in New York, he received a bachelor's degree from City
College there and a doctorate in regional planning from Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Nadine Posniak Rodwin; two sons,
Victor, of New York, and Marc Andre, of Bloomington, Ind.; a
daughter, Julie Anne Rodwin, of Groton, Mass.; a brother, Ted
Rosenbaum; a sister, Claire Levy, of Laguna Hills, Calif., and six
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-99 1906EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
