<HEADER>
A6757 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GIRLS-SPORTSEQUITY13-     12-12 1311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRLS-SPORTSEQUITY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia treats girl athletes second-class
 &HT;    By Mike Fish and David A. Milliron
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In 1972, the year when women first were allowed to
serve as FBI agents and the Equal Rights Act was passed by
Congress, something called Title IX became federal law.
</P>
<P>
   It mandated that school athletics programs for boys and girls be
given comparable support.
</P>
<P>
   More than 27 years later, gender equity still is not the
standard in most Georgia high schools.
</P>
<P>
   Not even close.
</P>
<P>
   The association in charge of high school athletics in Georgia
says ensuring a fair distribution of resources to boys and girls
sports is not and should not be its responsibility. In a survey,
the association's executive committee said policing gender-equity
issues isn't the responsibility of the state, and the association
has lobbied aggressively to prevent passage of a state Title IX
law.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say that with no state law, they have no
authority to act. Federal authorities say that if there is no local
enforcement, they rely on parents. They suggest that parents who
cannot get help locally contact the U.S. Department of Education's
Office for Civil Rights.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis by The Atlanta Journal-Constitution shows that
girls' participation rates in high school sports have grown in
recent years. But it indicates a majority of Georgia's public high
schools would not pass muster if they faced a federal gender-equity
challenge. The newspaper looked at participation levels, funding,
quality of facilities and coaching support for high school boys and
girls sports _ and found gender inequities to be commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia high schools, girls slightly outnumber boys.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the newspaper found:
</P>
<P>
   _ 75 percent of local salary supplements for coaching goes to
support boys sports, while 25 percent goes to girls programs.
</P>
<P>
   _ 95 percent of so-called ``extended pay'' supplements
(amounting to more than $12 million per year in additional
financial support for coaches) goes to the coaches of boys sports.
Girls programs get 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ For football, an almost exclusively male sport, the ratio of
students per coach statewide is 9-to-1. For softball and
volleyball, exclusively female sports, the ratio is 12-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   _ 64 percent of athletes are boys; 36 percent are girls.
</P>
<P>
   The state's top school official says she thinks a case could be
made that nearly every public high school in the state might be in
violation of Title IX.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the good ol' boy system,'' says Georgia School
Superintendent Linda Schrenko. ``And good ol' boys have traditional
roles for girls that don't include athletics.''
</P>
<P>
   The superintendent says she has little authority to make
improvements and suggests the Legislature to date has worked harder
to preserve the status quo than to change it.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the federal law does require is that local school
districts designate a Title IX coordinator. In a survey, one-fourth
of school superintendents acknowledged they did not have a
coordinator. And in those districts where superintendents did have
a designated coordinator, word hasn't always trickled down.
Fifty-five percent of principals who were surveyed said they were
unaware of a coordinator in their district.
</P>
<P>
   At the collegiate level, Title IX has brought huge changes to
women's athletics, with more than $200 million now available in
athletic scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   As is the case with boys, the benefits of girls' participation
in sports are well-documented. Studies show that involvement in
sports for girls leads to higher self-esteem and confidence, lowers
pregnancy rates, creates more positive attitudes toward school and
reduces destructive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In a number of states, including neighboring Florida, gender
equity has become part of the high school athletics culture. Last
year in Florida, female participation in high school sports
increased 24 percent, according to officials. Florida has had a
state gender-equity law since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Sports participation rates for high school girls in Florida are
six percentage points higher than in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has been slow to embrace the cultural shift. For
generations, what happens beneath Friday night lights on a high
school football field has helped define a community. High school
football rules, particularly in rural Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   In a building once used by a dry cleaner in Thomaston, a private
group led mostly by current and former football coaches has worked
to uphold that tradition.
</P>
<P>
   This group is the Georgia High School Association. The GHSA is a
private, nonprofit organization with millions in assets, garnered
from tournament profits, annual dues and high school sports
marketing agreements, financial statements show.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions made by the association directly affect the lives
of hundreds of thousands of Georgia students in public and private
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Football is the revenue leader that drives the GHSA. For
example, the state's high school football playoffs, played this
weekend at the Georgia Dome, are expected to generate about
$500,000 for the GHSA.
</P>
<P>
   Its executive board of 37 men and two women is particularly
expert in football; at least 72 percent of the members are or were
football coaches, according to a Journal-Constitution survey.
</P>
<P>
   But the GHSA governs more than football. It oversees all
extracurricular activities in Georgia high schools _ from drama and
debate competitions to baseball schedules and volleyball clinics.
Two years ago, the private group secured additional authority from
the state to decide who can participate in extracurricular school
activities.
</P>
<P>
   Parents who do not like the GHSA decisions can ask their local
school officials to appeal, but parents cannot go before the GHSA
on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Former state School Superintendent Werner Rogers says the GHSA
deserves credit for assuming a role the state was hard put to fill.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've provided a great service to the schools and school
systems by organizing interscholastic sports,'' he says. ``By
having stringent rules and holding people to them, they have pretty
much controlled the misuse of athletes, playing kids not eligible,
etc.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the GHSA's efforts, coaches say, Georgia is a very
good state to grow up in if you are a boy interested in football.
The state ranks as a leading feeder system for collegiate football
ranks and the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   But some argue the GHSA's actions have slowed the growth of
girls high school sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, more work needs to be done for the girls programs,''
says Mary Francis O'Shea, national Title IX coordinator for the
U.S. Department of Education's Office for Civil Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Schrenko says the Legislature has helped perpetuate inequities
between boys and girls athletics by using the state Department of
Community Affairs as a pork-barrel vehicle for funding
brick-and-mortar projects that tend to favor boys sports.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal-Constitution examined the legislative grants made
during a five-year period for stadiums, lighting, field houses,
equipment and the like. The newspaper found that 86 percent of the
dollars were directed to projects where the primary beneficiaries
are boys sports.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the athletics director and assistant principal of
Macon County High was asked whether a $100,000 grant from the state
Legislature to expand the football stadium prompted any concerns
about gender equity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gender equity,'' Tommy Moore says, considering the idea. ``We
got girls in the band. The cheerleaders are girls. Half the people
in the stands are girls. We hold graduation in the stadium, and
half the graduates are girls. Our managers are girls; our
statisticians are girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
