<SLUG> BC-OLY-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC BANS TRIPS TO BIDDING CITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Three days before he faces a certain
grilling from the U.S. Congress, Juan Antonio Samaranch gained an
important political victory Sunday by persuading members of the
International Olympic Committee to give up one of their most
cherished and abused privileges _visiting cities that are bidding
on the Winter and Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   When Samaranch, the president of the IOC, appears on Capitol
Hill on Wednesday, he will now be able to assert that the
organization has instituted an extensive package of reforms a year
after the Salt Lake City bribery scandal. At the same time,
delegates cautioned Sunday that much more work needed to be done to
restore public trust in the Olympic movement and that substantial
change does not guarantee the prevention of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Roland Baar, a gold medalist rower from Germany elected Sunday
to the IOC, said the reforms were ``a kind of probation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The world and the athletes will check the results very
precisely,'' Baar said.
</P>
<P>
   The willing acceptance of millions of dollars in cash payments,
scholarships, free medical care and other gifts from Salt Lake City
bid officials has come to represent the widespread perception of
the IOC as an arrogant and unaccountable organization. Ten members
resigned or were expelled, and another 10 received warnings in the
worst crisis of the modern Olympics. A continuing investigation by
the U.S. Justice Department has resulted in two indictments related
to allegations that people involved in the Salt Lake City bid gave
a sham job to the son of Kim Un-yong of South Korea, a prominent
IOC member.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch has agreed to speak with FBI agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a political decision today,'' said Mario Pescante, an
Italian who is a member of the IOC. ``At the moment of voting,
there was a very intense feeling that this was very important to
strengthen the position of the president. The strength of the
president is our strength. Going before the United States Congress,
it is very important that he can prove that we made important
reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   Had he not been able to end the visits, or push through age and
so-called term limits for IOC members, Samaranch would have
substantially increased his vulnerability when he appears before
the House Commerce Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations,
headed by Rep Fred Upton, R-Mich. Samaranch will still most likely
face tough questioning on subjects ranging from his role in Spain's
Franco regime to a $12,000 side trip that his wife and a friend
took to Charleston, S.C., in 1990, while Atlanta was bidding on the
1996 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enacting a package of reforms as a whole is his best ally,''
said Kevan Gosper of Australia, a member of the committee's
executive board.
</P>
<P>
   After two hours of debate Sunday on the issue of visits,
Samaranch used shrewd manipulation to ban them when the issue came
to a vote. Instead of asking which delegates were against the
trips, Samaranch asked who favored them, forcing those who would
oppose him to raise their hands. Only 10 of 100 delegates did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did what we promised,'' Samaranch said of the reform
package enacted over two days of meetings here. But he also
acknowledged that the Salt Lake City scandal was the ``catalyst for
reform that we should have seen as necessary a long time
beforehand.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, considerable change has been made in the IOC in
the last year. The committee has opened its meetings, made
financial records available, started a worldwide doping agency,
banned visits to bidding cities, forced the delegates to face
re-election every eight years, restricted future members to an age
limit of 70, limited future presidents to a maximum of 12 years in
office, enacted an ethics commission, implemented a code of conduct
and selected 12 active athletes to its assembly. Officials from bid
cities can also no longer visit IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mr. Samaranch goes to Washington as president of a
renovated, renewed, transparent, rejuvenated, more democratic
IOC,'' said Jacques Rogge of Belgium, a vice president of the
committee and a possible successor to Samaranch. ``That is not a
bad position to start with.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the IOC remains essentially the same
organization it was before the weekend, and the period while the
reforms are implemented could be considerable. Skeptics have
questioned whether the IOC is committed to reform or is simply
acting out of political expediency under pressure from corporate
sponsors, lawmakers and the news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have changed rules, but that is not enough; we also have to
change behavior,'' Rogge said. ``Reputations are not made by rules
and amendments; reputations are made on a day to day basis by the
individual behavior of every member. I'm confident we will prove
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics contend that the committee could even become more
insular with so-called term limits, because delegates might be
reluctant to agitate their colleagues and risk not being
re-elected. Even though 10 delegates were removed in the past year,
most were from developing nations; insiders such as Phil Coles of
Australia and Kim were given only warnings.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC also has admitted being far behind in research to combat
the use of performance-enhancing drugs. One of the athletes elected
Sunday, Manuela Di Centa, who won two gold medals for Italy in
cross-country at the 1994 Winter Olympics in Lillehammer, Norway,
has been linked to an investigation by an Italian judge into the
use of the performance-enhancing endurance drug EPO. She has denied
using the drug.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 30 delegates have been implicated in various
improprieties linked to bids by Salt Lake City to host the 2002
Winter Games, Atlanta's hosting of the 1996 Summer Games and
Sydney's bid for the 2000 Summer Games. Even so, Syed Shahid Ali, a
delegate from Pakistan, Sunday blamed the ``Satanic'' practices of
bid cities for creating the climate of excessive favors.
</P>
<P>
   Despite new professions of openness, the IOC would not provide a
list of the 10 delegates who voted against the ban on visits.
Reporters were forced to watch from another room on closed-circuit
television. One vocal opponent, Princess Anne of Britain, said the
ban would be unenforceable because many delegates would still visit
the cities in other capacities as sports officials. She called the
ban ``nonsense,'' saying it was passed ``because it has been deemed
necessary to put on a public performance of how to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   One delegate, Lambis W. Nikolaou of Greece, urged Samaranch not
to appear before Congress, saying that it might be seen as a sign
of weakness and that, as president of the IOC, Samaranch was
``accountable only to the Olympic family.'' However, the
79-year-old Samaranch said he was ready to answer any and all
questions. He is buttressed by having pushed through 50 reform
proposals this weekend, all by votes that were unanimous or an
overwhelming majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not thinking of Congress,'' Samaranch said. ``We were
only thinking of the future of the IOC.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch repeated that he planned to remain as president until
his term ends on July 16, 2001, exactly 21 years after he was
elected. Saying that the newly enacted reforms would make the IOC
``more open, more transparent, younger, in short more modern,'' he
also acknowledged, ``We recognize there has been a breach of trust
between the IOC and the public, and that it will take some time to
heal.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
