<HEADLINE>
OH, CANADA! VANCOUVER MAKES THE CULINARY `EH'-LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I learned at an early age that there were plenty of wonderful
things to see and do in western Canada. It was a wonderful place to
visit, but you really wouldn't want to eat there.
</P>
<P>
   At least half the restaurants in Alberta advertised
``Canadian-Chinese food,'' which suggested chow mein topped with
maple syrup. You couldn't buy a decent hamburger in British
Columbia. Restaurants offered hot dogs but then served ``bangers''
_ seasoned sawdust in a pig's intestine. Meat pies in Vancouver
delis were cheap and about as tasty as a donkey's ear.
</P>
<P>
   Only lately, after numerous research excursions north of the
border, have I erased these prejudices to the point where I might
suggest that Vancouver may be the best restaurant city north of San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Don't laugh. Instead, visit Robson or Denman streets at 10 p.m.
on a Tuesday night. The stores are open, the restaurants are doing
gold-rush business and, unless it is pouring rain, locals jam the
sidewalks four abreast.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver's population has topped 2 million and is climbing.
Construction cranes are as numerous as Starbucks outlets. During a
Vancouver visit, Bette Midler nominated the city as the coffee
capital of North America.
</P>
<P>
   In a seven-block span on Robson there are 41 restaurants, by
recent count. Turn the corner and travel another seven blocks on
Denman and you pass 50 more restaurants offering cuisine from every
corner of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen or 20 years ago our favorite Vancouver ``discoveries''
included Hy's steakhouse, the William Tell, a First Nation
restaurant named Muckamuck, Umberto's and Cafe de Paris, which
offered the best pommes frites in the world and a stunning dish
featuring rabbit in red wine.
</P>
<P>
   More recent recollections include giant scallops wrapped in
octopus ``bacon'' with shiitake mushroom cakes and truffle oil at C
Restaurant; a Dungeness crab and shrimp cake with arugula pesto and
smoked lentils at the Beach Side Cafe in a neighborhood known as
Ambleside; breast of duck with a roasted pear tart at Diva at the
Met; Double Belgian Chocolate Truffle and Fudge Cake at Seasons
Restaurant in Queen Elizabeth Park, where Bill Clinton and Boris
Yeltsin put on a few pounds at lunch during the 1993 summit
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the best eatery in Vancouver is supposed to be Le Crocodile,
unless it is Bishop's, Chartwell, Cin Cin Restorante or one of the
other establishments mentioned above. And there are probably as
many quality Chinese restaurants as you would find in San Francisco
or New York.
</P>
<P>
   But do not believe the tour guides who swear that the yellow
pile identified as sulfur across the bay from Stanley Park is
actually a stockpile of Canadian powdered eggs, ready for export to
all the fast-food franchises in Seattle and Portland, rivals for
the Pacific Northwest Gutbuster Award.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a major appetite but a minor bankroll, skip the
expensive restaurants and fulfill your lust in your own kitchen
with dishes such as these.
</P>
<P>
   Robson Risotto
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half cups Arborio rice
</P>
<P>
   5 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup minced red onion
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped fresh mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 medium clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup chopped sun-dried tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon powdered saffron
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-quarter cup chopped smoked chicken
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   You usually can find smoked chicken in some form at major
grocery stores. Or throw an extra bird on the grill the next time
you roast whole chicken on your barbecue, then reserve the
leftovers for this dish.
</P>
<P>
   Wash and drain the rice a couple of times. Heat the broth and
keep it at a simmer.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a heavy pot and saute the onions and mushrooms,
about 5 minutes. Add the drained rice, the garlic and the sun-dried
tomatoes. (Use the tomatoes that are packed in olive oil. If you
use packaged dry tomatoes, they must be reconstituted according to
package instructions.)
</P>
<P>
   Stir-cook the rice and other ingredients 2 minutes. Stir in the
wine and cook at medium-high heat until most of the liquid is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Add a half-cup slurp of hot broth to the pan. When it is almost
all cooked away, add another half cup of broth containing the
saffron. When this is almost cooked away, add half cup more broth
and so on, until the rice is tender to the tooth. The cooking
process should last about 25 minutes and will keep you busy in the
kitchen while all the guests are clinking glasses, whooping and
hollering in the other room. Use just as much broth as you need to
achieve a creamy risotto. It should not be soupy.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the smoked chicken, and when it has had time to warm up,
stir in the butter and Parmesan, plus salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Burrard Beefsteaks
</P>
<P>
   2 steaks, about 1 inch thick
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon canola oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped shallots
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup red wine
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper the steaks. Heat the oil in a skillet, then
brown the steaks 4 minutes on each side for rare, 6 minutes on each
side for medium.
</P>
<P>
   Remove steaks from pan and pour off all but 1 tablespoon of oil.
Add the shallots and cook 1 minute. Stir in the wine and boil until
reduced by half. Blend in the butter and parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Return the steaks to the pan, turning once to coat with the
sauce, and serve immediately. Add a tossed salad with a blue cheese
dressing and you have a terrific dinner, whether it's served in
North Vancouver or West Seattle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
