<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-NCAA-MEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANA OVERCOMES FATIGUE AND SANTA CLARA FOR NCAA MEN'S TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ The play that decided the men's collegiate
soccer championship Sunday and brought Indiana University its
second consecutive title with a 1-0 triumph over Santa Clara was
originated and executed by Yuri Lavrinenko, a senior midfielder
from Ukraine, who had a little help from another Ukrainian, Aleksei
Korol.
</P>
<P>
   Lavrinenko started the play in the 30th minute with a marvelous
35-yard run down the left side. After dribbling with authority
around several players, he relayed the ball to Korol at the top of
the penalty area and kept on running.
</P>
<P>
   The diminutive Korol returned the pass, and Lavrinenko used the
outside of his right foot to slide the ball under Santa Clara
goalkeeper Rusty Johnson from 7 yards for the day's only goal
before 15,439 at Ericsson Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got the ball in midfield and I started dribbling,''
said Lavrinenko, the tournament's outstanding offensive player, ``I
was looking to pass right away. But my teammates opened up space
and I continued running. When I played the ball to Aleksei, two
players went to him and it opened up more space for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavrinenko's goal, his third of the tournament and seventh of
the season, caught Santa Clara's defense off guard during a
counterattack after Indiana gained possession in midfield. ``They
countered so quickly, and it was one of the few times our guys
didn't get in there,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Santa Clara was so well organized defensively they made it
very difficult to play against them,'' said Coach Jerry Yeagley,
who has led Indiana to five national titles in his 27 years as
coach of the Hoosiers. ``It's a credit to their players and ours,
who had the heart and perseverance to play like that after the
semifinals.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams were engaged in quadruple overtime in Friday night's
semifinals. It took Indiana 141 minutes 24 seconds to eliminate
UCLA by 3-2, and Santa Clara needed 138 minutes 50 seconds to
eliminate Connecticut by 2-1. The two teams were so physically and
mentally drained after the semifinals that fatigue was a factor
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Garcia, Indiana's junior sweeper, held up better than most.
He was solid throughout the match and had enough energy in the 70th
minute to clear the ball off his line with a desperation header
that nicked the crossbar and bounced away.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia was voted the tournament's outstanding defender for the
second year in a row, primarily because of that effort, and he was
the focus of questions afterward, not because of his heroics on the
field but because he declared that he would follow the professional
route and not return to Indiana for his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mitch Murray of Santa Clara (16-4-3) said his team had to
play its best to defeat Indiana, and it didn't. He credited
Indiana's defense for the victory. Indiana, he said, was
outstanding, but ``overphysical.''
</P>
<P>
   The referee, Brian Hall, issued four cautions (yellow cards),
none for blatant fouls, and Indiana (21-3-0) had three of them.
Murray acknowledged that ``there was no intention to hurt anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   By capturing the title for the second year in a row, the
Hoosiers joined St. Louis, San Francisco and Virginia as the only
teams to repeat. Virginia's four consecutive triumphs from 1991 to
1994 is a record that may never be matched.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
