<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FORDHAM-UCONN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPENSION OF FORDHAM PLAYER HELPS TO MAKE UCONN'S VICTORY EASIER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ Fordham, which may not even be the best college
team in the Bronx, went up against a Connecticut team Sunday that
is ranked sixth in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   What appeared to be a mismatch when the game was scheduled
became even more so when Fordham's best player, the junior guard
Bevon Robin, was suspended Sunday morning by Coach Bob Hill,
apparently for missing the team's curfew Saturday night. The
presence of Robin, the Rams' second-leading scorer and rebounder,
would probably not have changed the outcome of the game as
Connecticut (7-1) posted its seventh straight victory, by 94-75,
before a crowd of 10,027 at Gampel Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies scored the first 8 points and led by 25 in the first
half and 27 in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's interior defense forced Fordham (4-4) to to shoot
often from the perimeter. The Rams took 25 shots from 3-point range
but made only six, while shooting 37 percent against 56.5 percent
by the Huskies, who tried only eight 3-pointers and made one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had guys who were scared at the beginning,'' said Hill,
adding that UConn's size was ``a major factor.''
</P>
<P>
   If Fordham was off target from the perimeter, it was not much
better inside or in its transition game. The Rams, who have lost
three straight games after winning four in a row, managed only 28
points inside, as against 50 for Connecticut, and 9 second-chance
points compared with 20 for the Huskies. And Fordham made only 2
points off its fast break, while UConn scored 22.
</P>
<P>
   With Calhoun substituting often, 11 Huskies scored, led by
center Jake Voskuhl (16 points on 5-of-6 shooting and a team-high 8
rebounds) and forward Kevin Freeman (16 points). Guard Khalid
El-Amin scored 10 points on 4-of-9 shooting and dished off a
game-high eight assists.
</P>
<P>
   Robin's absence put an inordinate load on Fordham's other
outstanding guard and leading scorer this season, the 5-foot-9-inch
junior Jason Harris, and forced Hill to start the little-used Ray
Carroll. Harris, who averaged 20 points a game and connected on 29
of 67 3-point shots through the Rams' first seven games, made only
four of 15 field-goal attempts _ all of them from 3-point range _
and had a team-high 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   But as UConn Coach Jim Calhoun said: ``Harris tried to carry so
much himself. He's a terrific player, but he tried to do too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill, in his first year as the Fordham coach after coaching the
Knicks, the Indiana Pacers and the San Antonio Spurs in the
National Basketball Association, agreed with Calhoun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made a huge difference because, without Bevon, we had no
true point guard and were forced to play a halfcourt game, and
couldn't play the style of basketball we're accustomed to, which is
to run the court like UConn does,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the one-game suspension of Robin, who sat on the Rams'
bench in street clothes, Hill said, ``We have team rules and
everybody has to respect them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
