<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6776 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-KOSKINEN-PROFILE-ART-     12-12 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSKINEN-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREPARING FOR A DISASTROUS NEW YEAR'S EVE, JUST IN CASE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., N.C., Conn.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The special millennium bottle of Dom Perignon with the number
2000 stenciled on the back has already been drunk.
</P>
<P>
   The champagne bottle sits mournfully empty on the ledge over the
fireplace in John Koskinen's office, a reminder that when
Washington hurdles into the new year at midnight on Jan. 1, he will
not allow himself even a single festive sip of the bubbly.
</P>
<P>
   ``None for me,'' said Koskinen, who holds the formal title of
chairman of President Clinton's Council on Year 2000 Conversion but
is better known around the White House as Clinton's Y2K czar.
`'I'll be in the middle of all sorts of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   At 11:59 and 59 seconds on the night of Dec. 31, Koskinen says,
he will be stone sober and seated in a specially built glass-walled
war room in downtown Washington, where a staff of more than 100
will keep watch on the global changeover to a new year, a new
century, a new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be people at different desks gathering information
domestically and from around the world, and there will be a wall of
eight or 10 television screens,'' he said of the so-called
Information Coordination Center, speaking with almost giddy
enthusiasm about the drama that will unfold three weeks from now.
``It'll look like NASA, it'll look like the Defense Department.''
</P>
<P>
   The question for Koskinen is whether the world's major computer
systems can cope with the changeover.
</P>
<P>
   Because older computers were built to record years as only two
digits _ ``99'' for 1999, for example _ the fear is that many
computers will recognize ``00'' as the year 1900 instead of 2000,
creating the potential for disaster if computers controlling
utilities, banks and air-traffic control systems shut themselves
down.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen, the former deputy director for management at the
Office of Management and Budget, has been at work at the White
House since early last year to make sure disaster is avoided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are clearly going to be glitches,'' he said.
``But we're satisfied that the basic infrastructure in the United
States that people depend upon is going to work. We don't expect
any national failures or regional failures in banking,
telecommunications, oil and gas, transportation.''
</P>
<P>
   The bigger fear, he says, is what will happen overseas, in
developing nations with less sophisticated computer systems and
without the resources to update them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first concern everybody had _ I had, anyway _ was over
what would happen at Russian-designed nuclear plants,'' he said.
``There are 65 of them in Russia and elsewhere, and nobody knew
anything about them two years ago. We've spent a lot of time
focusing on it.'' By working with Russian nuclear and computer
experts, he said, ``I think we're satisfied now that no operating
system will fail for Y2K reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is disaster in the United States or elsewhere, the
coordination center will serve as an information clearinghouse for
the public, with Koskinen providing television briefings on the
federal response.
</P>
<P>
   This is the sort of assignment for which the 60-year-old
Yale-educated lawyer has been preparing all his life. Before
joining the budget office in 1994, Koskinen was known as one of the
nation's premier corporate crisis managers.
</P>
<P>
   A turnaround specialist who was hired to try to restructure
bankrupt companies, he worked for two decades for the Palmieri Co.,
perhaps the nation's best-known turnaround consultants, and helped
untangle the finances of such failed companies as the Penn Central
Railroad. He helped sell some of Penn Central's real estate in the
1970s to an exceptionally brash young businessman named Donald
Trump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, Donald, don't tell people you're 29, pretend
you're 35, because people don't want to lend $75 million to a
29-year-old,'' Koskinen said.
</P>
<P>
   He admits finding a certain pleasure in turmoil _ or, rather, in
bringing order from it. ``Running things in a maintenance mode is
just not interesting to me,'' he said. ``The reason I liked the
Palmieri Co. is that we were forever taking over disasters, crises,
things that were about to disappear. I've always enjoyed doing
things that looked impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   The grandson of Finnish immigrants on both sides of his family,
Koskinen was raised in Ashland, Ky., where his father worked at
Ashland Oil.
</P>
<P>
   The middle child of three _ his older sister is a retired social
worker, his younger brother an electrical technician _ Koskinen
went to Duke on scholarship and began a lifelong love affair with
the university. He has been chairman of Duke's board of trustees,
and the university's soccer stadium is named for him.
</P>
<P>
   He was a law clerk for David Bazelon, the legendary liberal
jurist who was chief judge of the U.S. Court of Appeals here, and
then joined the staff of the Kerner Commission, established by
President Lyndon Johnson to study the causes of urban racial
violence. He went on to become administrative aide to Sen. Abraham
Ribicoff, D-Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen, who normally enjoys the New Year's holiday with his
wife in Hawaii, will not have time even to dream of the tropics
this New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   His day, he says, will begin when he arrives at his office at 6
a.m., when New Zealand becomes the first large nation to cross into
the new year. ``From then on, we'll monitor the world as it goes
into 2000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:30 that night, Koskinen is scheduled to take a shuttle
flight to New York in a demonstration that the air-traffic control
system is Y2K ready. (The air traffic computer system is tied to
Greenwich Mean Time, which means that it will register midnight at
7 p.m.) He is set to return to Washington on the 8:30 p.m. shuttle,
in plenty of time to monitor the United States as it enters the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   He expects to remain on duty, providing regular televised
briefings, until 4 a.m., ``at which point they will have to wheel
me out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
