<SLUG> BC-CHILE-VOTE-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTION IN CHILE SEEN AS MEASURE OF SOCIAL CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ A former aide to the late Socialist president,
Salvador Allende Gossens, faced a former official in Gen. Augusto
Pinochet's dictatorship in Chile's presidential elections on
Sunday. The vote capped a yearlong campaign that has been
surprisingly free of tension or ideology, with both candidates
concentrating on practical solutions to everyday problems involving
crime, health care and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls have forecast that neither the Socialist-Christian
Democratic candidate, Ricardo Lagos, nor his main conservative
challenger, Joaquin Lavin, will be able to tally the outright
majority required to avert a runoff election next month, since the
four minor-party candidates together are expected to win more than
5 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   With 50 percent of the vote counted, Lagos led Lavine by 48.08
percent to 47.52 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was seen as a first test of whether an estimated 8
million Chilean voters are ready to rally behind the first serious
presidential contender who is a member of the Socialist Party since
Allende died in a 1973 coup, or elect a right-wing candidate as
president for the first time since Pinochet stepped down in 1990.
Christian Democratic presidents, in coalition with Socialists, have
led Chile since then.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates downplayed the early years of their careers in
more polarized times, and they ran on similar platforms in order to
attract moderate voters. Both promised to make job growth their No.
1 concern, expand public health care in rural areas and overhaul
the nation's police to stem rising crime.
</P>
<P>
   They even agreed on the most sensitive issue in Chilean politics
today: a Spanish judge's efforts to extradite Pinochet from
Britain, where he remains under house-arrest on allegations of
torture. Both candidates said they would continue the current
government's policy of contesting the extradition so that Pinochet
might face justice in the Chilean courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both candidates are exorcising the demons of the past,'' said
Lucia Santa Cruz, a historian. ``If Lavin wins, we will have an
alternation of government, which is an essential ingredient of
democracy. And if Lagos wins we will have a Socialist president who
hopefully will prove that Socialists can govern with political and
economic stability.''
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts were critical that neither candidate made
much of an effort to address several issues tied to the past, like
whether to start investigations of torture under the military
regime or to rewrite a constitution, prepared while Pinochet still
ruled, that gives the military several appointed senators and
independent powers over its budget and command structure.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos' slogan, ``Growth With Equality,'' and Lavin's slogan,
``Long Live Change,'' sound as if they belong to the same campaign.
But for all their similar proposals and caution, the 61-year-old
Lagos and the 46-year-old Lavin have offered the voters a contrast
in resumes and campaign styles.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer and economist, Lagos was Allende's candidate to become
ambassador to the Soviet Union at the time of the Pinochet coup.
But Lagos has preferred to emphasize his service as minister of
education and minister of public works in the two governments led
by Christian Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   He has promised to fill his Cabinet with many Christian
Democrats, who continue to form the largest party in Lagos'
coalition, in an effort to retain the support of more conservative
Christian Democrats who express fear that a Socialist president
could upset the country's stability.
</P>
<P>
   An engineer who studied economics at the University of Chicago,
Lavin worked in Pinochet's Planning Ministry. But he has preferred
to publicize his programs to control traffic congestion, control
gang activity and create charter schools in his seven years as
mayor of the Santiago community of Las Condes.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to stir an increasingly apolitical youth vote, Lavin has
run a tightly scripted, populist campaign that warms up crowds with
rap music, dueling drummers and clowns on stilts. He frequently
shuns hotels while touring the country, preferring to stay in
peoples' homes _ favoring recent victims of crime to emphasize his
interest in the issue.
</P>
<P>
   His most effective applause line is a promise that he will end
the policy of the last two Christian Democratic presidents of
blocking executions of convicted murderers, but otherwise he has
positioned himself as a liberal reformer.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At a campaign rally in Santiago last week, Lavin said his dream
was to see that the child of a poor Mapuche Indian standing on the
platform with him would have the same educational opportunities as
his seven children have had. ``I don't believe in a country that
pits the rich against the poor,'' he said, ``nor a country that
pits civilians against military officers nor a country that pits
businessmen against workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lagos has run a more traditional and, until the last few weeks,
a rather lackluster campaign that has exhibited difficulty in
parrying Lavin's liberal-sounding campaign without going too far to
the left itself.
</P>
<P>
   But Lagos' Christian Democratic-Socialist coalition appeared to
make an effective maneuver earlier this month when it brought a new
labor law to the floor of the Senate that would have given
collective bargaining rights to an additional 2.5 million workers.
When senators belonging to the two conservative parties backing
Lavin blocked the legislation, Lagos mocked Lavin's contention that
he is an agent of change who would uplift the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday the right took their covering off and showed whose
interests they really represent,'' Lagos said triumphantly at a
rally a week ago in the port of Valparaiso. ``The same right that
opposes the workers and who supported the dictatorship now are the
ones who call for change.'' He later added, ``When we speak of
equality it's not just a slogan, it's a principle we have fought
for all our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Just how far Chile has come in recent years could be seen Sunday
at the National Stadium, where the military gathered thousands of
leftists during the 1973 coup for torture, execution or forced
exile. On Sunday, conservatives, Socialists and even Communists
formed long, neat lines to vote _ without incident _ as military
police in fatigues looked on under a blazing sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our dreams of 30 years ago have had to change,'' said Nelson
Miranda, 44, an art teacher who said he voted for Lagos. ``Today we
Socialists are talking about taking the best from capitalism but
then better redistributing the wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Santana, 22, a marketing assistant at a public relations
firm, said he voted for Lavin because ``we need fewer words and
more action, change, new ideas and younger people in government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
