u s BC-FBN-REDSKINS-CARDS-NY     12-12 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REDSKINS-CARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDSKINS CONFUSE PLUMMER AND WIN PERHAPS THEIR BIGGEST GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ Arizona quarterback Jake Plummer had one of
those afternoons that make a head coach want to pull out his hair.
There were moments when Plummer was dazzling, running as if his
feet were on fire, throwing deep with that bionic arm. But those
moments were only a few.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time Plummer looked confused, throwing the ball into
double coverage or one-hopping passes off the grass. For a defense
that has been as popular around these parts as team owner Daniel
Snyder at a former Redskin employees' convention, Plummer picked a
particularly embarrassing time for his funk.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins were happy to oblige Plummer, intercepting him
three times. Washington's 30th-ranked defense was the main reason
the Redskins captured perhaps their biggest game of the season,
28-3, before 75,851 at Fed Ex Field.
</P>
<P>
   If Washington had lost, Snyder might have started poring over
his Rolodex, stopping at `C' for Dom Capers, the defensive
coordinator of the Jacksonville Jaguars and `S' for Schottenheimer,
the former Kansas City Chiefs coach, as possible replacements for
Coach Norv Turner, who is fighting for his job. The game was
crucial because Dallas beat Philadelphia, and the Redskins needed a
victory to stay ahead of the Cowboys and the Giants. A Washington
loss could have led to playoff extinction, and at the end of the
season Turner would have gone the way of the dodo bird.
</P>
<P>
   Now the National Football Conference East is realistically a
three-team race among Washington (8-5) and Dallas (7-6) and the
Giants (7-6). The Cowboys have the easiest schedule, with home
games against the Jets and Giants and a road game against sorry New
Orleans. The Redskins finish at Indianapolis and San Francisco and
then home against Miami, a game both teams might need to make the
playoffs. The Giants, in addition to the Cowboys game, play at St.
Louis and at home against Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play like we did today, you feel pretty good about
yourself,'' Turner said. ``Hopefully this win can carry us a long
way.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't all Washington's defense. The Redskins had 406 total
yards of offense. They were well balanced, with Stephen Davis
rushing for a career-high 189 yards on 37 attempts and Brad Johnson
throwing for two touchdowns and keying the Redskins' juicy 63
percent completion rate on third down.
</P>
<P>
   But the Redskins' defense, which all season has been picked
apart by opposing teams and ridiculed by the news media, finally
did well. Washington forced five Arizona turnovers, including a
crucial Adrian Murrell fumble late in the first half with
Washington ahead 14-6. The Cardinals did not have a first down in
the second half until near the two-minute warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to watch film and not be proud of some of the
things we did,'' Arizona wide receiver Frank Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason the Washington defense played so well was because of
a series of extraordinary meetings. Players on defense have been
privately complaining about the play calling by some of the
defensive coaches. This week Snyder stepped in to stop a potential
disaster. He met individually with team leaders Marco Coleman, Dana
Stubblefield, Tre Johnson and Irving Fryar, asking them to spread
the word to players that no one should worry about play calling and
instead just do what the coaches ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players need to be accountable to themselves, instead of
blaming things on the coaches _ that was the message,'' Fryar said.
</P>
<P>
   Then a small group of veterans called a players-only meeting on
Saturday, in which the message was that the team needed to become
more unified.
</P>
<P>
   Everything worked. After Davis ran for a spectacular 50-yard
touchdown, the Cardinals countered with a Chris Jacke 31-yard field
goal. That was all the sparing there would be.
</P>
<P>
   Washington scored on a Fryar 7-yard touchdown catch, a Michael
Westbrook 25-yard touchdown catch and an 11-yard Skip Hicks run.
The defense, meanwhile, strangled Plummer. They watched game film
of Plummer's final-second heroics last week against Philadelphia
and noticed that when he got outside the pocket, he was especially
dangerous. So they concentrated all week on containing the mobile
quarterback, and the extra effort paid off as he completed only 15
of 32 passes for 147 yards. He was also sacked five times.
</P>
<P>
   In the first nine contests, the Redskins gave up 27 points a
game but only 16 a game in the last four. The 3 points allowed
against Arizona are a season low.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to stand in there and deliver the ball, and I wasn't
doing that,'' Plummer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
