<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6791 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-FORBES-CAUCUSES-935(2     12-12 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-CAUCUSES-935(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES CAMPAIGN IS MAKING IOWA ITS TOP PRIORITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ In a convention hall filled with farm
families from every corner of Iowa, Steve Forbes recently came face
to face with George W. Bush and was treated to a vision of his
coming task in Iowa's caucuses next month.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever Bush went, cameras and flashes heralded his way, and
teen-age girls squealed with delight to be near him. A sea of John
Deere-green baseball hats labeled ``Bush Farm Team'' bobbed on
farmers' heads as they surged forward for autographs and a closer
look at Bush, the governor of Texas and the front-runner in the
race for the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In another corner at the Farm Bureau's annual meeting was
Forbes, the multimillionaire magazine publisher, with only a meager
crowd around him as he earnestly extolled the money-saving virtues
of his flat tax plan.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, when Kara Holtkamp of West Point, put one of the
Bush hats in Forbes' hands for an autograph, he gamely quipped:
``Bush will let you wear the green. I'll let you keep the green.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Bush's long shadow falls over the Forbes campaign
here, it is in Iowa, Forbes campaign strategists say, that they
feel they have the best chance of halting Bush's march toward his
party's nomination, and establishing Forbes as a viable
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the Forbes campaign is making Iowa its top
priority. Veteran political strategists, with years of experience
in local politics, are on Forbes' payroll. Television
advertisements that cost about $60,000 a week are filling the Iowa
airwaves. Grass-roots organizations have been set up in every
county and most of the state's precincts, complete with county farm
chairmen, anti-abortion captains and an assortment of other
volunteer leaders to round up Forbes supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Sophisticated direct mail and phone bank campaigns are under
way, stressing how Forbes' tax program will help farmers. And the
candidate himself has been hopping from one crossroads town to
another in a campaign bus that blares John Philip Sousa marches,
and wooing local voters by offering first-class food and drink.
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes campaign here sees itself as part of a one-two punch
to halt the front-runner: Forbes solidly challenging Bush in Iowa
and Sen. John McCain of Arizona closing in on Bush in New
Hampshire's first-in-the-nation primaries, to be held on Feb. 1,
one week after the Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   While no one _ even those in the Forbes camp _ expects Forbes to
win in Iowa, they are hoping to keep Bush's lead here as slim as
possible. McCain has avoided Iowa and is concentrating on New
Hampshire, where he and Bush are neck and neck in the polls and
Forbes remains a distant third.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain is banking on us in Iowa to hold Bush down,'' said
William Dal Col, the Forbes campaign manager. ``And we're banking
on him in New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   John Maxwell, the campaign's top pollster, said: ``Our Iowa
strategy is to show Forbes as a viable candidate and pierce the
veneer of inevitability of Bush. No one has ever gotten the
Republican nomination doing poorly both in Iowa and New Hampshire.
We're posing a serious threat to Bush in Iowa and McCain is in New
Hampshire. Bush cannot take a double hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes strategists are banking that their candidate's
conservative economic message _ reducing taxes and shrinking the
government _ will resonate with Iowa Republicans. But they are also
hoping to score big with a socially conservative message of family
values and opposition to abortion, much as Pat Robertson, the
religious broadcaster, did when he placed second in the caucuses in
1988, behind then-Sen. Bob Dole of neighboring Kansas, and as Pat
Buchanan did when he finished a strong second in 1996, behind Dole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forbes is trying to emerge as a religious conservative
alternative to Bush,'' said Dennis Goldford, head of the department
of politics at Drake University. ``In the Republican caucuses,
something like 40 percent of the voters can be social
conservatives, and Forbes has decided to bend that way. He has no
illusion he could beat Bush. But if he could soften him in Iowa and
McCain can deliver a punch, then people might start looking for
someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   To this end, the Forbes campaign has put the former head of the
Iowa Christian Coalition, Stephen Scheffler, on its Iowa payroll,
and Scheffler has lined up an array of Iowa anti-abortion leaders
who are telling social conservatives that Forbes is a more viable
candidate than Gary Bauer, who is also seeking votes from religious
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Audiotapes of Forbes' anti-abortion speech at the National
Christian Coalition convention are being sent to social
conservatives, along with a number of position papers and a
brochure called the ``Baby Mailer'' by local staff members because
of the photograph on the cover of this anti-abortion pamphlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced Forbes is a guy who can go the long haul, has a
message that is consistent and he's a winnable candidate,'' said
Scheffler. ``Social conservatives are convinced that he is for real
and won't get squishy with his pro-family agenda when he gets
elected.''
</P>
<P>
   In spending, organization and advertising, Forbes is going toe
to toe with Bush, just as he did in last August's Iowa straw poll,
when Forbes and Bush spent from $800,000 to $1 million each. Bush
came in first, with 31 percent of the nonbinding vote, and Forbes
finished second with 20 percent. The Forbes campaign would not say
how much Forbes, who is dipping into his $440 million fortune to
pay for his candidacy, has budgeted for the Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in a typical election that is settled at the ballot box,
victory in the Iowa caucuses often goes to the candidate with the
superior organization _ one that can deliver supporters to 2,142
local precincts for several hours of political debate with their
neighbors on a cold night in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to go out and get real people,'' said Dal Col, the
Forbes campaign manager. ``You've got to grab them and get them to
go out on a night that can be 20 to 30 degrees below zero, have
them fight for their candidates and then take a vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Grubbs, a Forbes campaign employee and former chairman of
the Iowa Republican Party, added, ``It's not like you have one big
battle; you have 2,000 little ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, about 100,000 Republicans _ roughly 20 percent of the
total in the state _ show up at the caucuses. In a multicandidate
field like the current one, the candidate who can get about 40,000
of those can win. In 1996, Dole won with 33,000 votes against
Buchanan, Lamar Alexander, the former governor of Tennessee, and
Forbes. Not only are the number of votes needed to win relatively
small, but victory is entirely symbolic _ they are not binding on
any Iowa delegate to the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   How Forbes is approaching his campaign in Iowa is markedly
different from his 1996 campaign, when he came in at the last
minute with a series of negative television advertisements
attacking Dole and had virtually no ground organization; Forbes
ended up placing fourth. In addition, his reputation here was
tarnished by the viciousness of his attacks on Dole, which only
succeeded in damaging Dole's image nationally and labeling Forbes
as a spoiler in his own party.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Forbes campaign here says, it has learned from
those mistakes. ``In 1996 we threw some ads up on the air, but we
didn't have a ground game,'' Grubbs said. ``This time we have a
ground organization second to none to compete with Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' broadcasting campaign consists of three television
advertisements promoting his own views and making subtle digs at
Bush, who has been criticized for his inexperience, especially in
foreign affairs. One commercial shows Forbes with Ronald Reagan,
highlights the candidate's ``three decades of experience'' and
``vast knowledge'' as publisher of the ``foremost business magazine
in the world,'' and maintains that Forbes' tenure at Radio Free
Europe ``helped play a role in the fall of Communism.''
</P>
<P>
   But will this all work? Iowa's five-term former Republican
governor, Terry Branstad, who is a Bush supporter, said that while
he believed that Bush had ``a broader base and wider public
support,'' Forbes was doing ``much better'' than in 1996: ``He's
got his bus tours, he's got his money, he's hired people who know
how to run an organization and he's spending the time here.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is clear that Forbes has his work cut out for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forbes seems mean-spirited,'' said Joshua Bronsink, a Des
Moines business consultant who attended a recent Chamber of
Commerce luncheon here where Bush talked about his tax plan. ``And
I'm against a lot of what he says socially. Forbes is not
electable, although I do think he will do well in Iowa. But, for
me, he's always tearing people down and he's never been elected to
anything before. That's why I'm for Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar concerns were expressed at the Farm Bureau meeting.
``I'm afraid people are tired of Forbes from last time around,''
said Don Wolhford, a Franklin County farmer. ``People don't think
he's electable, and they see Bush as a fresh face.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
