<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATE-PROCHAMPIONSHIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAR-OUT ARTISTRY OVERSHADOWS TECHNIQUE AT PRO CHAMPIONSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the Metabolife World Professional Figure
Skating Championships ended Saturday night at the MCI Center, Tara
Lipinski and Aleksei Urmanov had won the singles titles.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-year-old Lipinski, the American who won the women's gold
medal in the 1998 Olympics, skated a slow, dreamy program in which
her artistry overshadowed her technical achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Urmanov, the 1994 Olympic men's champion from Russia, mixed near
flawless skating with show-biz hype. He wore thigh-high boots, an
outrageous Russian-style jacket and a 16-foot cape and did
illusionist acts while skating. He seemingly turned a baton into a
kerchief and back again. He plucked a bouquet of flowers from
nowhere. He also did three triple jumps and a double axel.
</P>
<P>
   Urmanov was not alone in far-out costumes. Brian Boitano wore a
psychedelic shirt, bell-bottom trousers and little yellow glasses.
Ilya Kulik did a routine with a baseball cap. Even the women
combined untraditional programs with untraditional dress, notably
Tonia Kwiatkowski's Marilyn Monroe takeoff, complete with blond wig
and swinging hips.
</P>
<P>
   Such diversions are seldom seen in traditional competition for
amateurs, or, more accurately, for skaters eligible for the
Olympics. Which leads to some questions: Is professional figure
skating a real sport, entertainment, or both? And if it is a sport,
is it the same sport as amateur skating?
</P>
<P>
   The questions were put Sunday to Dick Button, a 1948 and 1952
Olympic champion, who is admittedly biased. While Button's candid
analysis for ABC has helped popularize the amateur sport, he is
also the founder, owner and major domo of the pro championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Professional skating is quite different,'' he said, ``maybe
not a different sport, but a different aesthetic, a different
agenda. We recognize there are two different aspects of skating:
aesthetics and artistry. Professional skating has some of both.''
</P>
<P>
   Button added: ``In the amateur world, they count your triple
jumps, and if you don't do enough they forget about your other
skating. We do not make our competitors prove their merit. We let
them present creative programs with as many or as few triple jumps
as they wish. And we take only the best skaters in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Or at least the best available. The best female skater in the
world is probably Michelle Kwan, the American who won this title
last year when the International Skating Union, the world governing
body for amateur figure and speed skating, allowed amateurs to
compete. She could not compete here this year because she is
technically an amateur, albeit an amateur who earns an annual
seven-figure income from skating.
</P>
<P>
   If Kwan and other amateurs were judged here under amateur rules,
they would probably dominate. Boitano, who has won this title six
times, boycotted last year because he thought it would be unfair
for him to have to compete against amateurs doing essentially
technical rather than show programs.
</P>
<P>
   The public seems to like pro skating's mix of athleticism and
entertainment. Ice-show tours bring $1 million or more to such
stars as Lipinski, Kristi Yamaguchi and Scott Hamilton.
Competitions such as the pro championships give pro skating
visibility because television thrives on figure skating and its
high ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Although pros receive scores from judges, they essentially skate
for the crowds. The pros like their version of the sport and insist
they are still athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel that much different,'' Lipinski said. ``I still
train every day. I take only one week of vacation a year. When I
compete, I'm not as nervous as I was in the Olympics, but I'm still
nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Boitano put it best when he said: ``The job of amateurs
is to jump. Our job is to jump and entertain.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
