<DOCNO> NYT19991212.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6800 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-EAGLES-HN     12-12 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-EAGLES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
IRVING _ The playoff picture didn't get much clearer Sunday, but at
least Dallas stayed in it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Needing a win to stay close in the NFC East, the Cowboys had
little trouble defeating the hapless Philadelphia Eagles 20-10 to
stay one game behind Washington in the race for the division crown.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants (7-6), who defeated Buffalo, remain tied with Dallas
(7-6) for second place. The Redskins (8-5) knocked off Arizona
(6-7) to dim the Cardinals' hopes of a repeat trip to the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   There was no celebrating in the Cowboys' locker room, just a
sense of guarded optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have to win the next three,'' Dallas safety Darren
Woodson said. ``We have to come back out next week and play well,
and then the next two after that. It's four wins, or we stay home.
That's the way we're looking at it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a victory on both sides of the ball, with the Cowboys'
offense scoring a pair of touchdowns for the first time since
hosting Green Bay last month. In the three games since, the offense
had been nearly nonexistent, scoring only one touchdown during an
11-quarter period.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas defense, which has played well most of the season,
held its opponent to less than 14 points for the fifth straight
time and the ninth in 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they understood our mission,'' Dallas coach Chan
Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   The cost, however, was as high as the net gain Sunday. Before
the first quarter had ended, the Cowboys had lost running back
Emmitt Smith to a strained left groin, defensive end Greg Ellis to
a fractured left tibia, and cornerback Kevin Mathis to a strained
left knee. Center Mark Stepnoski later left after aggravating his
left calf strain.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis' injury ended his season, and the second-year player
underwent surgery after the game. The other players will be
re-evaluated today.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start feeling snakebit, you start feeling sorry for
yourself, and that doesn't do anyone any good,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys made some changes on offense Sunday, putting Deion
Sanders into the game plan and signing Eddie Murray off the Detroit
Lions' broadcast team to replace fired kicker Richie Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   Both contributed, but neither was the hero.
</P>
<P>
   The heroes were the guys who generally spend more time on the
bench than on the field but who had healthy bodies and were pressed
into duty. Chris Warren, running for the injured Smith, carried 25
times for 92 yards. He skirted four yards untouched into the end
zone in the first quarter to score Dallas' initial touchdown,
giving the Cowboys a 7-3 lead with 4:49 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   First-year receiver Jason Tucker finished the day with three
catches for 37 yards. Chris Brazzell, recently elevated from the
practice squad, caught a big pass for 12 yards. And tight ends
David LaFleur and Eric Bjornson combined for six catches for 69
yards. LaFleur was on the receiving end of a an eight-yard
touchdown pass in the third period that put Dallas on top 20-3.
</P>
<P>
   Eight Cowboys caught passes as quarterback Troy Aikman completed
22 of 40 attempts, including several long gainers. He hit Rocket
Ismail with a 26-yarder, LaFleur with a 25-yarder, Warren with a
24-yarder and Tucker with a 19-yarder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like the guys we are playing with because they are
doing what they can to help us,'' Aikman said. ``I have confidence
in these guys, but I need more playing time with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders caught a pair of passes for 14 yards, one to convert a
third down. But his largest contribution won't show up in the
statistics. When Sanders was on offense, the Eagles were forced to
commit two defenders to his side, opening things up for leading
receiver Ismail (four catches for 52 yards) and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he even steps on the field, they have to account for where
he's at,'' LaFleur said.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders expects to see more time on offense in upcoming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to incorporate me more and more,'' he said.
``They didn't want to overload me to make sure I didn't blow my
hamstring and groin out.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray proved a so-so substitute for Cunningham, connecting on
field goals of 30 and 34 yards in the second quarter. He missed two
other attempts _ a 49-yard try to cap the Cowboys' first drive
bounced off the right upright, and a 33-yard try early in the
fourth quarter went wide right.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just like anybody else. He needs to get out there and
play,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys moved the ball much better than in recent weeks,
amassing 337 total yards, the most since the Nov. 14 Green Bay
game, when they had 339. Aikman, who has failed to throw for 200
yards in six of his 10 starts, threw for 242, the most since he
amassed 244 against Washington in the sixth game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're improved,'' Gailey said, ``but we're not where we need
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to get too excited over the offensive improvement,
considering it came against a 3-10 team with the 23rd-worst defense
in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to know how much the team progresses from one
week to the next,'' Aikman said. ``I don't know if we did. I don't
know if we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense has clearly gotten better each week, and on Sunday
it contained Philadelphia rookie quarterback Donovan McNabb, who
escaped the pocket only three times to scramble for 24 yards.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb completed seven of 17 passes for 49 yards before leaving
the game in the fourth quarter with a knee sprain. Doug Pederson,
who led the Eagles to a 13-10 victory when the teams first met this
year, completed eight of 12 passes for 108 yards and one touchdown
late.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas defense limited the Eagles to 233 yards total
offense, 90 on the ground. The Cowboys didn't allow a touchdown
until 6:41 remained and the game was pretty much out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense is playing wonderful football,'' Sanders said.
``Those guys did a wonderful job of stepping up when Greg went
down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys next host the New York Jets. They wrap up the season
with a road trip to New Orleans, followed by a home game against
the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go into that locker room right now, it's not a sense of
jubilation or anything,'' Gailey said. ``Guys know where we are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-99 2010EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
