<SLUG> BC-CROATIA-POLITICS-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUGH GRIEVING FOR TUDJMAN, MANY CROATS WANT CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAGREB, Croatia _ Anka Sedarevic became breathless while
expressing her respect and devotion to President Franjo Tudjman,
who died Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Sedarevic, 72, was taking a free bus to join a line of
several thousand people who waited up to three hours to file past
Tudjman's coffin and to write a few words in a fat book of
remembrance. ``He gave us our Croatia, and we waited for it a very
long time,'' she said. ``He lived and died for Croatia.''
</P>
<P>
   Tudjman founded an independent Croatia in 1991 from the remains
of the Communist Yugoslavia he helped to destroy. In August 1995
his troops drove out many of the Serbs who lived in Croatia and
opposed independence, especially in the Krajina region in southwest
Croatia, around Knin.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for her strongest memory of Tudjman, Mrs. Sedarevic said
it was ``when he kissed the flag on the Knin fort, and his happy
face.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Sedarevic says she intends to vote for the opposition
in coming parliamentary elections on Jan. 3, spurning Tudjman's
governing party, the Croatian Democratic Union, known as the HDZ.
``I won't vote for them,'' she said with nearly equal fervor. ``I'm
voting for the opposition. It's time for change.''
</P>
<P>
   Unhappiness with a wretched economy, high taxes, late pension
and salary payments and widespread corruption has undermined
support for the governing party, even from those who devoted their
Sunday morning to standing in the chill to honor Tudjman.
</P>
<P>
   A six-party opposition coalition is expected to win the
elections. That would mark the first peaceful change of authority
here, despite the governing party's firm control over the state
media.
</P>
<P>
   Together with the peaceful transition under way in Macedonia,
another former Yugoslav republic, with the election of a new
president, the shift in Croatia could help to persuade a weaker
democratic opposition in Serbia to surmount its own bitter
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia's governing party is thought to be particularly strong
among the elderly. But Ankica Bojic, too, wants an opposition
victory. With curly gray hair and large glasses, Mrs. Bojic, 65, a
retired textile worker, said that Tudjman's party had made ``many
mistakes,'' and that ``older people still feel like we live in the
old Yugoslavia, with bad pensions, and we're not so enchanted by
all this.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Bojic, with her granddaughter, Iva Bojic, 14, waited
for hours to pass by Tudjman's coffin. ``He was our first president
and he made our state,'' Mrs. Bojic said. ``We don't want to have
Serbs in Yugoslavia over our heads. So I went up there to pay my
respects.''
</P>
<P>
   Iva said she waited for three hours to have a minute inside the
presidential palace, where Tudjman lay surrounded by flags,
flowers, an honor guard and the many medals he had awarded himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I went, but I'm freezing,'' she said. She wants to be
an actress and go abroad, to make money, she said, wondering how to
find a pen pal on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Did she write something in the book of remembrance? Iva,
embarrassed, said she had. ``I wrote that `you did a lot for us and
I'm very grateful,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bojic simply wrote her name. ``I want life to be better for
the young people,'' she said. ``They will have a better chance with
the opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps 20,000 Croatians had filed by Tudjman's coffin by
evening, officials said. He will be buried Monday after a state
funeral in Mirogoj Cemetery in Zagreb, led by Archbishop Josip
Bozanic, the country's Roman Catholic primate, who in the past has
used key sermons to speak out against the poverty and inequalities
that came to characterize Tudjman's era.
</P>
<P>
   Church bells will toll for 10 minutes throughout the country,
and there will be an official Mass in Zagreb Cathedral in the early
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Three days of official mourning, with sports and entertainment
events canceled and movie theaters closed, will end Monday at
midnight, and official campaigning for the new Parliament will
probably begin Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A new president must be elected within 60 days, but the parties
have not yet selected their candidates. Foreign Minister Mate
Granic is one of the favorites, but he is considered a moderate in
the governing party, and the powerful deputy speaker of Parliament,
Vladimir Seks, a hard-line nationalist, is also likely to be a
contender.
</P>
<P>
   Tudjman's funeral will bring many foreign dignitaries here, but
the level of representation is likely to disappoint the government.
The prime ministers of Turkey and Hungary will attend, as well as
high officials from neighboring countries. But the United States,
which in recent years has had strained relations with Tudjman's
government, will be represented only by its ambassador, William
Montgomery.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Only last week, the United States and Montgomery were sharply
attacked here by state-controlled newspapers and television, which
accused them of coordinating intelligence activities and
nongovernmental organizations to try to bring down the governing
party.
</P>
<P>
   In language reminiscent of that of President Slobodan Milosevic
in Serbia, the Croatian media accused Washington of financing and
instructing the political opposition here, implying that the
opposition was disloyal to the state.
</P>
<P>
   American officials are convinced that Croatian intelligence
services regularly bug their conversations and are responsible for
break-ins at two apartments used by diplomats, although no
listening devices have been found.
</P>
<P>
   Andrija Artukovic, 69, said he had been waiting for more than
two hours to pay his respects to the late president. ``It's not
hard for me to wait for Tudjman,'' he said simply. ``This was our
first president, and I'm very thankful to him. He made this country
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Artukovic said he was jailed in 1951, at the age of 20, ``only
for being a Croat.'' He was in the Yugoslav Army, based in
Macedonia, and said he had been jailed for ``propaganda against
Tito, because I didn't perform my devotions to the president as I
should.''
</P>
<P>
   He then left the country and his family to work in Germany, as a
mechanic in a Porsche factory, and returned here to live in 1992.
``I couldn't have come back sooner,'' he said. ``They might have
arrested me again. So I waited for an independent Croatia.''
</P>
<P>
   And will he vote for the opposition? Artukovic said he would.
``President Tudjman made this country for us,'' he said. Still, he
added, ``There can't be a democracy without an opposition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
