<HEADLINE>
TV WEEK AHEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
TODAY 
J'ville has never lost on ``Monday Night Football'' _ 4-0 over the
past three years _ and shouldn't expect to again. Some will say
this is the old Super Bowl champs ushering in the new. Let's not
get carried away. NFL: Denver at Jacksonville, Channel 7, 6 p.m. 
TUESDAY 
Don't know if the NBA record books indicate such a thing, but we
gotta think the Clippers will be the first to play as a visitor at
their home arena. NBA: Clippers at Lakers, Fox Sports Net and
Channel 9, 7:30 p.m. 
WEDNESDAY 
When it comes to throwing a Super Bowl party, the inmates at
California State Prison in Lancaster aren't going to make it so
loud that the cops come. But they do have a regular celebration.
They splurge on food and hoard their money to lay down some bets.
Then they gather around the TV set. It's something to see during
the latest ESPN ``Outside The Lines'' episode on sports and the
prison system, hosted by actor Charles S. Dutton _ who served
nearly a decade in prison for manslaughter. At least watch to see
if you spot any friends in the background. ``Outside the Lines:
Sports Behind Bars,'' ESPN, 4 p.m. (replays Friday at midnight) 
THURSDAY 
Late night at the Pyramid for East Coast hoop-a-holics who need a
reason to stay up past midnight. NCAA basketball: USC at Long Beach
State, ESPN, 9 p.m. 
FRIDAY 
At what point does Roy Firestone decide he's got enough clips for a
``best of'' show and shelve the part when he sings a few show tunes
over a videoclip montage? And if Larry King can get the guy
formerly known as Prince, how will ``Mr. Saturday Afternoon'' top
that? ``Up Close: Highlights of Roy Firestone's 1999 interviews,''
ESPN, 6 p.m. 
SATURDAY 
The bowl season begins in the city where they can't even bet on the
contest and Mike Tyson's ferrets are just glad to be alive. Las
Vegas Bowl: Utah vs. Fresno State, ESPN, 3 p.m. 
SUNDAY 
Just a reminder: Last Sunday to shop before Dec. 25. Don't let
these events keep you glued to the screen. NBA: Lakers at Toronto,
Channel 9, noon; NFL: Buffalo at Arizona, ESPN, 5:15 p.m. 

