<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-BILLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS' COLLINS OUTPLAYS FLUTIE AND DOES SOME CHEERLEADING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. _ It was almost comical around the Giants
last week, with the cavalcade of injuries on the defense melding
with the aura of Doug Flutie to create a sense of invincibility
about the Bills _ and a sense of doom for the Giants, who had to
play them.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing they were given no shot in Sunday's game, the Giants
eagerly played along, engaging in gallows humor about their
predicament. But as the week went on, most Giants quietly concluded
something quite different: This was a game they could steal.
</P>
<P>
   So with 2 minutes 9 seconds left in the final quarter Sunday,
when Giants quarterback Kerry Collins entered the team's huddle and
screamed, ``We're going to win this game,'' there was no surprise
among his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   And 53 seconds later, when the Giants needed at least five more
yards to attempt what would become the game-winning field goal,
Collins did not wrangle with the assistant coach Sean Payton, who
was fretting over what play to call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dude, just call it,'' Collins told Payton. ``We'll get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a 5-yard pass from Collins to Pete Mitchell followed and
soon Cary Blanchard's 48-yard field goal was spinning through the
uprights, the final act in a stirring, unforeseen 19-17 Giants
victory over the Bills at Ralph Wilson Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, who only two weeks ago were the losers of three
straight and on the verge of coming apart at the seams, have a
winning record at 7-6, still have not lost a regular-season game in
December under Coach Jim Fassel and are again legitimate playoff
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We proved that last week's win over the Jets wasn't a fluke,''
said Collins, who had another sparkling day, outplaying Flutie as
he led the Giants on five scoring drives. ``We never thought it was
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants defense, playing without the starting cornerbacks
Jason Sehorn and Phillippi Sparks, held the Bills' offense to only
237 yards and essentially one touchdown. Buffalo's second
touchdown, which gave it a 17-16 fourth-quarter lead, was a 2-yard
run by Jonathan Linton, but it was set up by a 52-yard interception
return of a deflected Collins pass by Buffalo tackle Marcellus
Wiley.
</P>
<P>
   The field day most anticipated Flutie to have against the
reserve cornerbacks Emmanuel McDaniel and Jeremy Lincoln never
materialized. On the first Bills play, Flutie threw 36 yards down
the sideline to Eric Moulds, with McDaniel in tow.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be the high-water mark for the Bills' passing
attack as they never completed another pass of that length or
longer. Fittingly, a desperation pass on the game's final play by
Flutie, who completed 15 of 32 passes for 184 yards, was
intercepted by Bashir Levingston.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants used the offensive formula that worked a week ago,
with Joe Montgomery running for 77 yards and Collins completing 23
of 44 passes to five receivers and 240 passing yards.
</P>
<P>
   Still it was a seesaw, absorbing game, with Blanchard making
three field goals before his game-winner as the Giants came from
behind three times. When the Bills went up by 3-0, the Giants
rallied to take a 6-3 lead. When Buffalo led by 10-6, Collins led
the Giants on a 10-play drive in the final two minutes before
halftime, connecting with Amani Toomer for a precisely timed, crisp
14-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were aided by Bills kicker Steve Christie, usually
one of the National Football League's best, who missed field goals
from 39 and 48 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Bills had a 1-point lead and the ball at the Giants'
36-yard line with slightly more than two minutes to play. Ninety
seconds earlier, Flutie seemed to have won the game, scrambling for
12 yards on a third-and-9 when four different Giants could not
catch him on a zany dash back and forth across the field. Facing a
fourth-and-1, Coach Wade Phillips chose to go for it.
</P>
<P>
   If that proved to be the wrong decision, it was made worse by
the play called, which was a simple dive up the middle by Linton.
Defensive tackle Keith Hamilton met Linton in the backfield,
grabbing his legs. Safety Sam Garnes vaulted over the top to
complete the job _ a telling stop on a day when the Giants held the
Bills to only 76 yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Collins was trotting into the huddle, yelling at his
teammates, something he later said he did not remember doing.
Collins, however, spent the rest of the drive calmly leading the
Giants downfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kerry is very confident in those situations,'' running back
Tiki Barber said. ``It makes us all believe in him.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Barber who made probably the biggest play in the drive.
Facing a third-and-15 at their 49, the Giants called a trick screen
play: They faked a screen to the left, and when the linebacker
assigned to cover Barber drifted to that area, Barber cut back to
the middle of the field, where Collins found him with a pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it a man beater,'' said Barber, who talked Payton into
running the play with a one-back formation because he knew it meant
he would face man-to-man coverage. ``I was killing the linebacker
all day. I told them I can beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   Barber, who caught eight passes, was referring to linebacker
Marlo Perry, whom he did run past as he broke free over the middle.
With a burst of speed that was missing last year, Barber sprinted
to a 15-yard gain before Buffalo's defense collapsed on him at the
Bills' 36.
</P>
<P>
   Two incomplete passes under pressure left the Giants with a
third-and-10. Before the game, Fassel had decided the line of
scrimmage would have to be the 30-yard line for him to allow
Blanchard to attempt a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we had to at least move it up 5 or 6 yards,'' Collins
said.
</P>
<P>
   Payton called a play with several options but Collins, who would
roll to his right, knew he would look first for Mitchell, his best
third-down option.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just give me time,'' Collins said to his lineman as he clapped
his hands to exit the huddle. And the Giants' line protected
Collins, who was not sacked in the game.
</P>
<P>
   It became a 5-yard pass play to Mitchell, enough to advance the
ball to the 31-yard line. Close enough, Fassel said, and sent
Blanchard in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought about doing anything else,'' Fassel later
said.
</P>
<P>
   Blanchard, who has yet to miss an important field goal since he
was signed Oct. 20 to replace the injured Brad Daluiso, made the
field goal with a little right-to-left draw that split the goal
posts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a significant win,'' said Fassel, who like many of his
players was at ease last week and impishly confident. ``That was a
statement.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-99 2033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
