<DOCNO> NYT19991212.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6819 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     12-12 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IRVING _ Emmitt Smith was the lucky one. He got to pull his groin
after the first play and leave.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody else had to stay for the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   Head coach Chan Gailey said they are a team on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Troy Aikman said they were taking care of business.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you've been following the Cowboys at all through
this meandering season, you know those two descriptions are
actually one and the same.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to require a mission or a sense of impending doom for
the Cowboys to take care of their business, and so a 20-10 victory
over the punchless Eagles is regarded as a feat akin to those early
solo flights across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a game that we needed to win,'' said Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great team victory over a very good football
team,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Which only says that when it comes to getting fixed up on a
blind date, you'd be better served by relying on the eye and the
taste of the QB over the coach.
</P>
<P>
   What the Cowboys accomplished Sunday was the equivalent of not
falling down at the start of a marathon and getting stomped on by
so many thousands of feet.
</P>
<P>
   For there are still three games left in the regular season, and
so many things can happen, almost none of them good if Dallas
doesn't win out and grab the NFC East title.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, with a remaining schedule that is currently weaker
than Charles Barkley's left knee _ home against the Jets, at New
Orleans, home against the Giants _ anything less than winning out
to finish at 10-6, and the Cowboys would be deserving of any bad
hand fate might deal them in the so-called playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, anything less than a division title, and Dallas
could be looking at an offseason of changes in high places. Namely,
the head coach's spot, which may be why Gailey was ready to make a
grand pronouncement after one in a row.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the season, Gailey has listened to the criticism of
his passive offensive philosophy and responded by serving up just
more helpings of an attack that would make day-old oatmeal look
exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, though, with the season still teetering on the brink at
6-6, Gailey finally took off the wraps, and the result was the kind
of production that does not make a team feel like it should back up
to the pay window.
</P>
<P>
   Here was a Cowboys team going all but one play without its
workhorse Smith and never losing its gallop. Chris Warren filled
the hole, running for 92 yards and a touchdown on 25 carries.
</P>
<P>
   What's more impressive _ and what could portend good things
coming down the stretch _ was a willingness to open up the offense,
going down the field for longer passes and spreading the ball
around to eight receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman has spent much of a morose season complaining that he is
not at all comfortable with his receiving corps, that he
appreciates the deep threat provided by Rocket Ismail but misses
his old buddy Michael Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   So Gailey finally turns him loose to throw 40 passes, gets
Aikman in position to roll out and away from pressure frequently,
and suddenly he's as comfortable as if sitting in a La-Z-Boy.
Everyone from Ismail to David LaFleur to Warren to Jason Tucker to
Eric Bjornson caught passes that gained at least 16 yards, and the
Cowboys looked like the aggressors rather than part of the scenery.
</P>
<P>
   LaFleur, the third-year tight end who was supposed to be a big
weapon, finally looked the part, hauling in four balls for 44 yards
and a TD. Deion Sanders jumped over to offense for more than a
handful of plays and caught just two passes. But his mere presence
on the field attracted the attention of the Eagles' defense and
opened opportunities for others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can do more, and I'm sure I will,'' said Prime Time.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' defense, which has propped up the team for most of
the year, suffered two significant hits when Greg Ellis went down
with a broken left leg and Kevin Mathis sprained his left knee, but
it still managed to pick off one Donovan McNabb pass and recover
two fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   All of which made for a drab, routine win over a 3-10 team in a
season when there has been no reason for anyone to fear the Cowboys
or regard them as real contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't put together back-to-back victories since we
started 3-0,'' said Aikman. ``At 7-6, it's a little early to be
talking Super Bowl or anything like that. What we have to do is
beat the Jets, beat New Orleans, beat the Giants and see where we
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to know how much the team has progressed
week-to-week. I don't know if we did or we didn't. We won.''
</P>
<P>
   And there hasn't been enough of that to say much else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-99 2033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
