<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHT ON CYBERSQUATTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A week after the new Anticybersquatting Consumer
Protection Act was signed by President Clinton, which will fine
people who register the domain names of people without their
consent, the NFL is one of the first to test it.
</P>
<P>
   The league filed a suit last Wednesday in U.S. District Court in
New York against an Internet site operator for extensive
unauthorized use of NFL and team trademark names. Ken Miller of
Clearlake Park, Calif., has sites identified under URLs as
NFLtoday.com, NFLtoday.net and NFLtoday.org, which promote gambling
on NFL games.
</P>
<P>
   Miller told the Associated Press the NFL had offered him $270
for the names, and he countered with $120,000.
</P>
<P>
   Another suit was filed by Quokka Sports on behalf of the New
Zealand America's Cup yachting team because it wants to use the URL
americascup.com, owned by two New Zealand men. A temporary
injunction has been granted.
</P>
<P>
   __The NFL's official site for the Super Bowl (www.superbowl.com)
has already gone up. On game day, the Enhanced TV that ABC and ESPN
has used on their prime-time package also will be available; the
Jan. 30 contest is on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   __Did you know: The Cincinnati Bengals are the only ones left of
118 major pro teams (taking those from the NFL, MLB, NBA, NHL, WNBA
and MLS) that don't have their own Web site, according to the Wall
Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Even the yet-to-field-a-team L.A. Avengers of the Arena Football
League have a site (www.laavengers.com), which has info about a
tryout camp at the Coliseum on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   __Collectible find of the holiday season: Eight relay batons
used in the 1996 Olympic Games in Atlanta, with a letter of
authenticity, are for sale for $995 on Vaultstuff.com. There's only
one set available.
</P>
</TEXT>
