<DOCNO> NYT19991212.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6824 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PLANE-MAINTENANCE-2TA     12-12 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANE-MAINTENANCE-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG, BIG JOB OF MAINTAINING A BOEING 737 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Sitting on huge steel jacks in a maintenance
hangar here, the big, gray Boeing 737, tail No. N-1383, was in for
some serious work.
</P>
<P>
   A floor beam under the aft galley was rusting; the steel tracks
that guide the wing flaps were wearing out, and engineers suspected
that the cargo doors were developing hidden cracks. The plane's
maintenance report over the past month formed a computer printout
about 15 feet long, and the Federal Aviation Administration, in
response to airplane crashes, had demanded that United Airlines,
the plane's operator, install a better flight data recorder and a
firefighting system in the cargo holds, among other changes. In
all, the plane needed about 50 changes, plus extensive routine
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   The situation seemed to prove the aviation adage that a plane is
a collection of spare parts flying in close formation. But
Frederick Mohr, managing director of United Airlines' maintenance
center here, called N-1383 a ``pretty good airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   Passenger jets like N-1383 usually get close public scrutiny
only after fatal accidents. At that point, every broken part they
ever flew with, every flaw that was waiting to be corrected, every
malady that any plane of that type ever experienced, takes on an
ominous aura.
</P>
<P>
   But the everyday reality for planes like N-1383, which is based
at United's San Francisco hub and makes short flights around
California, is far different. With hundreds of thousands of parts,
multiple redundant systems, elaborate monitoring systems and a
strict maintenance regimen, the plane is almost always available,
able to safely carry 126 passengers in coach and eight in first
class, and even safely sustain a variety of part failures in
flight.
</P>
<P>
   The plane almost always needs work, however. Today was ``day
three of 19,'' as described by Robert Corriveau, the team leader
for the hangar section where 215 mechanics were stripping pieces
off the plane, like insects on the carcass of a giant bird.
</P>
<P>
   In its 10-year lifetime, in 30,166 hours of flight, the plane
has never had an engine fail or had to be shut down in flight, and
if it is a typical United plane _ the airline's engines are more
reliable than most others _ it will not have that problem for years
to come. In 20,080 flights, it has never had to return to an
airport or divert on the way to a destination because of a
mechanical problem.
</P>
<P>
   The airline has had to report to the FAA on problems involving
N-1383 on three occasions, all relatively minor incidents involving
lights that were not working correctly. One involved floor lighting
for emergency escapes, another the light on an emergency exit
slide, and the third an indicator light that flickered instead of
correctly showing whether the plane's wing slats were retracted in
flight. The pilot had to look out of a window of the passenger
cabin to see that the slats were functioning properly.
</P>
<P>
   But the history of airline crashes is, in a way, carved into the
hardware of this airplane. For example, in May 1996, a ValuJet DC-9
took off with improperly packed hazardous cargo that caught fire,
causing the plane to crash. On this visit, N-1383 was having smoke
detectors and fire-suppression systems installed in its forward and
aft cargo holds.
</P>
<P>
   The inspection itself is partly a result of an incident in which
the roof peeled away in flight on an Aloha Airlines 737 in April
1988. (The plane landed safely.) Some of the flaws found are not
easily detected. A worker examined the floor beam, for example,
with a mirror only a little bigger than the one a dentist might
use.
</P>
<P>
   N-1383 has been inspected and modified several times because of
the discovery of flaws in fuel tank wiring in other 737s, in
inspections brought on by the explosion of the TWA 747, Flight 800,
after it took off from Kennedy Airport in New York in July 1996. In
the recent maintenance visit, workers were checking the connections
that prevent static charges from building up in the tanks.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1994, a USAir 737 crashed near Pittsburgh, and
determining the cause took more than three years, partly because
the plane's flight data recorder had been an early model. N-1383
was getting an updated version.
</P>
<P>
   The new flight data recorder is a good example of the difference
between minimum requirements and what United considers good
maintenance. The original flight data recorder captured 16
categories of information; the FAA, after much debate, is requiring
22, but the one United is installing will capture 36.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft is also getting a computer, the ``enhanced ground
proximity warning system,'' that compares the plane's course to an
electronic map and warns against flying too low. That is a result
of the 1995 crash of an American Airlines plane in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   And the plane is getting a new weather radar that can detect
windshear, the sudden shift from a headwind to a tailwind, which is
the cause of many accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Forty of the 50 changes in the maintenance visit are voluntary,
most of them recommended by Boeing, others by United. For example,
an internal report on the reliability of its 737 fleet, made
available by the company, shows that part of the system for
measuring fuel quantity tends to show signs of wear between 31,000
and 34,000 flight hours. The problem has caused an average of one
flight cancellation every two months among the airline's 182 737s.
United will soon begin replacing the parts.
</P>
<P>
   From a bolt on a landing gear that tends to crack because of
corrosion, causing delays, to unreliable seals on a refrigerator in
the galley, the list of changes goes on and on.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But these are only the changes made in heavy maintenance. The
service report for the plane over the last month is a secession of
burned-out light bulbs or other small problems. The plane has six
wheels, and has had four tire replacements in the last month. One
tire was replaced twice.
</P>
<P>
   Over and over, maintenance officials say that safety is their
top priority. But it was clear that many of the changes would be
reliability problems long before they would be safety problems. For
example, United was doing preventive maintenance of tracks that
hold the plane's flaps in place, to prevent eventual vibrations
that have occurred on other planes.
</P>
<P>
   The engineering staff evaluates a constant flow of service
problems from the field, and ``service bulletins'' from Boeing
recommending changes, as well as from the manufacturers of the
engines and other components. On a plane like the 737, the service
bulletins can reach 1,000 a year. Airlines like United will take
action on most of the recommendations. The aviation agency will
focus on a handful and make them mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   United's aim is to complete action on the suggestions in the
safety-related bulletins long before the agency mandates them,
which can take years. Sometimes this backfires.
</P>
<P>
   For example, after the National Transportation Safety Board said
that the USAir crash in Pittsburgh showed a problem with the
hydraulic unit in the rudder, United replaced the unit in its 737s
before the agency finished drafting its rule to require the change.
In the end, though, the agency mandated one test more than United
had accomplished, and the airline had to take the hydraulic units
off the plane a second time and put them to the additional test.
``We went out and tried to lead the industry, but then they came
out with another test,'' said Gregory Borsari, United's manager of
engineering for 737s.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Each change leads to a raft of other changes. Anything that adds
five pounds or more to the plane's weight goes into a database used
to recalculate its center of gravity, for example. (And planes,
like people, tend to get heavier as they age.) And any new system,
like the fire detection and suppression system, means a new
maintenance schedule.
</P>
<P>
   For N-1383, which United bought new from Boeing in March 1990,
this was heavy-maintenance visit No. 2, the second time it has been
torn apart and rebuilt. The process will include 20,148 hours of
mechanics' labor at a total labor cost of $420,000. Materials will
cost another $342,000.
</P>
<P>
   That is relatively cheap. By heavy-maintenance visit No. 7, when
the plane will be more than 30 years old, N-1383 will require
38,000 hours of labor, and the visit will cost about $3 million,
not counting modifications that have not yet been devised.
</P>
<P>
   The escalating cost of heavy maintenance may be what determines
how long the plane can economically be flown, said Mohr, the United
official. Ultimately it will be scrapped or sold to another
airline, probably in another part of the world, ``that doesn't have
the same standards,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-99 2049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991212.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6826 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PLANE-MAINTENANCE-ART     12-12 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANE-MAINTENANCE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG, BIG JOB OF MAINTAINING A BOEING 737 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
