<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6832 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LAD     12-12 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLYFIELD IS FIGHTER OF THE DECADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In some ways, the 1990s were disappointing for
boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Most significantly, the decade failed to produce a fighter who
captured the public's imagination as Mike Tyson did in the '80s,
Ray Leonard did in the '70s and '80s and Muhammad Ali did in the
'60s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic gold-medal winner Oscar De La Hoya, a fine young fighter
with Leonard-like ability and charm, seemed to have what it takes
to fill the void but has failed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   And we'll never know how good Roy Jones Jr. is because no one
around is good enough to give him a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we were left with a faded Tyson as the sport's biggest
draw and wondering when the next great fighter might emerge.
</P>
<P>
   However, all was not lost.
</P>
<P>
   One fighter, special in his own way, did do us proud in the
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   No, Evander Holyfield doesn't have the ability or the charisma
of an Ali or Leonard or the mesmerizing punching power of a Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   What he did do was establish himself as the dominant champion in
the sport's marquee division as much as a result of grit and guts
as natural talent. And, while he did it quietly, he also did it
with was as much class as any of his predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   The fighter of the decade? No brainer: Holyfield's the man.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   1. Holyfield. He joined Ali as the only three-time heavyweight
champions and he did it all in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   He knocked out Buster Douglas in three rounds in 1990 to win the
title; lost it to Riddick Bowe in 1992; regained it from Bowe in
1993; lost it to Michael Moorer in 1994; and, in one of the
decade's most dramatic moments, knocked out Tyson in 11 rounds as a
huge underdog to become champ a third time.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield gave us so many memories.
</P>
<P>
   2. Pernell Whitaker: He won 17 world championship fights in the
'90s before he began to decline late in the decade. With Jones and
Julio Cesar Chavez, he's the greatest talent of his era.
</P>
<P>
   3. Jones: He easily outpointed much-feared James Tony with his
rare boxing skills to win the WBC super middleweight champion and
then graduated to the light heavyweight division, which he
dominates to this day.
</P>
<P>
   He's a great fighter without a great fight.
</P>
<P>
   4. Ricardo Lopez: He had owned the strawweight division since he
stopped Ohashi Hideyuki in October of 1990 and now is the junior
flyweight champ.
</P>
<P>
   However, he has had Jones' problem: Precious little competition.
</P>
<P>
   5. Oscar De La Hoya: He has had some fine moments, but his
career has been marked so far by inconsistency and
unpredictability.
</P>
<P>
   Is he a boxer? A puncher? Both? We're waiting for him to find
himself and realize his potential. Against Felix Trinidad, he had
an opportunity for a sensational, breakthrough victory but
squandered it by running the final few rounds.
</P>
<P>
   6. Trinidad: He won the IBF welterweight title in 1993 and still
holds it. That's a long, impressive run sullied only by a lack of
top-notch competition.
</P>
<P>
   He added the WBC welterwight belt by outpointing De La Hoya in a
fight he should've lost.
</P>
<P>
   7. Julio Cesar Chavez: We'll think of the '90s as the decade
that Chavez's skills faded. However, he won 15 title fights in
machine-like fashion between 1990 and 1996, the year he first lost
to De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, he was at his best in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   8. Terry Norris: OK, he had the chin from you know where. At the
same time, he was a wonder to watch with his rare combination of
skills and power. He won 19 world title fights in the decade and
won't be forgotten. If he could've taken a punch, he would've been
one of the greatest.
</P>
<P>
   9. Riddick Bowe: His peak didn't last long but was impressive.
His two victories over a young Holyfield in three fights are the
reason he's here.
</P>
<P>
   10. Lennox Lewis: He has yet to give anything resembling a great
performance. However, this big, talented heavyweight has lost only
once _ a questionable stoppage against Oliver McCall _ and twice
beat Holyfield, once officially and once in reality.
</P>
<P>
   Others: Among others worthy of consideration: Johnny Tapia, who
was a dominating junior bantamweight; George Foreman, whose
knockout of Michael Moorer to win the heavyweight championship at
45 was one of the decade's most-thrilling moments; Humberto
``Chiquita'' Gonzalez, one of the '90s most exciting little men;
Azumah Nelson, one of the great fighters of his era; and Genearo
Hernandez, who had a quiet, but long run in the junior lightweight
division.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Mayweather, Fernando Vargas and David Reid? The talent is
there but the accomplishments aren't ... yet.
</P>
<P>
   Next week: In next Monday's boxing column, we'll rank the top-10
fighters of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Please phone or e-mail with your thoughts and comments.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican War: In terms of potential, it's tough to top the
scheduled bout between Erik Morales and Marco Antonio Barrera on
Feb. 19 in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Both fighters are big punchers with aggressive styles who will
be fighting for Morales' WBC junior featherweight title and hero
status in their native Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, unbeaten, will be the favorite. He's one of the sport's
fastest-rising stars, while Barrera is still trying to come back
from losses to Junior Jones in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Morales is very confident. He called the matchup ``a transition
fight,'' meaning there are much bigger and better things ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Naseem Hamed, for example. Morales' face lights up when the
Prince's name is mentioned because of the money and recognition
that would come with a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will be my biggest fight,'' Morales said through an
interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Barrera was regarded as perhaps the next great Mexican champion
until the Jones fights, in which he was exposed as painfully
mortal.
</P>
<P>
   He took 10 months off to rebuild and has won six straight fights
since his return.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has the fire of old as he prepares to take on
Morales.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot from those losses,'' he said through an
interpreter. ``It helps me a lot for this fight. I was at a point
right before I fought Jones where I thought I was invincible, that
no one could touch me. The Jones fights put my feet on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put doubts in peoples' minds with the Jones fights. This
fight will bring me back to the top.''
</P>
<P>
   It's important to note that Morales stopped Jones in four rounds
in 1998. However, that might not be as significant as Morales seems
to think it is because Jones had taken a severe beating from
Kennedy McKinney before that fight, the kind of beating that takes
a lot out of a fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Morales-Hamed: Bob Arum, Morales' promoter, said he will not
jump into a bout with Hamed.
</P>
<P>
   The flamboyant Briton recently engaged in a bout with Cesar Soto
that resembled a wrestling match and Arum is hesitant to subject
his fighter to such a risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have to be confident something like that wouldn't
happen again,'' Arum said.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya-Trinidad: OK, hopefully they'll get it right this
time.
</P>
<P>
   Arum, De La Hoya's promoter, and Don King, Trinidad's promoter,
are scheduled to sit down today in New York and discuss a possible
rematch for June 17 in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Let's make the deal. Trinidad could make $15 million-plus, a
figure he couldn't approach against any other fighter. And De La
Hoya reportedly is eager to exact revenge for his controversial
loss in their first meeting.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense in every way.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya is scheduled to fight Derrell Coley on Feb. 26 at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-99 2103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
