<SLUG> BC-BBO-MEETINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS ARE STILL SHOPPING AFTER ACQUIRING ZEILE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Shortly after 9 o'clock Saturday night, Todd
Zeile sat in his agent's hotel room and experienced an epiphany.
``I've got three years left, maybe four,'' Zeile said. ``Which team
do I have a better chance of winning a world championship with?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, as it turned out, was simple. That's why Zeile
accepted the New York Mets' three-year, $20 million offer and left
the Texas Rangers stunned and wondering about their immediate
course.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Phillips, who engineered the Zeile coup, went back to work
Sunday in an effort to make sure Zeile will not regret his
decision. Ken Griffey Jr., Manny Ramirez, Jim Edmonds, B.J.
Surhoff, David Wells, Scott Erickson, Jason Schmidt, Francisco
Cordova. These were some of the players, hard-hitting outfielders
and starting pitchers, that Phillips, the Mets' general manager,
was talking about with other teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some larger deals we're still talking about,''
Phillips said without naming teams or players.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips was fresh off of signing Zeile, a free-agent third
baseman, to replace John Olerud at first base. He began pursuing
the 34-year-old Zeile the minute Olerud signed with Seattle last
week. But besides replacing the offensive production Olerud took
with him, Phillips wants to upgrade the Mets' offense, and that's
why he was talking to the Mariners about Griffey, to Cleveland
about Ramirez, to Anaheim about Edmonds and to Baltimore about
Surhoff.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to add a strong starting pitcher; thus the talks
with Toronto about Wells, with the Orioles about Erickson and with
Pittsburgh about Schmidt and Cordova.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' general manager, Brian Cashman, isn't at the winter
meetings; no high-level member of the team's front office is. But
that hasn't stopped Cincinnati from pursuing Hideki Irabu, whom the
Yankees would like to trade. The Reds won't give up Dennys Reyes,
the young relief pitcher the Yankees would like, but Cincinnati is
offering prospects, and the Yankees may well make the trade.
</P>
<P>
   In one trade that was made Sunday, the Chicago Cubs became the
beneficiary of the Los Angeles Dodgers' desire to unload enough
salary to give them greater payroll flexibility. The Dodgers sent
Ismael Valdes, a starting pitcher, and Eric Young, a second baseman
and base-stealing leadoff hitter, to the Cubs for Terry Adams, a
reliever; Chad Ricketts, a minor-league reliever; and a player to
be named.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey and Ramirez presented the most intriguing possibilities
for the Mets, who don't have a problem with payroll flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' contingent of trade talkers had not held their daily
meeting with the Mariners when Phillips briefed reporters with
sparse details of what he had been up to. But when they met
Saturday, the Mariners finally began mentioning names. They didn't
tell the Mets the specific players they wanted, one of the meeting
participants said, but ran down a list of ``a bunch'' of players.
</P>
<P>
   Among the players the Mariners asked about were Armando Benitez,
Roger Cedeno, Octavio Dotel, Masato Yoshii and Dennis Cook.
``There's more potential there today than yesterday,'' the
participant said after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the Mariners did not ask about Edgardo Alfonzo,
the Mets' outstanding second baseman. The Mariners' talks with the
Reds collapsed over Seattle's insistence on getting second baseman
Pokey Reese in a package for Griffey and the Reds' refusal to
include him.
</P>
<P>
   Like Griffey, Ramirez can be a free agent after next season.
John Hart, the Indians' general manager, said he met with Phillips
on Saturday morning but declined to name the names they discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that there's anything there,'' Hart said.
``There's been a lot of people talked about. We haven't got to the
point where we've entertained anything on the trade front.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Moorad, Ramirez's agent, said the former Washington Heights
resident prefers to remain in Cleveland. ``We made that point clear
to John Hart,'' Moorad said. But if the Indians decided they didn't
want to pay what a contract extension would cost (presumably more
than $15 million a year), he added, ``either New York team would
make sense to explore.''
</P>
<P>
   Moorad, who negotiated a $14 million-a-year contract for Shawn
Green with the Dodgers last month, said he was not certain if he
would be willing to negotiate with a team the Indians might trade
Ramirez to before the deal would become final.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels want to trade an outfielder, preferably Edmonds or
Garret Anderson, and they met with the Mets Sunday, but the session
was brief and unproductive.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' talks with the Blue Jays, on the other hand, have at
least produced an offer. ``We made them a proposal, a multiplayer
deal on both sides,'' Gord Ash, the Toronto general manager, said.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, whom the teams discussed last month at the general
managers' meetings, would be at the center of such a trade. The
Blue Jays, like every team that talks to the Mets, are believed to
have asked for Dotel in return.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' talks with the Orioles had not reached the offer
stage. But the Mets expressed interest in Erickson, a veteran
right-handed starter, who overcame a poor start last season and
finished with a 15-12 record. They also asked about Surhoff, a good
left-handed-hitting outfielder. The Mets want to find a left-hander
to replace Olerud's bat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
