<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-DOLPHINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS' THEATRICS PUT MARINO AND DOLPHINS IN THE WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Ray Lucas was on the ground, so groggy
he had to be helped to the sideline with the score tied at 13-13 in
the final quarter against the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   No problem. Lucas left for a play, Rick Mirer came in for a
handoff and suddenly Lucas was back on the field after Bill
Parcells had quizzed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know how to execute this play?'' Parcells asked. Lucas
explained it to his coach.
</P>
<P>
   And then on his first play back after getting leveled on a
helmet-to-helmet hit, Lucas rolled right, found Keyshawn Johnson in
the end zone to his left and drilled a difficult 24-yard touchdown
pass to break the tie and send the Jets on their way to a 28-20
victory Sunday. As for the Dolphins, now 8-5, it dealt a powerful
blow to their playoff hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' a satisfied Johnson said later, ``was an Elway kind of
throw.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a Dan Marino kind of fourth-quarter comeback. But
this time, for a change, it wasn't Marino. Instead, the 38-year-old
quarterback was on the sideline as the game wound down, and for all
anyone knew it could have been his last appearance in Giants
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, though, remain alive to the possibility of finishing
the season at 8-8. They have five victories with three games
remaining, and in the most extreme case, they could make the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   First they had to win a game. This they did to snap a two-game
losing streak and avoid being the first Jets team in the three-year
Parcells reign to lose three in a row.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy, but for the fans on hand it was fun. After all,
John Hall missed a pair of extra-point attempts _ the first time a
kicker has done that since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   And the Jets needed some final-period theatrics. Just last
Sunday, Lucas had sprained his ankle against the Giants in the
final period, and Parcells wanted to keep him out. Lucas grabbed
his coach by the arm and insisted on returning. He threw two
touchdowns in a losing effort. Sunday he repeated the
fourth-quarter scoring, but with different results.
</P>
<P>
   After Aaron Glenn intercepted Marino with the score 13-6 toward
the end of the third quarter, the Jets began a drive that ended
with the first of two Lucas-to-Johnson touchdowns. The two
collaborated on a 26-yarder to tie the score, and then connected
for the dramatic second score.
</P>
<P>
   That final catch gave Johnson a career-high 11-reception game,
following his 10-catch effort against the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   After John Hall missed the extra point to leave the score at
19-13, the Jets added a 46-yard Hall field goal. Then safety Omar
Stoutmire produced the crushing play _ he intercepted Marino and
returned the ball for a 67-yard touchdown. Stoutmire, who obviously
will see more action the rest of the season, had replaced Steve
Atwater, who may miss the rest of the year with a pulled hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   With Marino on the bench, Damon Huard led a final Miami
touchdown drive in the closing seconds. But the Jets then recovered
the onside kick. And this game belonged to a quarterback who had
said he would be thrilled just to be on the same field as Marino. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The game was lacking in theatrics at halftime, each team having
kicked two field goals, but Lucas came out looking for the big play
in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The first time the Jets touched the ball, on the opening
kickoff, Dwight Stone returned it 45 yards. Then Lucas, on the
first play from scrimmage, whipped the ball 45 yards in the air
over the middle, looking for Wayne Chrebet.
</P>
<P>
   The pass was overthrown _ indeed, Lucas came into the game
having completed only one pass that actually traveled at least 20
yards in the air.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets continued to try to make the big play when they went
for it on fourth-and-1 from the Miami 46. It was an odd thing to do
on the opening drive, but then again, the Jets were running out of
opportunities this season. Martin converted.
</P>
<P>
   However, the drive ended in failure when Hall missed a 47-yard
field goal attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Marino, though, completed his first six passes, getting the
Dolphins close enough for a 24-yard Olino Mare field goal and a 3-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   This has been a season in which the smallest setback hurts the
Jets, who do not have the resiliency on offense to offset a
problem. Until Sunday, they had kept most of their games manageable
by avoiding turnovers. They had in fact gone three straight games
without one, and had not lost a fumble since Game 6, against the
Colts.
</P>
<P>
   But on the kickoff following Miami's field goal, Stone fumbled,
the Dolphins recovered only 23 yards away from the Jets' goal line,
and Mare converted the lost ball into a 33-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets tied the score with a pair of field goals in the second
quarter, each time helped by good field position. First, Lucas took
over on the Dolphins' 36, could not get the team into the end zone,
but did see Hall boot a 28-yarder. Then the Jets took over on the
Miami 33 and got close enough for a 31-yard kick.
</P>
<P>
   Again, though, the Jets gave up the sort of play they cannot
afford: Nate Jacquet produced the longest punt return of the season
against them, and it positioned the Dolphins only 25 yards out.
Five plays later, Stanley Pritchett smacked over from the 1 for a
13-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   As they have been all season, the Jets were depleted Sunday _
this time on defense. Ray Mickens, their nickel back, sat out with
a hamstring injury. Jason Wiltz, who was becoming effective in the
rotation on the defensive line, also was sidelined, with a turf-toe
injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets finally got a big play of their own toward the end of
the third period, when Glenn produced his third interception of the
season to put the Jets at the Miami 39.
</P>
<P>
   This time the Jets did something with their break. Johnson took
a 26-yard Lucas pass a few seconds into the the final quarter and
easily outhustled safety Shawn Wooden into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The score lifted Johnson over the 1,000-yard receiving mark for
a second straight year. That had not happened since George Sauer
and Don Maynard each did it in 1967 and 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson followed that with his 24-yard end-zone grab on Lucas'
theatrical return with 5 minutes 26 seconds left, but the Jets
still kept the fans in their seats as Hall's extra-point attempt
hit the top of the left upright and bounced the wrong way. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
