u s BC-BKC-RUTGERS-PRINCETON     12-12 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RUTGERS-PRINCETON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRINCETON SHEDS ITS OLD IMAGE WHILE PUSHING RUTGERS AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PISCATAWAY, N.J. _ Meet the new Princeton Tigers. They push the
ball straight inside. When they are shoved underneath, they shove
back. And they now press. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers got newly acquainted Sunday with the
rougher-around-the-edges Ivy Leaguers in their 105th meeting,
falling by 66-60 in overtime. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mason Rocca, the last link to Princeton's talented team of two
seasons ago, is now the flagship of the renovated Tigers. The
6-foot-9-inch Rocca has muscles that he is not afraid to use, a
quick first step, and a sweet version of a hook shot. The
combination added up to 28 points and 13 rebounds. Most of his
damage came in the first 32 minutes, when the Scarlet Knights
rotated single defenders on him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They were making me make the shot,'' said Rocca, who missed
the Tigers' first four games with a groin pull. ``I like that.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And when Rutgers (6-2) stopped Rocca's scoring for the last 13
minutes with a double-team, Princeton (5-4) resorted to the other
advantages that had kept it ahead for most of the time in a
physical game abetted by a loud throng of 8,012 at Louis Brown
Athletic Center. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers worked for better shots, making 49 percent to
Rutgers' 36 percent, and squirmed their way to the foul line more,
making 20 of 33 free throws, compared with Rutgers' 9 of 19. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we played at a particularly high level,''
Rutgers Coach Kevin Bannon said. ``I was kind of shocked. We
weren't sharp offensively.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If not for Dahntay Jones' 27 points, Rutgers would not have made
a game of it with an 8-2 spurt to take a 51-49 lead with 1 minute
25 seconds to go in regulation. At that point, Rocca took on the
role of playmaker, flipping a backdoor pass to Nate Walton, who
made a layup to tie the score at 51-51. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That was one of the few backdoor scores for Princeton. Without
the offensive firepower of a few years ago, Coach Bill Carmody has
eliminated a lot of the team's cuts to the basket. He is also
dabbling with a press, which was largely responsible for 21 Scarlet
Knight turnovers. Princeton had 22 of its own, Rocca coughing up 7
of them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Scarlet Knights had the ball with 14.5 seconds to go in
regulation and could work only for a Jeff Greer fadeaway that fell
short at the buzzer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers briefly took the lead in overtime on a driving layup by
Jones, but Princeton answered with a 9-1 surge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Players and coaches did not trumpet the full resurgence of this
once important rivalry, but Sunday afternoon's emotional affair was
something to build on. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need to look at a stat sheet to know that it was a
very intense game,'' Carmody said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
