<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TRANSIT-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRESS IN N.Y. TRANSIT NEGOTIATIONS AS STRIKE DEADLINE NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Negotiators for the Metropolitan Transportation
Authority and the union representing 33,000 New York City transit
workers said Sunday that they had narrowed their differences over a
proposed wage increase, the biggest issue dividing the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   With a strike deadline set for 12:01 a.m. Wednesday, officials
involved in the negotiations said that Willie James, president of
Local 100 of the Transport Workers Union, had scaled back his
demand for a 27 percent wage increase over three years.
</P>
<P>
   These officials said that negotiators for the MTA, which runs
the city's subways and buses, have raised their wage offer to above
the 12 percent over four years they offered last week. The MTA's
previous proposal included a wage increase of about 9.5 percent
over four years and increased pension contributions equal to 2.3
percent of each worker's salary. ``Both sides have made a move on
wages,'' said Marc Shaw, the MTA's executive director, who declined
to spell out the latest proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said that the negotiations gained momentum on Friday night
and Saturday morning, when the two sides altered their wage
proposals. While slow progress had been taking place in other
areas, the deadlock over wages was hurting the tenor of the talks
and their overall momentum, negotiators said.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing both sides' new flexibility on wages, Shaw said: ``It
had the effect of allowing a lot of discussions to become much more
fruitful. The amount of movement on wages wasn't that significant,
but the fact that there was movement was significant. So long as
there is movement toward a center, we're comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sides resumed negotiations at about noon Sunday at MTA
headquarters, a block from Grand Central Terminal. Later in the
day, they moved the talks to the Grand Hyatt Hotel, where they plan
to sequester themselves for continuous talks until the Wednesday
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Sunday night during a break in the negotiations,
Shaw said he was more optimistic about a settlement being reached
than he had been a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm moderately more optimistic, because movement is
continuing,'' he said. ``The progress that happened yesterday
continued, and we'll be going over a list of what the outstanding
issues are. Tonight, we'll start to move to close them.''
</P>
<P>
   But he voiced concern that some serious snags could still
develop that would slow or halt momentum toward a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Frank, a union spokesman, said, ``Things are moving
along.'' He would not be more specific.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said they expected the MTA to raise its offer to
match the 13 percent over four years that most unions at the Long
Island Rail Road and Metro-North Railroad have accepted. A big
question, many labor experts say, is whether the MTA will raise its
offer above that 13 percent, a move that might anger the railroad
unions.
</P>
<P>
   James insists that his members deserve more than the railway
workers because his union made several significant concessions to
the MTA in its current contract, which expires on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   James has been under heavy pressure from his members and from a
large dissident faction to obtain well more than 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Schermerhorn, who narrowly lost to James in an election last
year and who heads the New Directions dissident group, said in an
interview that James should secure raises of 7 percent or 8 percent
a year _ figures that MTA officials say would cause a large
deficit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-99 2136EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991212.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6853 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      12-12 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Carlos Rogers had waited years for his chance, and now he had it.
He had been doomed to persona non grata status by the Trail
Blazers, offered little more than relative cameos by the Warriors
and Raptors. But now he was starting, sent to fill the huge void
left by Charles Barkley's injury. He was playing well, and he knew
it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But in another agonizing irony in a season filled with them,
playing time meant nothing to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minutes don't mean anything if you're losing,'' Rogers said.
``That doesn't matter. If you win with 10 minutes, you did a great
job. If you lose and play 48 minutes, it doesn't mean (anything).''
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances of the Rockets' three consecutive defeats
would not be considered, he said. The Rockets dismissed the
obvious, handy explanations for their ``funk.''
</P>
<P>
   Emotions could have been considered as torn as the Rockets'
preseason blueprint. There had been no time to regroup. No team had
suffered through more calamities, and by the time the Rockets hit
New Jersey on Saturday for their third short-handed game in four
nights, they were road-weary and emotionally spent.
</P>
<P>
   But they would buy none of it. They could have understandably
explained away the 106-94 loss to the Nets as an aberration, but
they refused.
</P>
<P>
   Getting beaten by the Nets might not have been so humbling had
the Rockets blamed their continued misfortune. Calling on the
excuses so readily available might have softened the blow.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they said they knew they would have to win without
their veteran stars eventually. They would not pretend that losing
Barkley and Hakeem Olajuwon prevented them from playing with
intensity or working defensively. They knew that if they blamed
their personnel losses for their defeats now, they might also be
accepting of defeat later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I'm going to coach to win, coach these guys
hard,'' coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``If I didn't, it would be a
wasted year. You've got to get something positive out of it. It
really just speeds up the process we were going to have to go
through at the beginning of (next) year when we wouldn't have had
Charles.''
</P>
<P>
   The process, however, has not really had time to begin. The
Rockets have had one practice since Barkley's career-ending rupture
of his quadriceps tendon, and the workout was tempered because it
came on the one day of the four-day trip without a game.
</P>
<P>
   After taking Sunday off, the Rockets will get a full practice in
today. But they go from facing a team that views spring as lottery
season to the teams that last spring played for the NBA
championship, battling the Knicks on Tuesday and the Spurs on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had enough time to prepare for it,'' Shandon
Anderson said of the alterations in style that constant roster
changes bring. ``With all the new guys, we have to still learn the
system a little bit. Having that post game to rely on isn't there.
We have to get up and down, more setting picks, getting guys open.
But there hasn't been enough time yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets were seemingly starting to mature past their
early-season growing pains, winning three straight before Barkley
went down.
</P>
<P>
   With Olajuwon not due back from hernia surgery until late
January at the soonest, the Rockets have completely turned over
their starting lineup since last season. Only one current starter,
Walt Williams, has ever held that job before, and for Williams that
was three years and two teams ago. No current starter was a Rocket
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of 16 guys who played for us last year, only three are on
the team right now,'' Tomjanovich said, referring to Cuttino
Mobley, Bryce Drew and Matt Bullard. ``We really have made a big
change. It's just a tremendous opportunity for our young guys.
There's a lot of responsibility, a lot of leadership situations
they're going to have to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things like this happen. Sometimes you get an upset win early;
sometimes you don't. But then you get into acceptance of this is
what we have, this is what we have to work with. I've seen it a lot
of times where you develop a lot of chemistry that's successful.
That's what I hope happens.''
</P>
<P>
   But for that to happen, the Rockets must go back to Chemistry
101. Where Barkley and Olajuwon had taken turns as the fulcrum of
the offense, the Rockets must radically change much of what they
had done offensively and then discover what can work as
consistently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team has one player, one post guy they know they could
go to when they need him,'' Anderson said. ``Charles was the guy
for us. Utah has Karl (Malone). LA has Shaq (O'Neal). Now we have
to find our guy. We knew we could go to Chuck at the end of the
game. We knew they were going to double-team him, and he would get
the ball out to the open guy. We need one play we go to when
everything is going bad. We haven't found that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost as if in training camp again, the Rockets must experiment
to uncover the best qualities that remain and hone them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really using it as a growth period, an improvement
period,'' Tomjanovich said. ``It's very valuable time. Hopefully,
we get some good results out of it. That's not the bottom line. I
do want to win, but we all know we've got a lot of new guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sort of a young team now that we don't have those guys
(Barkley and Olajuwon). As good as those guys are and how much we
relied on them, there can be some strengths because of youth _ more
running, different kind of defenses, things like that. More
versatility. Of course, we're not going to have the big entree, the
big meat-and-potatoes deal we know we can expect. It's going to be
interesting how we establish things offensively. It's wide-open
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve (Francis) has had some good things. Cuttino has had some
good things. But we need to expand on that.''
</P>
<P>
   More than changing plays and styles, the Rockets' individual
roles are more fluid than ever. Side dishes must become main
courses. But Rogers said the Rockets also must balance doing more
and trying to do too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people's roles have been defined,'' Rogers said.
``They have changed. We haven't addressed it. Without Chuck and
Dream here, people want to step up. The emotions say `step up.' But
reality is sometimes `stay back.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what we can do as a team to come out of this funk
or whatever it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it should be obvious. Stubbornly refusing to accept
their misfortune could make facing the latest obstacles more
challenging. It also might be the only hope to overcome them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
