<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6855 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-LIONS-BUCS-NYT &LR;      12-12 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LIONS-BUCS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCCANEERS FIND THEMSELVES IN AN UNUSUAL PLACE ATOP DIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ The Detroit Lions started fast. Sizzling. The
running game was clicking, the passing game hit big notes and the
Lions lapped the Tampa Bay Buccaneers, building a 10-0
first-quarter lead and possessing a 7-point lead midway through the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Lions fizzled. Collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay started with a fizzle. Collapsing all around. Then the
running game clicked and the passing game hit big notes. The
Buccaneers began lapping the Lions.
</P>
<P>
   It was an odd game of opposite patterns, of opposite fortunes,
as Tampa Bay saved its best for last, scoring 14 fourth-quarter
points to rattle Detroit, 23-16, before 65,536 fans at Raymond
James Stadium. In a fight for the division lead, Tampa Bay (9-4)
gained the edge and stands alone in first place in the National
Football Conference Central. Detroit slipped to 8-5. With three
games to play, the Bucs are in first place this late in the season
for the first time since 1981. It won its sixth straight, a
franchise record. And broke a four-game losing streak against the
Lions.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit quarterback Gus Frerotte (23 of 44 for 241 yards, no
touchdowns, 4 sacks, 1 interception) and his offense got the early
jump.
</P>
<P>
   But the Buccaneers' rookie quarterback, Shaun King (23 of 37 for
297 yards, 2 touchdowns, 3 sacks, 1 interception), and his crew
dominated in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed that we can come back in the fourth quarter and
that's something we haven't done a lot,'' said King, making his
second pro start; he is 2-0. ``I'm not afraid to win. I'm not
afraid to make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs played King conservatively until the fourth quarter. He
entered having passed 27 times for 206 yards and with his team
trailing 13-9. Detroit kicked a field goal early in the quarter to
earn a 16-9 lead.
</P>
<P>
   And then the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   A Mike Alstott 1-yard touchdown run. A Frerotte interception
returned 28 yards to the Detroit 24 by safety John Lynch. An
Alstott 22-yard catch and run off a screen pass where the Lions
were destroyed, falling over themselves and blocked, too, on the
touchdown with 4:18 left. That would give Tampa Bay its first lead
of the game. And the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our opportunities; we missed them,'' said Bobby Ross,
the Detroit head coach. ``We had control of the game let them get
back in it. The screen plays _ we've got to defend that a lot
better. We're not out of it yet. We'll be fighting and maybe we'll
get a chance to come right back here.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's plan to build a quick first-quarter lead and then
unleash its defense on King in hopes that he would answer with
mistakes nearly worked. The Lions leaped to a 10-0 lead in the
game's first 14 minutes and then early in the second quarter
recovered a King fumble.
</P>
<P>
   But King in the final minutes of the half connected with Warrick
Dunn on a 68-yard pass play that injected spirit into the sleepy
Tampa Bay offense and crowd. That play set up Tampa Bay's only
first-half score. Thus, Detroit led, 10-7, at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit dominated for the initial 14 minutes. In the first
quarter, it won in total yards by 114 to 52 and limited Tampa Bay
to 3 first downs and 9 rushing yards. Detroit drove to the Tampa
Bay 19 on its first possession and scored on a Jason Hanson 37-yard
field goal. With :52 seconds left in the quarter, Greg Hill sped 10
yards around left end for a touchdown. The key play in that drive
was a Frerotte 48-yard pass to a diving receiver, Johnnie Morton,
who caught it and landed flat and face-first at the Tampa Bay 22.
</P>
<P>
   King and the Tampa offense struggled early because the Lions
defense tackled the run and pass with equal effectiveness. And the
Detroit third-down defense was especially smart. Tampa could not
convert a third-and-18 and a third-and-10 on its first two
possessions and then on its third possession fumbled. King took a
snap from the Detroit 32, dropped in the pocket, attempted to pass
under presser from end Robert Porcher, but the ball slipped out of
his hands. Tackle Luther Ellis recovered for Detroit at the Detroit
44.
</P>
<P>
   That series could have proved fatal for Tampa Bay. Had Detroit
used that mistake to build a 17-0 advantage, how would King and the
Tampa Bay offense respond? Could they respond? The Buccaneers
defense, however, would not allow Detroit to pull away. The teams
would trade possession for the next four series and then with 1:40
remaining in the half, King found Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   It was your basic, soft, swing pass to the right flat but Dunn
took it and turned it upfield, down the right sideline for 68 yards
to the Detroit 7. A facemask penalty on Detroit cornerback J.B.
Brown while tackling Dunn moved the ball to the Detroit 4. And on
the next play, King calmly swung a play-fake pass to the left flat,
to fullback Kevin McLeod, who bobbled the pass, braced it against
his facemask and held on for the score with 1:34 left before
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit controlled the game for more than 28 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Then King and Dunn and Tampa struck.
</P>
<P>
   That was the nature of this game _ in a blink, a turnaround, a
few big plays, and the game turned Tampa Bay's way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
