A6858 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-YAC-AMERICA'S-CUP-NYT     12-12 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAC-AMERICA'S-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG AMERICA ELIMINATED WHEN ANOTHER U.S. BOAT FORFEITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barring a catastrophe to the French yacht Le Defi Francais, the
New York Yacht Club's four-year, $30 million quest to regain the
America's Cup came to an abrupt conclusion Monday. Its entry, Young
America, was eliminated in the third round of the Louis Vuitton
challengers' trials in Auckland, New Zealand, when the skipper of
another American yacht decided not to sail and forfeited a race to
the French.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Sunday's match with Dawn Riley's San Francisco-based
America True syndicate, Young America's fate was in its own hands.
Had it swept its final three races, it would have secured the sixth
and final spot in the challengers' semifinal series, which begins
Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   But, as has happened so often in this nightmarish round, the New
Yorkers found themselves on the wrong side of the first critical
wind shift, and they lost to the Californians by 2 minutes 5
seconds. With the loss, they suddenly needed help from other
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Young America needed America True to defeat Le
Defi _ its sole remaining rival for the final semifinal slot _ in a
race scheduled for Monday. Had America True triumphed, it could
have set up a sudden-death contest between the French and New
Yorkers on the series' final day.
</P>
<P>
   But with her berth in the semifinals already assured, and a
potentially gear-busting forecast of 20- to 40-knot breezes for
Monday, Riley elected to officially retire from the round and
forfeit the race to Le Defi.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Le Defi must sail the course uncontested to earn the points
for a victory; when that formality is completed, Young America's
run will officially be over. But the exercise was canceled Monday
when the gale-force winds postponed all racing. The one-boat race
has been re-scheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made absolutely no sense to go out and bash our boat around
for points that mean absolutely nothing,'' Riley said by telephone
from Auckland, New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   Riley admitted that her no-go decision might raise controversy,
but added, ``People who were supporting New York could see it that
way, but the sailors competing here will understand. This is a
competition and we're out here to win. We're a one-boat program and
we can't do that if we break our boat.''
</P>
<P>
   In last October's opening round of the series, Young America
established itself as one of the elite challenging teams. But the
tide turned on Nov. 9, when one of the syndicate's two boats
cracked and nearly sank. From that point on, New York victories
were few and far between.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if America True had raced today and forced a final match
between the French and Young America, the speculation here is that
the French would have won,'' said Keith Taylor, a Louis Vuitton
spokesman, by telephone. ``In recent weeks, Young America just
hasn't displayed efficient boat speed and the tactical smarts to
beat people at the top level.''
</P>
<P>
   Young America president John Marshall agreed that his team's
problems were multifaceted. ``People wonder how a team with so much
potential could fall short,'' he said in a conference call from
Auckland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's hard to identify a single factor,'' he added.
``We didn't fall short by losing one critical race to one key
competitor. The fact that Sunday's race was vital was because we'd
lost other races. We have a situation where, on the whole, the
program under-performed starting in mid-November. And we couldn't
put the brakes on during the December series.''
</P>
<P>
   For the New York Yacht Club, Monday's developments had an
unsettling precedent. In the club's last Cup campaign, in 1987, its
well-funded, star-studded squad also started quickly but ultimately
failed to advance to the challengers' semifinal round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised,'' Riley said, echoing the sentiment along the
Auckland docks. ``After that first round this time around, you
never would've thought New York would be in this position right
now.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
