<HEADER>
A6871 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-CELTICS-NY     12-12 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-CELTICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS USE THEIR DEPTH TO WEAR DOWN THE CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marcus Camby did not have a warm look for Coach Jeff
Van Gundy every time he was pulled off the floor and replaced by
Patrick Ewing Sunday night, but the sound of the chorus is what
counts. And the depth of the Knicks' talent drowned out everything
else at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter that Ewing finished 3 for 11 from the field
with 9 points when Van Gundy could throw stars at the Boston
Celtics with the repetition of a Pop-a-Shot arcade game. After
Latrell Sprewell and Kurt Thomas pushed the team through the first
half, Houston and Larry Johnson combined to nudge their team past
the Celtics the rest of the way in a tight 99-97 victory that
lifted the Knicks to a 13-9 record.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, who entered the night shooting just 36 percent over his
last four games, missed four of his first six shots before
finishing the night with 26 points on a 11-for-20 effort. Sprewell,
who added some color to the Knicks' bland beginning, ended with 17
points and four steals. But it was Johnson (23 points) who
delivered in the most difficult minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics turned up their pressure and forced the Knicks into
some sloppy play at the end. A healthy 12-point lead midway through
the fourth was down to 90-87 with 2:15 left in the game. But
Johnson came on to lead the Knicks to the finish with 7 points in
the last two minutes of the game and forced a turnover by Antoine
Walker with one second left in the game to end the threat of a tie
or loss.
</P>
<P>
   Houston is the one who gave the Celtics a chance. He missed two
free throws with 2.1 seconds left and the score 99-97. Camby, who
has been irritated about the potential for a drop in minutes due to
the return of Ewing to the starting lineup, ended the night with 1
point and two rebounds in 20 minutes. In the end, Camby did get a
steal to help protect the Knicks' fragile lead. The Celtics were
led by Walker's 24 points.
</P>
<P>
   A drowsy-looking Knicks team got jarred from its slumber when
the energetic Celtics came out with their usual frenzied style and
opened a 22-13 lead. After two angry timeouts called by Van Gundy,
Sprewell acted as smelling salts for the team. He made a steal that
led to a fast-break layup by Chris Childs, then hit a 3-pointer to
bring the Knicks back to life and pull them to 24-19.
</P>
<P>
   They quickly went ahead, 29-28, early in the second quarter
after a pull-up jumper by Sprewell in transition. A few minutes
later, the Knicks went on a 16-2 run to take a 51-35 lead with 2:43
left in the half and held a 55-43 edge entering the third quarter
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell's second-quarter partner in sapping the Celtics' spirit
was an unlikely suspect. It was Kurt Thomas, receiving Sprewell's
passes for layups in transition and putting back the Knicks'
misses. While Sprewell ended the half with 12 points, 4 assists and
3 steals, Thomas led the Knicks with 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   The duo made Ewing's struggles insignificant. At halftime, Ewing
was 0 for 6 from the field, bringing his total through six quarters
since his return from injury to 0 for 14. The silence of Ewing's
offense changed in the second minute of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It was a show-stopping moment. Ewing had the ball in the post,
wheeled to the middle in front of Vitaly Potapenko, then put up an
awkward turn-around jumper that fell as he was fouled to give him a
3-point opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   With 10:57 on the clock, the crowd stood in an ovation for
Ewing's first field goal of the season. But the fans quickly let
out a sigh as Ewing missed the free throw. Still, he had scored his
first points since June 1, the night he partially tore his left
Achilles' tendon in Indiana during Game 2 of the Eastern Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   It was a start for Ewing. He was still winded and often wandered
down the floor long after Sprewell or another teammate was scoring.
But Ewing's reflexes were impressively keen as he became an
intimidating force in the paint with four blocked shots through
three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being an albatross, Ewing became the complement to
the Knicks. He helped protect them from inside drives, and they
looked for him, too. Johnson saw Ewing sneak open under the basket,
fired a bullet pass and watched his 37-year-old center dunk the
ball to give the Knicks a 63-50 lead with 8:30 left in the third.
The unselfish Knicks had a good inside-outside mix going.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more we go inside, the better we are,'' Van Gundy said
before the game. ``When we play inside-out, and I don't know why
this is, but we play better defense. We're 9-1 when we have more
assists than our opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were headed that way through three quarters. Using
crisp passes, the Knicks were beating the pressure defense the
Celtics thrive on, a fact not even Van Gundy was expecting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got great anticipation,'' Van Gundy said. ``The way we
pass, I'm sure they are salivating.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being turnover-prone, the Knicks were mentally into
the game. The only letdown of the third quarter came when Ewing,
perhaps getting a little greedy, called for the ball twice in the
paint and missed both times on jumpers, allowing the Celtics to
pull to 63-55 with six minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   With Ewing on the bench resting, Houston was able to connect on
a couple of jumpers and find a groove he had been missing of late.
His 9 third-quarter points helped the Knicks take a 73-61 lead
after three quarters. Instead of looking disjointed, as they had
against Philadelphia in a tough victory on Friday, the Knicks had a
comfortable look about them heading into the fourth quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-99 2201EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
