<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6880 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-HOOD-INSTITUTE-SPI &LR;      12-12 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOD-INSTITUTE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENE HUNTER LEAVES UW TO CREATE NEW MODEL FOR SCIENCE RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Dr. Leroy Hood, renowned for developing the technology
that has helped propel the worldwide race to decipher the human
genetic code, is leaving the University of Washington to start a
private venture here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a chance to change the way science is done,'' Hood
said Sunday. ``I want to create a model for how academic
institutions will operate in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   How academia and the public university system operate today
turned out to be a bit too constrained for the envelope-pushing,
entrepreneurial scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Hood is forming a private, nonprofit institute that will become
a ``scientific melting pot'' for experts focused on marrying
biology with computer science.
</P>
<P>
   The union promises to revolutionize medicine by creating new
tools for diagnosis, treatment and prevention of disease at the
molecular level.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute for Systems Biology already has netted an
anonymous donation of $5 million toward start-up costs, and Hood is
talking to Merck and Immunex about potential projects.
</P>
<P>
   Hood envisions a small campus located near other research
institutions in town. He emphasized that his institute will be much
more than just another biotech start-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be an enormous integrator of technologies,'' Hood
said. Biologists working to understand living creatures will work
with computer scientists and engineers skilled at deciphering the
language of life.
</P>
<P>
   He wants the institute to focus on long-term scientific
problems, not just drug development or other short-term
achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Hood hopes his institute will be a place where scientists follow
their interests, but also where researchers give back to society.
He and his wife, Valerie Logan, have spent years working to improve
the teaching of science from kindegarten through high school.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Hood said, he wants to create a new kind of academic
enterprise _ a model for how science should be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really think this will be a unique approach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of running his own show, without the bureaucratic
obstacles and political snarls of the university, is a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the impatient type. ... I'm ready to be my own boss,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hood was recruited to Seattle in 1992 from the California
Institute of Technology in Pasadena, thanks largely to a $12
million grant from Microsoft chairman Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   The Gates donation created the UW Department of Molecular
Biotechnology with Hood _ as the William Gates III Professor of
Biomedical Sciences _ at the helm. The department has grown since
Hood took over, from a $3.5 million start-up budget to $32 million
last year.
</P>
<P>
   UW President Richard McCormick said Sunday he was sorry to lose
Hood but expects a continued, close collaboration between the
university and the gene hunter's new research institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lee feels he needs the independence provided by the institute
to accomplish (his) goals,'' McCormick said. Hood has done a
``brilliant job'' bringing in talent and building up the UW
research program in the fast-paced, high stakes field of molecular
biology, biotechnology and genetics, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has benefited the university greatly,'' agreed Dr. Maynard
Olson, director of the UW arm of the Human Genome Project.
</P>
<P>
   The federal project, sponsored by the National Institutes of
Health, aims to identify and decode all of the 60,000 to 100,000
genes of the human body. Hood's lab at Caltech developed automated
genetic decoding, or ``sequencing,'' machines that have greatly
speeded up the analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hood likes to start new things, to move from one start-up to
another,'' Olson said. ``Now he wants to try something new.''
</P>
<P>
   Last April, he and the UW announced plans to create the
Institute for Quantitative Systems Biology, a public-private
venture intended to exploit the increasing amounts of genetic
information made available by the genome project.
</P>
<P>
   It was to be operated by the UW School of Medicine off-campus
with an annual budget of $100 million. Hood had agreed to seek
funding independently from government, industry and other sources.
The agri-chemical company Monsanto had already funded plant-genome
research.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paul Ramsey, dean of the UW School of Medicine, heralded the
project as ``the future of biomedical research. ... Ensuring the
success of the institute is, and will remain, among the School of
Medicine's top priorities well into the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, the vision for this institute leaves with Hood,
and success or failure will rest solely on his shoulders. He likes
it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Hood said he and the UW administration agreed they needed to
part ways. He has been a strong advocate of academic-industrial
partnerships in science _ sometimes too strong for his scientific
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   When he first came to the UW, Hood helped found Darwin, a
biotechnology start-up company. Some of his colleagues grumbled
that he was more interested in business than science.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the then-dean of the medical school, the late Dr.
Phil Fialkow, ordered Hood to contribute all of his founder's stock
to charity to avoid any appearance of personal aggrandizement or
conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty annoyed at the time,'' admitted Hood. He said
other faculty who had established companies hadn't been so
constrained. Now, he said, the $2 million charitable foundation
created with his founder's stock is something he's proud to see
used for education and conservation projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
