<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: RAY FROM RUTGERS BEATS A LEGEND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The hit was a cruncher, Daryl Gardener's
helmet to Ray Lucas', 315 pounds of prime Miami beef sending 214
pounds of worth of raw quarterback crashing to the Jet-green
ground. Lucas would later say that he couldn't seem to get his eyes
to obey the brain's command to open. He remembered the chill of the
artificial turf seeping through the back of his shirt. He heard
familiar voices _ the trainer's and that of his new best friend,
Keyshawn Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas was helped to his feet and staggered to the sideline.
``Stay here!'' Bill Parcells barked. The coach used all of his
renowned medical experience to determine the extent of Lucas'
cerebral damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's No. 6?'' Parcells asked.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas groggily contemplated the question. Then he looked at the
plays scrawled on his wrist tape.
</P>
<P>
   One play later, he returned to the game.
</P>
<P>
   One play after that, he was rolling right, throwing back across
the grain, high and far, to a sprinting Johnson, the kind of pass
made in one's dreams, where Ray from Rutgers somehow morphs into
Dan Marino.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a thrill just to be on the same field with him,'' Lucas
said Sunday after his two fourth-quarter touchdown connections with
the rampaging Johnson took his nowhere Jets past Marino's fading
Dolphins 28-20 at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, to be young, strong-armed and hard-headed. Marino, better
than anyone, remembers when his body was unfailingly resilient,
when he could throw for 313 yards one week and do it again the next
week without missing a beat.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, a week after he put 34 points on the board in a
last-second defeat to the Indianapolis Colts, Marino had the
unmistakable look of an aging right-hander. He was David Cone
pitching on three days rest. The greatest statistical quarterback
in the history of the sport was outplayed and outpassed, 230-192,
by Parcells' class project. He was intercepted twice, and pulled
from a field on which he so often has had the last word.
</P>
<P>
   A sullen and almost whispering Marino had little to say after
what, conceivably, could have been his last game at Giants Stadium.
That left Jimmy Johnson, the coach who most assuredly wishes him a
happy next life, to bring finality to Miami's third straight defeat
since Marino returned to an 8-2 team after missing six weeks with
an injured shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``You throw interceptions on your end of the field, turn the
ball over,'' Johnson said, spitting out his thinly veiled critique.
``The last three or four years, it's been that way. It's nothing
new.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an old story, the Marino-Johnson tension, the uneasy
co-existence, the butting of heads by the legend-in-residence and
power coach who can flash two Super Bowl rings in Marino's baby
blue eyes.
</P>
<P>
   More than ever, for Marino, the Elway ending seems out of the
question. He admitted last week as much. Elway was fortunate enough
to find Terrell Davis in his backfield in the twilight of his
career. Marino took on the Jets Sunday with his wing and a prayer,
with no discernable running game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' Johnson lied, ``the running game wasn't the
problem today.''
</P>
<P>
   It has always been the problem for Marino in Miami. No one in
the history of the National Football League has thrown for more
touchdowns, more completions and yards. Johnson has provided him
one of the American Football Conference's better defenses. But
Johnson's machinations to redesign the Dolphins into more of a
running team have been a well-intentioned failure.
</P>
<P>
   Though injuries have played a part this season, it is of little
consolation to Marino at this point in his career. All he knows is
that the Dolphins have played 13 games, and run for fewer than 100
yards in nine of them. They managed a grand total of 69 Sunday.
They average about 90 a game. For the tenth time since Marino's
rookie season in 1983, they will have a different player lead them
in total yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Martin had 75 all by himself, and the threat of Martin at
the line of scrimmage loosened up Miami's secondary, where nine
different Jets were on the receiving end of Lucas' 22 completions.
Johnson caught 11 of them, giving him 21 in his last two games. He
talks a lot of stuff and catches a lot of balls. The 24-yard catch
in the left corner of the end zone on the Lucas rollout following
his one-play absence gave the Jets a 19-13 lead with 9 and a half
minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in Harrison, N.J., and knows all about Marino's
history of comebacks, about the fake-spike game here against the
Pete Carroll's Jets. There was, it turned out, nothing to worry
about Sunday. Marino didn't have the old zip on the ball, what he
had last week, when he chased Peyton Manning into the final seconds
of a 37-34 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play very well,'' Marino said. ``I didn't do what we
needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas will never be Marino, that much we know. His team isn't
going anywhere and Parcells won't even say he's guaranteed himself
a backup job when Vinny Testaverde returns next year. But Lucas
beat a legend Sunday, the way he beat Drew Bledsoe and Doug Flutie
last month. A season that has been something of a nightmare for
Parcells has become his fantasy, hard knocks be damned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
