<SLUG> BC-MA-FIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKERS START TEARING DOWN CHARRED WAREHOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ By Sunday morning, the out-of-town
firefighters had departed, the camera crews had left, and the men
of F&AMP;D Trucking Co. were left alone to do what they have been
itching to do all week: make the Worcester Cold Storage and
Warehouse Co. buildingisappear.
</P>
<P>
   A wrecking ball tapped at one of the warehouse's three standing
walls, breaking the structure into 3,000-pound chunks that toppled
and crashed down. Nicholas DiLiddo, one of F&AMP;D's owners, arrived at
the scene Dec. 3 after the blaze and worked 60 hours straight as he
dismantled the building from the inside, to avoid further burying
the six men who died in the inferno.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:30 p.m. Saturday, the remains of the last firefighter _
Paul Brotherton, 41 _ were removed. And DiLiddo could finally give
the Worcester firefighters what they wanted. ``They said, `Nick, go
get it. We want it out of here. It was a hellhole,' '' DiLiddo
said.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday night, the wall nearest Route 290 had been almost
demolished, allowing the expressway to reopen. So far, funerals for
three of the firefighters are scheduled this week: James Lyons's is
Monday, Joseph McGuirk's Tuesday, and Lieutenant Thomas Spencer's
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The demolition team has a formidable target in the warehouse,
which was built in 1906 and used for years by the Chicago Dressed
Beef Co. Susan Willett, who took a job in the building in 1968,
when she was 20, recalled an antic workplace where oxtails were
comic props and she was forever throwing her coat on and ducking
through sides of beef.
</P>
<P>
   But since the deadly fire, the building contains few good
memories. Betty Haddad came Sunday to watch the demolition, with
tears streaming down her face. ``It's much too sad to look at,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even weakened by the fire, it will fall slowly. The walls are 3
1/2 feet thick and reinforced with concrete. DiLiddo had passed the
building countless time,but didn't really know it until he took his
4,500-pound wrecking ball to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave it one god slap and the ball just went, dunk. When I
hit that building I knew it was going to be a fight all the way,''
he said. Do not mistake that respect for admiration, he said.
``There is nothing I like about that building at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-99 2220EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
