<DOCNO> NYT19991212.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6886 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-N.Y.-LOBBY-ASSESS-550     12-12 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-LOBBY-ASSESS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: THE QUAGMIRE OF LOBBY-LAW REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ For years, when self-styled good-government
groups have wanted to tighten New York's lax restrictions on
lobbyists or campaign fund-raising, the Democrats who control the
Assembly have been their most sympathetic audience. Bills have been
introduced, and occasionally passed, only to die in the
Republican-controlled state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But when those same gadflies applauded Saturday's far-ranging
proposal by Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno to revamp the
lobbying law, a spokeswoman for Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver
said the Democrats were not interested.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic legislators archly suggest that it is easy for Bruno
to play the reformer when he knows his plan will go nowhere. A
similar exchange occurred six months ago, when Gov. George Pataki,
a Republican, made a campaign finance proposal that left critics of
the current system almost giddy with delight, only to have the
Legislature ignore it.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats scoffed that Pataki knew there was no real danger that
his plan would become law.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats insist with some justification that they have
substantive objections to Bruno's lobbying package. Bruno said his
bill would ban nearly all gifts to legislators from lobbyists, but
Democrats asserted that it would not apply to trips to speak to
interest groups, even if those trips were to luxurious resorts; to
gifts from the corporate officers the lobbyists represent; or to
attendance at longstanding events like the Business Council's
annual meeting at a Lake George resort, a Republican favorite.
</P>
<P>
   But now it is the Assembly Democrats who risk looking like the
obstructionists, the false reformers who talk the high-minded talk
and pass bills that are doomed, but back away as soon as their
rivals get serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to begin to question their real support for reform,''
said Barbara Bartoletti, state legislative director for the League
of Women Voters. ``If you are serious about reform, you take these
proposals as a starting point and you talk.''
</P>
<P>
   People close to Bruno acknowledge his political motivation. The
Republicans, who hold the Senate by a 36-to-25 margin, are worried
about next year's elections, and Bruno will do whatever he can to
make his group more popular.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly Democrats, with an overwhelming 98-to-52 advantage
in their house, have less to worry about, and they know it.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, there is little heartfelt support in either house
for reforming the lobbying law, though lawmakers are loath to say
so on the record. While they got a raise this year, to an average
of about $90,000, legislators still enjoy being wined and dined.
</P>
<P>
   ``They view this as a perk of the job,'' said Blair Horner,
legislative director of the New York Public Interest Research
Group. Horner agreed that the onus was now on Silver and refused to
question Bruno's sincerity. ``If I worried about people's motives
in Albany, I would spend all my day thinking about it, and I would
be very unhappy,'' Horner said.
</P>
<P>
   Silver's office declined to comment for the record, but people
close to the speaker said they were aware that the whole episode
could make the Democrats look bad and that he would make his own
counterproposal for reforming the lobbying law.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pataki has so far managed to have it both ways. He professes
distaste for the current system but does not say how to change it.
But people close to Bruno think the governor will have a hard time
accepting one of the senator's central ideas: that lobbyists should
have to disclose publicly the work they do to influence the
agencies the governor controls, just as they report their
legislative lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   Reform is a relative concept in Albany, where phrases like ``the
slowest,'' ``the most secretive'' and ``the most dysfunctional''
are routinely used to describe lawmaking, and the lobbying law is
among the weakest in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Fundamental change is rare here, and it is usually brought on by
crisis or embarrassment. The legislative ethics law was passed a
decade ago only after scandals brought down some powerful
Democratic legislators. State Republicans changed the notoriously
restrictive ballot-access rules _ and then only marginally _ after
a spate of bad publicity over their efforts to make sure that only
the party favorite, Bob Dole, appeared on the 1996 presidential
primary ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The current debate is no different. Over the summer, The New
York Times reported that Philip Morris' chief lobbyist here had
failed to report hundreds of thousands of dollars in lobbying
expenses, as required by state law. When those expenses were
disclosed last month, it turned out that they mainly involved gifts
like expensive dinners and theater tickets to scores of
legislators. It also appeared that many lawmakers broke the law in
accepting those gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The State Lobbying Commission hit Philip Morris with the largest
fine in the commission's history, $75,000 _ a paltry sum for a
giant corporation. Critics of the current law clamored for change.
</P>
<P>
   The current lobbying law expires on Dec. 31, so the Legislature
is expected to do something, if only to extend the law as is. The
Legislature might convene this week for a special session on health
care proposals, and lobbying could be on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The people who truly want change hold out hope that Bruno is
playing a game of chicken, and that Silver will not want to leap
first. But years of experience have taught them that each house
could adopt a different plan, that the two could fail to agree on
changes and that all 211 legislators could then run for re-election
next year while proclaiming, ``I voted for lobbying reform.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
