<HEADLINE>
IRVING BERELSON, LAWYER AND PHILANTHROPIST, 83 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Irving Passon Berelson, a retired lawyer and
philanthropist, died Dec. 5 at his home on the Upper East Side of
Manhattan. He was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Berelson retired in 1995 as a senior partner at the Manhattan
law firm Parker Chapin Flattau &AMP; Klimpl, which he joined in 1943.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Brooklyn, he graduated from New York University in
1937 and from Harvard Law School in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   He had a long association with the Metropolitan Opera, and
became an advisory director in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   He had also been president of the League for the Hard of
Hearing, and backed the New York Philharmonic program of children's
concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Berelson is survived by his wife of 60 years, Thelma Dorfman
Berelson; a daughter, Ellen Berelson of Alexandria, Va.; and a
brother, Elliot, of New Springville, Staten Island.
</P>
</TEXT>
