<HEADLINE>
STANLEY SHIRK, COMPTROLLER OF CURRENCY NOMINEE, DIES AT 83
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Conn.)   (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stanley E. Shirk, a former executive at the
accounting firm KPMG who was once nominated to be comptroller of
the currency, died Dec. 7 at a hospital in Manhattan. He was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Shirk, who lived in West Cornwall, Conn., was born in Brooklyn
and graduated from St. John's University.
</P>
<P>
   He began his career with Barrow Wade Guthrie &AMP; Co., which in
1950 merged with Peat, Marwick, Mitchell &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring from the firm in 1976, Shirk was nominated by
President Gerald Ford to become comptroller of the currency.
However, congressional hearings were never held on the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Barbara; a daughter, Susan Shirk of
La Jolla, Calif.; a son, Richard Shirk of Manhattan, and two
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
