<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIKERS-FOUND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIKERS, STRANDED OVERNIGHT, FIND THEIR WAY TO SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KERA RITTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two hikers emerged safely from a trail on Mount Washington in
New Hampshire Sunday morning after driving snow and
125-mile-an-hour wind gusts forced them to spend the night under
railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Arnao, 35, of Glen Rocks, N.J., and Victor Barres, 35, of
Hasbrouck Heights, N.J., stumbled into the summit weather
observatory at 7:30 a.m., as a team of rescuers from the New
Hampshire Fish and Game Department headed up the mountain searching
for them, uncertain of their fate.
</P>
<P>
   Both were in good condition and were transported down the
mountain Sunday, said Sarah Curtis, a meteorologist at the
observatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have gone either way,'' Curtis said. ``People weren't
exactly sure how prepared they were, where they were located, or
exactly what their condition was. People have perished in a lot
better and survived in a lot worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The men, both moderately experienced hikers, drove all night
Friday and started hiking up the Jewell Trail about 10 a.m.
Saturday. The summit is 6,288 feet, the highest peak in the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   About 5:30 p.m. the men called 911 on a cellular phone and said
they were in trouble. The temperature had dipped to 20 degrees.
Almost 10 inches of snow had fallen. Wind gusts of 125 miles an
hour were knocking them over, and visibility was zero.
</P>
<P>
   Although they were just 100 feet from the summit observatory,
they could not see it.
</P>
<P>
   The Appalachian Mountain Club called them back and advised they
head back down the mountain, but the men reported they were unable.
</P>
<P>
   By 7:30 p.m., Fish and Game decided conditions were too severe
to launch a rescue and advised the men hunker down below the tree
line. The two said they were unable to make it and crawled into a
space two feet high under the Cog Railroad, wrapping up in their
sleeping bags. A steam engine runs up the tracks during the warmer
months carrying tourists.
</P>
<P>
   One of the men then called his wife to report their location and
said they would not be rescued that night.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday morning, conditions had improved and the hikers
followed the light on the observatory tower to safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little surprised to see them when they stumbled into
the building,'' Curtis said. ``Fish and Game had started up the
mountain at 5 a.m., so we expected them all to come up or we would
head down.''
</P>
<P>
   Both were exhausted but neither needed medical attention, Curtis
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One was shivering but we gave them hot Tang and that subsided
quickly,'' Curtis said. ``They gave them dry clothes and they were
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the men had food, water, sleeping bags, and heavy
coats, Curtis said they were unprepared and lucky to be alive.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis said increasing numbers of hikers are relying on cellular
phones instead of proper planning. Inexperienced climbers often
gain a false sense of security and later find themselves in trouble
when darkness falls or weather conditions change.
</P>
<P>
   As in the situation Saturday night, rescuers cannot always reach
hikers immediately, and the risk of death and injury increases. ``A
cell phone is not insurance,'' Curtis said.
</P>
<P>
   The two New Jersey hikers did not heed a wind advisory that
caused several hikers to turn around, including a tour group with
reservations at the summit observatory. One of the men was wearing
three-season leather boots instead of mountain boots. They did not
have a tent, stove, or wind- and water-resistant covers for their
sleeping bags, all necessities, Curtis said.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures at the summit are often 30 degrees colder than at
valley level, with strong wind gusts. Several hikers have died on
the mountain, and each year others become stranded after changes in
the weather.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 124 fatalities on and around Mount Washington
since 1849, many of them involving ill-prepared hikers, skiers, and
climbers. Steve Carmody, 29, of Danbury, Conn., was the last
fatality on the mountain. He fell to his death on Sept. 27, 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
