<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6907 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     12-12 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS WITHOUT A CLUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Los Angeles Dodgers have a plan, it's seriously
encrypted. Hackers who can tap into the Pentagon's X-Files and
download Bill Gates' memos would be stumped by the Dodgers'
well-cloaked strategy. If the Germans had access to the Dodgers'
system during World War II, we'd all be eating schnitzel.
</P>
<P>
   The only discernible surface clue to all of their moves is a
faint outline of the domino theory -- every action relates to the
previous action.
</P>
<P>
   But this couldn't be. The Dodgers have been a major league
franchise for more than a century. Their ``plan'' couldn't possibly
be this simple-minded, right?
</P>
<P>
   Right?
</P>
<P>
   One has to wonder. Sunday's trade of Ismael Valdes and Eric
Young to the Chicago Cubs won't break many hearts in Los Angeles.
Valdes usually became faint at the mere sight of the eighth inning,
and Davey Johnson had no use for Young. Eric's a sweetheart, but
Johnson hated his bad footwork in the field and didn't put much
value on his stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   But this trade doesn't solve any problems, other than financial.
The Dodgers got one major league pitcher in the deal, reliever
Terry Adams, who is often wild and just a setup man.
</P>
<P>
   No, this trade is just the latest reactionary move that can be
traced back to May of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Foxies can't sign Mike Piazza, so they trade him and the
underrated Todd Zeile for a kettle of fish, including Gary
Sheffield, a player with the kind of contract ($10 million a year,
six years) Piazza wanted. Only one player remains from that deal,
Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   -- Deluded into thinking they could win despite having traded
their best player, prospects leave in exchange for veterans
requiring new, expensive contracts, Jeff Shaw, Mark Grudzielanek
and Carlos Perez.
</P>
<P>
   -- Davey Johnson is hired, demands a left-handed hitter, so
Charles Johnson and Roger Cedeno go to New York for the damaged
Todd Hundley. Elderley (37 this month) switch-hitter Devon White is
given a three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   -- Dodgers throw money at Kevin Brown. Team chooses not to
resign the rehabilitating Ramon Martinez, removing vital Latin
security blanket in the locker room. Dave Mlicki, obtained for
Hideo Nomo, is given away for one of the Marx brothers, Checo.
</P>
<P>
   -- Mondesi goes Krakatoa, leading to the trade for the
appropriately named Shawn Green, leading to salary dumping of
Valdes and Young.
</P>
<P>
   Since this descent began, six pitchers have been traded or
dumped -- Martinez, Hideo Nomo, Mlicki (obtained for Nomo), Dennis
Reyes, Ted Lilly and now Valdes -- and only three remain from the
1998 opening day roster, Chan Ho Park, Darren Dreifort and the
injured Antonio Osuna.
</P>
<P>
   That's mind-numbing, because pitching wasn't considered a
weakness until these changes began. Only one pitcher obtained in
those deals has contributed, closer Jeff Shaw. The Dodgers were
forced to get 347 innings of work last season from the firm of
Arnold, Bochtler, Borbon, Checo, Maddux (not Greg), Masaoka, Mills
and Rojas. This doesn't include some of the rookies who will now
compete for Valdes' starting job -- Eric Gagne, Matt Herges, Mike
Judd, Jeff Kubenka and Jeff Williams.
</P>
<P>
   And the Dodgers may not be done dealing, either. They're still
considering deals for Dreifort, and they'll know by Christmas if
Adrian Beltre will stay under their tree or leave without
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to say things have been choatic and leave it at that.
But G.M. Kevin Malone has been on watch long enough to bear some
burden. He may have been shrewd keeping the Expos afloat, but he's
drowning in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   He was badly abused by two agents, Scott Boras in the Brown deal
and Jeffrey Moorad in the Green-Mondesi trade, and the Mets
suckered him into taking the damaged Hundley. Now he's let Mlicki,
Valdes and Young go without compensation.
</P>
<P>
   He also lacks vision.
</P>
<P>
   If we are indeed in a transient player era, where the five-year
plan is anachronistic and a dynasty is back-to-back playoff visits,
then why didn't Malone step boldly into this new world instead of
straddling it?
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, staring at losing both Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex
Rodriguez after this season, are accepting trade offers but won't
let any interested teams negotiate a contract beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   That's a major obstacle ... unless your team hasn't won a
post-season game since 1988 and is going to lead the league in
salary anyway. If Malone and the Dodgers are serious about winning
now, they should have called the Mariners and asked them exactly
what they wanted for both future Hall of Famers.
</P>
<P>
   Two starting pitchers, Valdes and Dreifort? Fine. Some prospects
who can play soon, like catcher Angel Pena and shortstop Mike
Metcalfe? Done, pick anyone in the system except Chin-Feng Chen.
Two more young pitchers? Great, pick two from the above list. A few
young vets to fill some holes? Sure, take Young, Mark Grudzielanek
and Todd Hollandsworth.
</P>
<P>
   Not enough? OK, throw in Todd Hundley and Devon White, and we'll
cover the last year of their deals.
</P>
<P>
   What's the worse that could happen? Another 77-85 season?
Another year without a playoff? A payroll that could circle the
globe? So what if the Dodgers crack the $100 million barrier in
payroll? Other teams already hate the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   And even if Griffey and Rodriguez happen to make L.A. a one-year
layover enroute to becoming the first player-owner elsewhere,
wouldn't it be worth a shot? I'm guessing the fan base in town
would step up to the plate at a rate of 45,000 a game, and buy a
jersey or two.
</P>
<P>
   I'd also guess Griffey and A-Rod would kind of dig the scene
themselves. They would arrive with a one-item agenda: Win a World
Series. Now. No regrets thereafter. Plan to move on? Thanks for the
visit, it was real.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey and A-Rod in the same lineup with Eric Karros, Shawn
Green, Gary Sheffield and maybe Beltre. Platoons elsewhere. Brown,
Park and a combo of rookies and journeymen in the rotation, and
Shaw to close. Let's see how they like that in San Francisco and
San Diego, and who cares what Brian Sabean and Kevin Towers have to
say?
</P>
<P>
   Alas, no one in Dodger Blue has this kind of vision. Instead,
the team will forge ahead with the current plan -- size up the hole
the last move has created, and then dig a deeper hole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-99 2256EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991212.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7029 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-AUTISM2-AZR &LR;      12-12 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTISM2-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPARENT IMPROVEMENT IN AUTISTIC CHILDREN HAS PARENTS PUSHING FOR
FURTHER DRUG STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JODIE SNYDER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX0 - Days after her first secretin injection last year,
Rebecca David slept until 7:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   It was a remarkable development for a girl who for years had
been rousing her parents at 4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca's family, along with several dozen others in the Phoenix
area, called the Southwest Autism Research Center in Phoenix with
the good news: Their autistic children were sleeping better, eating
better, communicating more easily.
</P>
<P>
   The parents attributed the differences to secretin, a drug they
hoped would help free their children from &UR; autism, a developmental
disorder that has baffled researchers for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one problem: Almost all the 30 Phoenix area
children in the yearlong clinical trial of secretin reported great
results _ even though a third had received a placebo.
</P>
<P>
   Because the center's study was double-blinded, neither
researchers nor parents knew who got the real secretin until the
end.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the old familiar sadness returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we broke the code (to find who received the real
injections), we were stunned,'' said Dr. Cindy Schneider. There was
no correlation between who got the drug and who improved.
</P>
<P>
   A study published in Thursday's, Dec. 9, New England Journal of
Medicine echoed the Phoenix center's findings: No difference
between placebos and secretin.
</P>
<P>
   The results convinced the National Institutes of Health to
recommend halting the use of secretin until more tests can be done.
Doctors expressed concern that children could be getting dangerous
doses.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; But researchers and parents say it's not over yet.
</P>
<P>
   Secretin has helped too many children improve for them to stop
using it, they say.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Secretin is a pancreatic-stimulating hormone produced by the
small intestine. It is only approved by the Food and Drug
Administration for tests of the digestive system.
</P>
<P>
   But when an autistic New Hampshire boy made startling progress
last year after receiving it, parents nationwide began begging for
it for their autistic children.
</P>
<P>
   The interest prompted U.S. researchers to begin controlled
tests. The study in Phoenix, which began a year ago, is one of a
dozen being conducted across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Journal study, which also was double-blinded,
involved 60 children who were given either secretin or placebos and
tested four weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider and others say the tests may have been flawed. For
example, neither study tested large amounts of secretin: The
Phoenix study gave children the amount of secretin produced after
one meal. Because it was a preliminary test, researchers wanted to
find out if it was safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like 15 diabetics who get a shot of insulin. And there's
no impact,'' Schneider said. ``That doesn't mean there is no hope
in the potential to be of benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   But future tests could be in jeopardy. Schneider worries that
investors will become jittery and will be reluctant to back
Repligen Inc., the company that holds secretin's patent. Repligen
and the center are in negotiations for more tests.
</P>
<P>
   And without more tests, desperate parents will still find ways
to get the drug. ``The trouble is, they will be using them without
proper clinical trials,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider said the center has gotten calls from 500 parents,
some as far away as Australia, who want to participate in further
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Brittany Done of Carefree, for example, is resolved to get
another injection for her son Alex, 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've read the studies, and I'm not impressed. I saw what I
saw, and I know this helped my son.''
</P>
<P>
   After the first injection, her son's diarrhea stopped. He
started sleeping eight hours a night rather than in two-hour
snatches. He blurted out new words: purple, dog, cat.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, he started to look her in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like `Oh, there you are. I see you now,' '' his mother
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teachers didn't know he was on the drug, but they called
me up to ask me what was going on. He was so much more focused and
paying attention.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Done wants that little boy back, and despite what researchers
say, she said, she will get him more secretin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not letting this drop,'' she said. ``This is just way too
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Both of Karen Jason's children, Rebecca, now 9, and Sean, now 7,
were in the trials. The two Phoenix children got their first dose
of secretin in November 1998. They got a second dose in June.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weeks after the first injection, both children seemed
different. Rebecca slept through the night; Sean went to bed
earlier and seemed more interested in people.
</P>
<P>
   During Rebecca's birthday party in July, Sean helped her open
gifts _ a far cry from the boy who had seemed oblivious just a few
weeks before when his big sister screamed during her injections.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, however, Rebecca has returned to her nocturnal ways,
rising before daybreak. She walks around with her fingers and toes
crossed for stimulation.
</P>
<P>
   She does what her mother calls ``eeee-runs,'' in which she
charges, her head tilted down, arms flapping, and crying,
``Eeeee!''
</P>
<P>
   The kids at her new special school tease her, but the
fourth-grader doesn't notice. She's still never been invited to a
birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   She does seem to have developed a sense of humor, though. Making
human-body noises now gives her the giggles.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother said she worked all year to find her daughter's funny
bone. ``She knows to laugh, but maybe she still doesn't know why
it's funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason believes her son, Sean, is different in other ways. He
still engages in ``video talk'' _ using lines from movies to
communicate _ but now he'll grab a person's hand and give stage
direction as if he wants company in a private production.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hallelujah,'' he'll tell them.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a year of big change for Jason. She got a divorce and
received custody of the children. Rebecca and Sean _ usually
sensitive to changes in routine _ seem OK with the differences, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just keep going along,'' Jason said. ``Sometimes day by
day.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Mary O'Neal &UR; of Scottsdale, the days since the injections
have been ``two steps forward and three steps back.''
</P>
<P>
   Although secretin didn't seem to affect her son, Evan, 4, he did
change _ just as any child changes over the course of a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still isn't saying anything. He won't make eye contact,''
his mother said. ``But he can tell when something's different in
the room.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, O'Neal's younger son has been diagnosed with delayed
speech. At 20 months, Tim has the ability of a 10-month-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors told me that whatever it is, it's not autism,''
Mary O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   She remains determined to teach Evan to communicate. In addition
to the picture cards they used last year, they're trying sign
language. It could take hundreds of tries before Evan learns to
communicate one word, his mother said.
</P>
<P>
   That's a far cry from the instant gratification offered by
secretin, which O'Neal and other parents literally wrestled their
kids into receiving.
</P>
<P>
   Although grateful for being in the study, Mary O'Neal now
believes that the only miracles will come incrementally, day by
day.
</P>
<P>
   The hard way.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this, you always have to have one foot in reality,'' she
said. ``You can be hopeful. For your own sanity, you have to be
hopeful. But you have to be realistic.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
