and more franchises on board. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- Dec. 12, 1999 -- SATELLITE-TV -- DirecTV's
president Eddy Hartenstein, left, hails the end of rebroadcasting
restrictions. EchoStar's chairman, Charles W. Ergen pushed to be
allowed to offer local TV. DirecTV, with about 8 million
subscribers, and EchoStar, with about 3 million, may have to spend
as much as $1 billion to deliver local stations, including local
affiliates of the four big broadcast networks, to dozens of markets
nationwide. (Ruby Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) SEATTLE -- Dec. 12, 1999 -- ONLINE-PRIVACY -- Kirk
Bailey, manager of information security at the Regence Group, an
alliance of health insurance plans. In October, Bailey dared a
group of security experts to spend two months trying to dig up as
much as they could about him. Their only constraints were to stay
within the confines of the law and to avoid asking his family or
friends for help. Bailey was thoroughly surprised by how much of
his personal information was available by through the Internet.
(Robert Sorbo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Dec. 12, 1999 -- GOLDMAN-EUROPE -- Scott
Mead, left, and Robert S. Harrison are co-heads of Goldman Sachs'
global communications, media and entertainment group. This year,
Goldman has been an adviser on $239 billion of telecommunications
mergers in Europe. That represents an almost fourfold increase over
1998, according to Thompson Financial Securities Data, and enough
to propel it from No. 11 to No. 1 on the list of bankers in
European telecommunications mergers. (Jeffrey A. Salter/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) INDIANAPOLIS -- Dec. 12, 1999 -- PLANE-MAINTENANCE-1 --
Terry Shepperd examines a door for a Boeing 737, tail No. N-1383.
The managing director of United Airlines' maintenance center,
Frederick L. Mohr, calls N-1383 a ``pretty good airplane.'' Still,
the N-1383 in question needed about 50 changes, plus extensive
routine maintenance. N-1383 has been inspected and modified several
times because of the discovery of flaws in fuel tank wiring in
other 737s, in inspections brought on by the explosion of the TWA
747, Flight 800, after it took off from Kennedy Airport in New York
in July 1996. (Mary Ann Carter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) INDIANAPOLIS -- Dec. 12, 1999 -- PLANE-MAINTENANCE-2 --
On a maintenance stop, a Boeing 737, tail No. N-1383, has corrosion
removed from the cabin floor by Matt Hurst. Although passenger jets
are almost always in need of work, the N-1383 in question needed
about 50 changes, plus extensive routine maintenance. N-1383 has
been inspected and modified several times because of the discovery
of flaws in fuel tank wiring in other 737s, in inspections brought
on by the explosion of the TWA 747, Flight 800, after it took off
from Kennedy Airport in New York in July 1996. (Mary Ann Carter/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) INDIANAPOLIS -- Dec. 12, 1999 -- PLANE-MAINTENANCE-3 --
Frederick L. Mohr, managing director of United Airlines'
maintenance center, examines new radar for a Boeing 737, tail No.
N-1383. Altough updates of equipment on passenger jets are routine,
the plane's maintenance report over the past month formed a
computer printout about 15 feet long, and the Federal Aviation
Administration, in response to airplane crashes, had demanded that
United Airlines, the plane's operator, install a better flight data
recorder and a firefighting system in the cargo holds. In all, the
plane needed about 50 changes, plus extensive routine maintenance.
(Mary Ann Carter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 12, 1999 -- KOSKINEN-PROFILE -- John
A. Koskinen will be keeping a close eye on the changeover to 2000.
Koskinen, who holds the formal title of chairman of President
Clinton's Council on Year 2000 Conversion is better known around
the White House as Clinton's Y2K czar. ``I'll be in the middle of
all sorts of stuff.'' At 11:59 and 59 seconds on the night of Dec.
31, Koskinen says, he will be stone sober and seated in a specially
built glass-walled war room in downtown Washington, where a staff
of more than 100 will keep watch on the global changeover to a new
year, a new century, a new millennium. (Paul Hosefros/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) KAVKAZ CHECKPOINT, Russia -- Dec. 12, 1999 --
RUSSIA-CHECHNYA -- Sergei Shoigu, Russia's minister for emergency
situations and the leader of a Kremlin-backed party in next
weekend's parliamentary elections, trying to arrange the evacuation
of refugees from Grozny on Saturday. The ostensible purpose was to
inaugurate a new humanitarian corridor for the thousands of
civilians trapped in the city, which Russian forces have pounded
for weeks. Although the search for fleeing refugees proved
unsuccessful, Shoigu pledged his undying efforts to help save
civilian lives. (James Hill/The New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Dec. 12, 1999 -- ECOMMERCE-WRONG-PRICES --
Don Blate, right, a Brookstone area manager, helped a customer on
the phone find a product on the company's Web site. Brookstone
relies on a team of employees to verify that prices posted online
are correct. When a pricing error does occur on a Brookstone site,
a situation that has yet to happen, Brookstone ``will appeal to the
reasonable expectations of our customers,'' says Michael Anthony,
chief executive of Brookstone, adding that ``most people are
reasonable.'' ``It also helps that we have one price on our items,
no matter how you buy them, so there's less of a chance of a
mixup.'' (Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Dec. 12, 1999 -- SIDE-SHOW-ACTORS-2 -- Emily
Skinner, left, and Alice Ripley, center, in a September rehersal of
``James Joyce's 'The Dead,''' the musical adaptation of the Joyce
short story at the Belasco Theater. Ms. Ripley plays Miss Molly
Ivors, a spunky Irish lass whose flirtation raises the body
temperature of Gabriel Conroy, the play's central character, played
by Christopher Walken. Ms. Skinner, meanwhile, is Mary Jane, a
kindly niece whose Christmas celebration sets the scene for the
play. The two characters never speak directly to each other.(Sara
Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Dec. 12, 1999 -- SIDE-SHOW-ACTORS-1 -- Emily
Skinner and Alica Ripley, Siamese Twins in ``Side Show,'' return to
Broadway once again in ``James Joyce's 'The Dead'''. Hint: Ms.
Ripley is seated and at right, in photo at right. It was just two
years ago that Ms. Skinner and Ms. Ripley burst onto Broadway
literally connected at the hip. Though ``Side Show'' lasted only
seven weeks, the Broadway community's mental connection between Ms.
Skinner and Ms. Ripley has endured. And that association is likely
to intensify now that the two find themselves on Broadway again in
``The Dead,'' the musical adaptation of the Joyce short story.
(Jeffrey A. Salter, left, Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
