<DOCNO> NYT19991212.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-WOMENS-FOOTBALL-ART-N     12-12 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMENS-FOOTBALL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO WOMEN'S SPORTS, ADD PRO FOOTBALL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Ill., Texas)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ The ladies couldn't throw, at least not as
much as they wanted to, in 40 mph gusts. The wind kept them from
kicking, too. So the New York Sharks, full of adrenaline and
athleticism, used a mean running game to defeat the Minnesota
Vixens, 12-6.
</P>
<P>
   It was a momentous day, especially for the Sharks, a squad that
put on the pads only about three weeks ago. The Vixens, members of
the Women's Professional Football League, have four games under
their belts, and have been on the field since the beginning of
October on a barnstorming tour to gauge the interest in and
audience for what the league advertises as ``high quality smash
mouth tackle football.''
</P>
<P>
   While the cold crowd at the 12,000-seat Mitchel Athletic Complex
here dwindled from just 300 to less than half that after halftime,
the players' enthusiasm was as strong as a blindside tackle,
judging from the post-game euphoria in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we've wanted to do all our lives,'' said
Lori DeVivio, 30, a wide receiver from Brooklyn. ``We're fulfilling
a fantasy that we never, ever thought would come true.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vixens roster includes a former Olympian _ Wendy Brown, who
was on the 1988 U.S. Olympic track and field team _ plus a NASA
engineer, three police officers and a World Cup rugby player. The
Sharks, who range in age from 25 to 49, include two lawyers, an
electrician and a construction worker known for her aggression.
(``You can see death in her eyes,'' one referee said.)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Sharks have been practicing tackle football for the
last 2 1-2 months, two or three times a week. Most were members of
the Long Island Sharks, a flag football team. In that noncontact
version of the sport, players ``tackle'' one another by pulling off
one of two flags worn on a belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we get the chance to put on the pads and really hit
someone,'' said Alinda Mitchell, 33, of Harlem, who plays defensive
tackle and is known on the team as Big Dog. In a practice she broke
her leg in three places, and her teammates wear her number, 99, on
their helmets in her honor. Like many Sharks, she prefers tackling
an opponent to pulling a flag off of her.
</P>
<P>
   ``You felt you were holding back,'' she said of playing flag
football.
</P>
<P>
   Members of both teams, who have nicknames like Smackie, Major,
Trigger and Tonka (as in truck), said the padding took getting used
to.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I thought football was a pansy sport, because of the
pads,'' said Jodi Anderson of the Vixens, who played rugby in
college. Now she finds football more painful, because of all the
protective gear: ``The pads cut into your arms. My neck hurt for a
week after wearing this 15-pound helmet.''
</P>
<P>
   Their second-hand equipment comes from semipro and high school
teams, and is often too big. Some of the women gathered the extra
fabric at the bottom of their football pants in knots, for a
snugger fit. Their football is one inch smaller in diameter, for
smaller hands.
</P>
<P>
   Women's football is not a new invention. In 1926, the Frankford
Yellow Jackets _ the forerunners of today's Philadelphia Eagles of
the N FL _ used a women's team as its halftime entertainment. In
1974, the National Women's Football League was formed, with teams
including the Dallas Bluebonnets and the Los Angeles Dandelions; it
expanded with the Philadelphia Queen Bees and the Tulsa Babes,
among other teams, but fell on hard times by the mid 1980s,
according to an essay included in Saturday night's program.
American football for women has fared better internationally, with
leagues in Germany and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Building on the success of women's basketball and women's
soccer, Terry Sullivan, a backer of minor league football teams,
and Carter Turner, the owner of the St. Paul Pigs, the 1999
Mid-America Football League champs, created the Women's
Professional Football League this year. They hope that the league's
teams will generate enough interest to bring sponsors and more
franchises on board.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only two teams _ the Vixens and the Lake Michigan Minx
of Chicago, have played league games, and two other teams, the
Sharks and a team in Dallas, are preparing to join the league. The
players are paid about $100 a game, along with traveling expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the game, the terminology was decidedly old school.
The players were most often ladies, as in, ``Ladies, dives and
options are the same,'' they were coached at halftime. They were
occasionally girls, but never women. ``Girls, ladies, we don't
care. It's all the same,'' Ms. Mitchell said. ``We just want to
play some football.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks played with heart, tackling hard, with defense that
stopped the Vixens cold. Men's games might be faster, cleaner and
sharper, but then some men have been playing football since they
were 4, said Julie Crotty, 35, a spectator from Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Among the fans, who huddled under blankets and quietly cursed
the sun for setting, there were a few who wondered if women's
football would _ or even should _ catch on.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to do football professionally, you need to do flag
football,'' said Portia Lack of Wantagh, 38, a spectator who plays
the nontackle game. ``It sounds bad, but people in general, guys
and gals, still want to see women look like women.'' In flag
football, which requires no bulky equipment, she said, ``You can
see that they're girls, that they have faces and pony tails and
legs.''
</P>
<P>
   What these girls _ or ladies _ had by the end of the hour of
play Saturday were uniforms stained with grass, dirt and blood.
When it was all over, the Sharks' 5-foot 5-inch quarterback, Val
Halesworth, 33, who threw a pass on a 70-yard play for the winning
touchdown, held her helmet in the air and yelled, ``That's
football, ladies!''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out she had been voted Most Valuable Player for four out
of her five seasons on boys' football teams, from age 8 to 14. A
crowd of reporters asked her what happened then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got breasts, and I didn't think I was supposed to play
football,'' she said. But Saturday night she played both offense
and defense, at one point stripping the ball from the Vixens at the
Sharks goal line and returning it 35 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best day in my life,'' she said as she headed
toward the locker room.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
