<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL BY FIRE FOR UCLA'S WATSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Earl Watson played fabulous defense against
Gonzaga, his first test as UCLA's starting point guard. He also had
eight rebounds, four assists and nine points _ solid numbers for a
floor leader.
</P>
<P>
   But there's only one statistic Watson will remember, only one
that really counts: seven turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played as poorly as I could have,'' Watson said dejectedly
in UCLA's locker room following a 59-43 loss Saturday to Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   For the Bruins (3-1) to be the best they can be this season, for
them to challenge for the Pacific-10 title and make an impact in
March, Watson must become a disciplined, dependable point guard. He
must distribute the ball to the right players in the right places.
He must make shrewd decisions on the fast break. And he must bring
order to the chaotic half-court offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earl's the key,'' Bruins forward Rico Hines said. ``We're one
big person, and he's the head. He's got to make sure we run the
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The body can't function with its head in a daze, and Watson
admitted Saturday that he's struggling without sidekick Baron
Davis, a point guard extraordinaire whose presence enabled Watson
to play off-guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is that last year I'd guard the top (opposing)
guard and I didn't have to play point guard,'' Watson said. ``This
year, I have to guard the top guard and play point. I'm definitely
tired. I've never played point guard.''
</P>
<P>
   For UCLA's sake, he'd better learn fast.
</P>
<P>
   Miss him already: Suspended forward JaRon Rush wouldn't have
helped UCLA's abysmal 3-point shooting against Gonzaga (4 of 26)
because he's a poor long-range shooter himself (26.5 percent last
year, 33.3 this season).
</P>
<P>
   But Rush's specialties are energy and rebounding, and the Bruins
desperately needed both Saturday afternoon. They were outplayed on
the frontline and showed a shocking lack of the spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really miss him,'' Watson said. ``We depend on him so
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Century mark: Saturday was Steve Lavin's 100th game as head
coach. He's 73-27 in a little more than three seasons, with one
Pac-10 title and five NCAA Tournament victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hundred games, and I've aged 100 years,'' he said _ and that
was before the Gonzaga disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The week ahead: Because of exams, the Bruins will practice at 5
a.m. this week _ a routine Lavin has used throughout his tenure. It
frees the afternoons and evenings for test-taking and studying, and
it assures the players are in bed at a reasonable hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, it's tough,'' Lavin said of the practices, ``but
once they get going, they're OK. You've got to jump-start them.''
</P>
<P>
   Same old story: Of UCLA's myriad deficiencies, executing against
zone defenses might top the list. Detroit Mercy zoned the Bruins
out of the NCAA Tournament last year, Gonzaga's zone snuffed them
Saturday and they'll probably see zone after zone this season _ at
least until they score against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams are going to zone us,'' Hines said. ``Every shot was
tough (against Gonzaga). We didn't get in the flow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
