<HEADER>
A7045 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-KIDBOOKS-AZR &LR;      12-12 0349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDBOOKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS THAT WILL GIVE YOUNG READERS HOURS OF ENJOYMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are some books that young readers will enjoy:
</P>
<P>
   ``THE HAT: THE HEDGIE GIFT BOX'' &QL; 
Jan Brett &QL; 
(G.P. Putnam's Sons, $16.99) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brett's 1997 charmer about a cute little hedgehog is freshly
packaged into a gift box with a stuffed toy hedgehog just in time
for the Christmas season.
</P>
<P>
   The story centers on Hedgie, who crawls inside a sock that blows
off a clothesline. As the other animals poke fun at him, Hedgie
proudly proclaims that he's wearing a hat to keep warm in the snow.
Not a bad idea, they think. Soon the clothes line is stripped bare.
</P>
<P>
   Brett's colorful, realistic illustrations appeal to young
children. Her trademark border pictures add another layer of
meaning to the tale. For ages 2-5. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``FINGER PUPPET THEATER: THE THREE LITTLE PIGS'' &QL; 
Illustrated by Peter Stevenson (Scholastic, $13.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What a great idea! Finger puppets, board books and fairy tales _
all wrapped up in one package. Scholastic's Finger Puppet Theater
series also includes Hansel and Gretel, Goldilocks and the Little
Red Riding Hood.
</P>
<P>
   Four finger puppet characters come with each story, which
children act out using the sturdy board book pages as a stage.
Lively text and amusing pictures carry the plots.
</P>
<P>
   Young imaginations will soar! For ages 3-7. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``MORRIS'S DISAPPEARING BAG'' &QL; 
Rosemary Wells (Viking, $15.99) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Author of more than 60 children's books, Wells and her beloved
bunny Morris always are a hit. This tale begins on Christmas
morning. Morris' brother Victor gets a hockey outfit. His sister
Rose gets a beauty kit. His sister Betty gets a chemistry set.
Hands off, they say to Morris, who gets a teddy bear.
</P>
<P>
   Then Morris discovers one last gift left under the tree, which
leads to much merriment. The adorable pictures of the bunny family
are funny and captivating. For ages 3-7. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Beverly Medlyn can be reached at (602) 444-8213 or at
bev.medlyn(at)arizonarepublic.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-99 2330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991212.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7052 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-OMNI-AWARDS-KAN &LR;      12-12 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OMNI-AWARDS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JENNIFER MANN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Advertising awards posters offensive to some  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A trio of provocative posters sent to area
advertising agencies has sparked a controversy both inside and
outside the industry _ from People for the Ethical Treatment of
Animals to the Midwest Transplant Network.
</P>
<P>
   The pieces were created to alert agencies to the upcoming Omni
advertising awards program in February, which are presented
annually by the Advertising Club of Kansas City. The theme of the
pieces: ``What Would You Do For An Omni?''
</P>
<P>
   The posters were designed for the Advertising Club by John
January, Tug McTighe and Paul Diamond, all of Sullivan Higdon &AMP;
Sink in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   According to the trio's interpretation, people would rip off an
award-winning campaign, blow up a kitten in a microwave or give
away a kidney, all to win an Omni.
</P>
<P>
   It's the latter two that have some people up in arms.
</P>
<P>
   January said the premise for the series came from sitting in a
darkened ballroom each year, watching rivals and peers stream to
the podium, receiving awards and accolades.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to say to yourself, `I'd do anything for an
Omni,' &UR; '' January said. ``We thought the examples were so absurd
that they were funny _ our intent was to lampoon the exaggerated
importance that winning a creative award often has.''
</P>
<P>
   The local advertising community, however, is split over the
intent and effectiveness of the pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Courtney, an art director at Bernstein-Rein Advertising,
said he thought the concept was brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to remember, this is a pretty jaded audience that
you're trying to capture the attention of,'' said Courtney, ``and I
certainly think they've done that.''
</P>
<P>
   But for others at least one of the posters is too graphic to be
considered satire.
</P>
<P>
   That one, the last in the series of three, shows a woman
kneeling on the floor of an operating room with her back to the
camera. The hospital gown she's wearing falls away, revealing a
pink-and-purple, freshly-stitched, semi-circle incision.
</P>
<P>
   Near to her is an ice chest, the words ``donor organ''
emblazoned in large red letters. Next to the cooler is a pool of
coagulated blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really pushing the envelope,'' said Tim Hamill, vice
president and creative director at Bernstein-Rein.
</P>
<P>
   The second poster in the series shows a kitten on a kitchen
counter. A trail of kitty food leads to an open microwave.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Bowers of Lee Bowers Productions was already offended by the
kitten poster. When she received the last mailing, the kidney one,
she threw it to the ground in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was deeply offended,'' Bowers said. ``I certainly wouldn't
give a kidney or blow up my kitten for an Omni.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the posters are intended to be seen only by those in
advertising, others outside the industry are perplexed and put off
by the strategy behind the posters, whether meant for their eyes or
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, people who do organ procurement work hard to
dispel these kinds of myths, that you could sell your kidney and it
ends up having a negative impact on the rate of donation,'' said
Myra Christopher, CEO of the Midwest Bioethics Center in Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Francis, spokeswoman for the Midwest Transplant Network,
said such depictions are disheartening to those in her field and
those who have donated or received a kidney.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a slap in the face,'' Francis said. ``If the
public sees this, or even your own set of colleagues, they get the
wrong information.''
</P>
<P>
   As for PETA's reaction on the kitten being enticed into the
microwave, that organization's spokesman said he was shaking his
head in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   ``People actually microwave animals, cats and dogs, to get their
kicks, so (this) glorifies a real-life tragedy,'' said Dan Matthews
of PETA in Norfolk, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secondly, I think it sort of shows when you've run out of
creativity you start getting a little destructive to get some
attention,'' Matthews said. ``Children do it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Butterworth, a Los Angeles psychologist, said the premise
of the posters doesn't surprise him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notoriety is everything,'' Butterworth said. ``Remember, shock
value only has the ability to shock for a certain amount of time
and then we become numb to it, so you have to move on to the next
level.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the call for entries is aimed at advertising peers,
these are the same people who create ads for the masses,
Butterworth said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can get away with a little more here just because of
their audience, but you see the same type of shock ads made for
general audiences, too,'' Butterworth said.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent call for Omni entries is only the latest in a
number of controversial ones, the most recent of which was two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That one showed the actual Omni, a white sphere encased in
Lucite. Trying to penetrate the Lucite to get at the ovum-like Omni
were sperm-like creatures with light bulb heads, representing
ideas. The tagline was: ``How Many of Yours Will Get In?'' That one
was tagged tacky, tasteless, sexist and silly.
</P>
<P>
   And the Public Relations Society of America created a roar in
1994, when its call for entries showed a swastika on its cover.
Type imposed over the symbol read: ``It Had A Strange Name. It Was
Ugly. It Was Created By Nazis.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon opening the brochure, there was a picture of a Volkswagen,
with the tagline: ``Never underestimate the driving force of public
relations.'' That one was deemed to make light of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   And while trying to capture the attention of an audience made up
of advertising executives is difficult, others have shown it can be
done without controversy.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, last year's call for entries, which was a mock-up
of an ad, won several awards, including a national Addy, an awards
program that had 60,000 entries.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Sullivan Higdon &AMP; Sink trio have plenty of
defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to lighten up,'' said John Q. Harrington, vice
president and creative director at NKH&AMP;W. ``This isn't Sunday
school stuff _ this is advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   And besides, said free-lance creative director John Benson,
everyone always thinks they can do a better job than the guy on the
hot seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the old joke in advertising,'' Benson said. ``How many
people does it take to create an ad? One-hundred-and-one _ one to
create the ad and 100 who said they could have done it better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-99 2343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
