<DOCNO> NYT19991212.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7053 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-SPEEDWAY-AIRPORTS-KAN     12-12 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEEDWAY-AIRPORTS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEEDWAY EXPECTED TO BRING TRAFFIC IN THE SKY AND ON THE GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ROBERT A. CRONKLETON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ Although the Kansas Speedway in Wyandotte
County won't open until 2001, there's already talk of traffic jams
on race weekends.
</P>
<P>
   But no one is complaining about the prospect of heavy traffic,
even though it could start as early as the Thursday before an
event. Nor is there griping about the mess as people head out of
town when the race is over.
</P>
<P>
   This has nothing to do with fans driving to and from the track,
which will be located near the intersection of Interstates 70 and
435 in western Wyandotte County. Instead, it will be the personal
jets and small airplanes that shuttle racing crews, drivers, owners
and sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you what, I bet (the Kansas City area airports) have no
idea what they are in for,'' said Berry Gamblin, program manager
for flight tracking software at Dimension International Inc. of
Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Gamblin's company captured the spectacle last year before a
Winston Cup race in Loudon, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   A few days before the race, the software picked up the radar
blips of more than 100 planes as they took off from North Carolina,
where most of the racing crew members live, and headed to Loudon.
</P>
<P>
   After the race, there was a mass departure, with race crews
headed back to North Carolina and sponsors back to their
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You better tell your airports that they better have plenty of
fuel,'' said James Wyatt, owner of Wyatt Aviation Service in
Homestead, Fla. ``The race weekends are also a gold mine for rental
car people.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt runs a company based at Homestead General and Homestead
Regional airports that provides car rental, catering and fueling
services for airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Last month was busy when the Pennzoil 400 was held at the
Homestead-Miami Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt said he handled about 310 airplanes, rented about 400 cars
and sold about 53,000 gallons of jet fuel in four days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really fills the town up,'' Wyatt said. ``Unfortunately, we
have only three of those races a year. I wish we could have one a
month. Still, it is unbelievable when we do have them.''
</P>
<P>
   After the race is the most hectic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The race really does not end until they reach home,'' Wyatt
said. ``The race includes trying to be the first on the taxiway to
the runway, then out to the runway and all the way back to North
Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   And the thought of all that air traffic has area airport
managers dreaming of the bonanza that might come.
</P>
<P>
   Some cities even are trying to expand their airports in hopes of
capturing a piece of the traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Boerger, director of operations for Kansas Speedway, said
it is difficult to predict how much air traffic there will be. No
formal agreements have been reached yet with auto-racing
sanctioning bodies to hold races at the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not guaranteed a Winston Cup event, which is the
granddaddy of them all,'' Boerger said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the track is trying to attract such an event, along
with a Busch Grand National race, an Indy car race and a truck
race. Schedules for the 2001 racing season will not be determined
until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Boerger said the Kansas Speedway is hoping races will take place
as often as four times a year. If that happens, Boerger said, the
track would bring in up to 1,000 planes annually.
</P>
<P>
   That amount of traffic, he said, would be similar to what
International Speedway Corp., the parent company of Kansas
Speedway, sees at its 11 other racetracks, including the Talladega
Superspeedway in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we hold a Winston Cup event at Talladega, that becomes
the busiest (regional) airport in the country,'' Boerger said.
``Air traffic increases tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   Area airport managers say they think they'll be ready to handle
the virtual air force that follows racing events. It's just a
question of where the planes choose to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to see quite a bit of traffic,'' said Lee Metcalfe,
executive director for the Johnson County (Kan.) Airport
Commission, which oversees two airports.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will come down to a matter of convenience,'' Metcalfe said.
``The racetrack will have to be nearby, and there will have to be
an availability of lodging and parking space for the planes.''
</P>
<P>
   Erica Hupp, a spokeswoman for the Kansas City Aviation
Department, said Kansas City's airports have plenty of capacity to
handle the planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need to expand any of our airports because the
capacity that we can handle is pretty high,'' Hupp said. ``We would
really welcome more flights.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Leavenworth and Lawrence are looking to expand their
airports in part so that they will be able to grab some of the
racetrack-related air traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leavenworth currently doesn't have the capacity to fuel up jet
aircraft,'' said Gary Ortiz, Leavenworth's city manager, which
leases space at Sherman Army Airfield for its airport.
</P>
<P>
   Leavenworth has exclusive rights to about eight acres of the
airfield, but wants to expand its rights to 234 acres or have the
Army cede the property to the city.
</P>
<P>
   With either of those options, Ortiz thinks the city would able
to attract some of the aircraft because the airport is about as
close to the racetrack as Lawrence is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have heard that proximity is the major determinant as to
where they will fly into,'' Ortiz said. ``They will pick the
closest place. That puts us right in the running for that if we
have expanded use of the facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lawrence is seeking $5 million in state and federal
aid for several projects at the Lawrence Municipal Airport,
including increasing the length of its runway to handle business
jets.
</P>
<P>
   While the potential to attract racetrack-related air traffic is
one reason behind the expansion, the city said the main driving
forces are economic development and the growth of general aviation.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Bryant, chairman of Lawrence's Aviation Advisory Board,
said the expansion is needed to retain businesses at the
70-year-old airport as well as attract new businesses to the
airport and Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we expand our runway, we will be able to accommodate
about 75 percent of all the business jets,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lawrence is thirsting to attract some of the air traffic
that might come because of the racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody really knows how large a fleet will be flying in for
the events,'' Bryant said. ``But we want to make sure that we get
our slice of the pie. We want our share.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
