r a BC-MOVIES-BOX-OFFICE-LAD     12-12 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TOY,' `MILE' GIVE HANKS TOP 2 SPOTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Hanks ruled at the nation's multiplexes as ``Toy Story 2''
and ``The Green Mile'' dominated a moderate weekend, with the
animated sequel edging the prison drama with an estimated
$18.7 &UR;  &LR; million at 3,238 theaters during the Friday-Sunday period,
studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toy Story 2,'' which fell only 32 &UR;  &LR; percent from the previous
weekend, has taken in an impressive $140.8 &UR;  &LR; million overall as it
topped the box office for three consecutive weekends. With Hanks
reprising his role as the voice of Woody, the sequel looks likely
to become the 29th member of the $200 &UR;  &LR; million club by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Disney distribution chief Chuck Viane said ``Toy Story 2'' is
continuing to draw well among all demographics. ``We are seeing
strong numbers for the 9 p.m. and 10 p.m. shows, which means it's
playing very well to adults,'' he added. ``We think some of its
best days are ahead of it around Christmas week.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros.' opening of ``The Green Mile,'' with Hanks
portraying a prison guard on Death Row during the 1930s, finished a
close second with $18.6 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,875 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers said the returns were respectable, given its
three-hour running time and ultraserious subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   With a difference of under 1 &UR;  &LR; percent between the top two films,
it remains quite possible for ``The Green Mile'' to emerge as the
weekend winner today when final numbers for the Friday-Sunday
period are released.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no surprise that `Toy Story 2' continues to perform well,
but the numbers for `The Green Mile' are a tribute to the pulling
power of Tom Hanks,'' said longtime tracker Arthur Rockwell.
``Serious pictures don't always have a wide audience so I'd also
say this has been well-marketed by Warner Bros.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner distribution chief Dan Fellman said moviegoers polled
after seeing ``The Green Mile'' had given it outstanding scores
with 97 &UR;  &LR; percent saying they would recommend it. ``These are the
best exit polls we've ever had,'' he declared. ``It really is the
people's choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source tracking service,
said ``The Green Mile'' should perform well through the holiday
season, particularly given its status as a leading Academy Awards
candidate and the strong word-of-mouth among moviegoers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're about 10 days away from the period of heavy
moviegoing,'' he added, noting ``The Green Mile'' could take in as
much as $145 &UR;  &LR; million by the end of its run.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Green Mile,'' based on a Stephen King story, is directed
by Frank Darabont, who also adapted King's ``The Shawshank
Redemption'' in 1994. Despite strong critical backing,
``Shawshank'' grossed only $28 &UR;  &LR; million overall.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's opening of goofy comedy ``Deuce Bigalow: Male Gigolo,''
starring Rob Schneider as a fish-tank cleaner turned male escort,
generated solid results in third place with $13 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,151
theaters. ``We think `Deuce' might play very well through the
holidays because there's not a lot of competition for the teen-age
audience,'' Viane noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deuce,'' produced by Adam Sandler's Happy Madison label, is
certain to be a moneymaker with a reported price tag of only
$15 &UR;  &LR; million.
</P>
<P>
   The top three films kept the box office healthy with
$50 &UR;  &LR; million of the $80 &UR;  &LR; million total, about matching last
weekend's total while topping the same weekend last year by
8 &UR;  &LR; percent. Total domestic gross for 1999 has already gone past the
$6.93 &UR;  &LR; billion total for 1998 and is on track to finish close to
$7.5 &UR;  &LR; billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers continue to be very impressive, particularly since
most people are still more concerned about holiday shopping,''
Rockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   MGM's fourth weekend of ``The World Is Not Enough'' led the rest
of the pack with $6.2 &UR;  &LR; million at 3,063 theaters as the 20th James
Bond movie dropped 40 &UR;  &LR; percent from last weekend. ``World'' needs
less than $500,000 to become the 199th movie to cross the
$100 &UR;  &LR; million mark in domestic grosses.
</P>
<P>
   Universal's third weekend of ``End of Days'' continued its fast
fade at multiplexes as it finished fifth with $4.7 &UR;  &LR; million at
2,652 sites, falling 51 &UR;  &LR; percent from its second weekend and barely
edging Paramount's fourth weekend of ``Sleepy Hollow'' with
$4.6 &UR;  &LR; million at 3,065 locations. ``Days'' has drawn $53 &UR;  &LR;  million
overall while ``Sleepy'' has topped $82 &UR;  &LR; million.
</P>
<P>
   Universal's sixth weekend of ``The Bone Collector'' finished a
distant seventh with $1.7 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,031 theaters, followed by
Lions Gate's fifth weekend of ``Dogma'' with $1.2 &UR;  &LR; million at 1,159
screens, Warner's fifth weekend of ``Pokemon: The First Movie''
with $1.1 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,426 sites and USA Films' seventh weekend of
``Being John Malkovich'' with $957,000 at 630 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's ``The Insider'' finished well out of top-10 contention
with just $573,000 at 823 theaters, pushing its gross to just
$24.9 &UR;  &LR; million after six weeks despite a strong Oscar buzz. The Los
Angeles Films Critics Association named it the year's top movie on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Two other dramas targeted for Oscar consideration posted solid
numbers in limited release, with Miramax's ``The Cider House
Rules'' taking in $115,000 at eight theaters while Disney's
``Cradle Will Rock'' drew $94,000 at eight sites.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday movie season will kick into high gear Friday as a
trio of high-profile films open _ Disney's comedy ``Bicentennial
Man'' with Robin Williams, 20th Century Fox's period drama ``Anna
and the King'' with Jody Foster and Sony's family comedy ``Stuart
Little'' with a computer-generated mouse voiced by Michael J. Fox.
``Bicentennial Man'' and ``Anna and the King'' both drew strong
business from sneak-preview screenings Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum said ``Bicentennial Man,'' ``The Green Mile'' and
``Toy Story 2'' will probably battle for first. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
