r a BC-DINER-CLOSING-TWOTAKE     12-12 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINER-CLOSING-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINER OWNERS CLOSING THE DOOR ON 40-YEAR ROUTINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 LEE HILLKAVANAUGH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The last thing Nick Nichols does when he
closes the diner is unwrap his apron, twirl it into a ball and
place it on a countertop. On his way out, he flicks off the lights.
</P>
<P>
   Betty, his wife, follows him out carrying a brown paper bag that
is growing grease spots. Leftovers. Today's lunch specials are
tonight's dinner for the couple.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Nichols twists the key in the front door lock till it
clicks. ``Stick a fork in me,'' he always says with a little smirk.
``I'm done.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Nicholses, it's a 40-year-old routine. But on Dec. 23,
they'll cook their last hamburger, fry their last chicken and serve
their last R.C. Cola (no Pepsi or Coke here). Nick and Betty's Cafe
is closing forever.
</P>
<P>
   When they began all those years ago, in the Leeds district in
eastern Kansas City, they just wanted to run a diner where
hard-working folks could eat a decent meal, pay a decent price and
feel welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Life's best dreams can be that simple.
</P>
<P>
   Before they close for good, their customers are telling the
Nicholses ``thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love coming in here,'' says ``Wild'' Bill Morrison, a
tow-truck driver and mule owner. For almost 40 years, he has sipped
coffee and argued politics with Betty Nichols. ``You're treated
just like family, orneriness and all.''
</P>
<P>
   In the center of it all is Nick Nichols _ husband, businessman,
short-order cook _ chatting with customers, an ever-present
cigarette dangling from his lips, smoke spiraling upward in blue
wisps.
</P>
<P>
   His gray hair has stood at attention in a quarter-inch burr
since his Army days in the 1940s. His face crinkles when he smiles.
And at the diner, he smiles a lot.
</P>
<P>
   That's life at Nick and Betty's Cafe between 4 a.m. and 2 p.m. _
where the music is country, the coffee is thick and the stories are
all exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   It's a place where everyone is treated like family, one customer
at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Nichols, 71, likes the way the world looks at 3:15 a.m.
Streets dark. No traffic. All those boarded-up windows and
abandoned buildings on Stadium Drive could just as well be asleep,
not blighted.
</P>
<P>
   As he eases his 1999 Lincoln Town Car into the same parking spot
he has used for years, Nichols remembers how the Leeds district
once was. Before the floods washed away the doctor's office, the
post office, the gas station. Before the General Motors plant
closed in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Nichols knows life stirs nearby. His very best early
customers, about 10 of them, will arrive soon. Truck drivers.
Milkmen. Salvage-yard operators. All working men with big
appetites, men in ball caps and blue shirts with their names
embroidered above their pockets.
</P>
<P>
   He knows they'll want his biscuits and gravy. A side of bacon _
or two. Some come to hear the gossip. But all want his coffee.
</P>
<P>
   He jangles his keys, twists the lock open. The booths are
silent, the air stale from old smoke and cooled grease.
</P>
<P>
   First, he tears open a shiny bag of Cain's coffee, slides it
inside the basket and pushes the button on the coffee maker. Water
rumbles deep inside the machine, then gurgles. Nichols disappears
into the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Pots clang. Refrigerator doors open and close. Soon there's the
sound of sausage sizzling and bacon frying.
</P>
<P>
   The cafe opens at 5 a.m., but James Thorp, the first customer of
the day, arrives around 4. Thorp has a special job. After Nichols
makes the gravy and the radio starts blaring country love songs,
Thorp gets the nod: time to turn over the cafe's ``Open'' signs.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols flips the main light switch.
</P>
<P>
   Fluorescent bulbs hum to life. Outside, the diner's windows
glow, piercing the gloom of the early morning like a lighthouse:
Nick and Betty's Cafe is now open for business.
</P>
<P>
   At least for a few more days.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1959 when Nick and Betty Nichols leased their first
restaurant, Nick and Betty's Highway Lunch and Bar, at 31st Street
and Van Brunt Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Nichols worked his shift at the General Motors plant, then
came to the restaurant to flip hamburgers and fry chicken. His wife
taught him how to cook.
</P>
<P>
   Word spread that their food was good.
</P>
<P>
   Mouthwatering meat loaf. Creamy gravies smooth as glass. And a
Friday special of fried chicken so first-rate that Roberts Dairy
milkmen still drive all the way from Topeka just to eat it.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Nichols dreamed of the day she and her husband could own
their own place and never rent again. She saved all the quarters
she earned in tips.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she had $1,000 in quarters and told her husband she
was ready to move. About the same time, a ``For Sale'' sign went up
in a building at 6422 Stadium Drive, just a few blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew this was going to be the place,'' Betty Nichols says.
``We bought it lock, stock and barrel.''
</P>
<P>
   With the help of friends from the old place, they slowly pieced
the diner together. In December 1974, they opened Nick and Betty's
Cafe. The crowds came then, and still do.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Betty Nichols has poured swimming pools of coffee,
heard thousands of stories and fed customers from every social,
economic and ethnic group in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, when I first opened at the other restaurant, I had
some people tell me that I shouldn't serve blacks,'' she recalls,
anger flashing across her eyes. ``I sent those people out of my
place. I don't put up with that nonsense. Never had, never will.
Besides, everybody's money is green.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-99 2354EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991212.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7058 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-DINER-CLOSING-2NDTAKE     12-12 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINER-CLOSING-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINER OWNERS CLOSING THE DOOR ON 40-YEAR ROUTINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... everybody's money is green.''
</P>
<P>
   At noon on a recent Friday, 18-wheelers line Stadium Drive like
a truck stop. Inside the cafe, milkmen share booths with bus
drivers. Mechanics sit next to crane operators. The voice of Paul
Harvey drones from the radio near the cash register.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all like a big family comin' here to eat,'' says Tim
Solomon. ``You go to McDonald's and you can't buy a filling lunch
for $3.50.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know only one other place that makes gravy like this: my
grandmother's,'' says Ron Stephenson.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a working man's place, not a chain,'' says John North.
``Here, you're a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Nichols smiles at the compliments, then glances at the
cafe's glass front door. It's covered with bumper stickers. About
10 years ago, someone shot holes in the door with a BB gun.
Probably kids, she says. She pasted over the holes with the
stickers.
</P>
<P>
   Five of them say, ``Tough times don't last; tough people will.''
</P>
<P>
   And there have been tough times for the Nicholses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Nick Nichols arrived and found the freezer and several
pounds of meat bobbing among the booths like bath toys. It was a
500-year flood, and it swallowed the cafe and all the other
businesses on Stadium Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols told his wife they were through. But they weren't.
</P>
<P>
   It took weeks of scrubbing, bleach and sweat to remove the
ugliness, stink and germs from the 4-foot-deep muck. It also took
all six of their children to undo the mess.
</P>
<P>
   But then, the cafe has always been a family affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regulars have all watched us kids grow up,'' Larry
Nichols, 41, says on a recent Friday as he sips his fifth cup of
coffee. ``Two of my sisters met their husbands here, and all my
girlfriends worked as waitresses. I think they were hired just so
my mom could check them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been on Mom and Dad to close for years,'' he says.
``It's sad for us, too. We'll definitely grieve the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the work here is too hard, too long of hours. And, man,
those country-fried steaks.I've seen country-fried steaks cold,
frozen, hard, burnt, shriveled up and fresh off the grill. I hope
to never see another country-fried steak again.''
</P>
<P>
   Then ``Wild'' Bill Morrison walks in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here comes trouble,'' Betty Nichols says, loud enough for
Morrison to hear, as he slides into a booth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, oh boy. Mercy sakes ali-i-i-i-ve,'' Morrison says with a
nasal-toned twang that could peel paint off a metal door. ``Don't
tell Betty if you like our current president. She once throwed a
dish rag at my head when I did. Me and that ol' boy have three
things in common: We're both named Bill, we're both from Arkansas
and we both lo-o-o-o-ove pretty women. Yessiree.''
</P>
<P>
   He flashes a grin at Betty Nichols, who threatens him with a
mock slap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some good fights haven't we Wild Bill?'' she says
and gives him a wink.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost a year ago when Betty Nichols' eyes couldn't tell
the difference between a one-dollar bill and a hundred. Her hearing
isn't so good anymore, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors don't know exactly what's wrong,'' Betty, 74, says
with a sigh. ``I guess it's just age. After raising six kids, I'm
finally gonna be able to be a housewife. I'll be able to do my
laundry leisure-like.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last few months, she's cut her workload. One day not long
ago, she looked at a regular customer and didn't recognize him. The
customer asked why she was ignoring him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, that shook me up when he asked me that,'' she says. ``I
never want anyone to feel hurt. I just can't see anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   On this day, Betty sees well enough to walk the aisles, but she
greets regulars and new faces alike, saying the same thing: ``Is
everything OK? Do you want more coffee? You doin' all right this
morning?''
</P>
<P>
   Then she sits at a booth, lights up a cigarette and blows the
smoke toward the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready to close three months ago,'' she says. ``It was
Nick that kept putting it off.He really likes being here. It'll be
hard to imagine neither one of us being here at all.''
</P>
<P>
   But through Dec. 23, customers still can find Nick Nichols
behind the orders window, maestro of the short order.
</P>
<P>
   Pancakes? Eggs? Side of bacon but with just a dollop of gravy?
</P>
<P>
   No problem.
</P>
<P>
   His hands dance over the blue flames of the gas stove. With his
left hand, he stirs the pancake batter. His right grabs a brush,
then cues an omelet pan with butter.
</P>
<P>
   He cracks two eggs with a one-hand smack, then tosses them into
the skillet, sans shells. With perfect timing, he reaches for the
bread with his free left hand, places four slices between his
fingers like rings and slides them into the toaster in one overhand
motion.
</P>
<P>
   A cigarette dangles from his lips, ashes hanging. He scoops the
eggs, pancakes, the toast as it pops up, and dabs the plate with a
little gravy before finishing his masterpiece with a single slide
of the knife cutting the toast point to point.
</P>
<P>
   The cigarette ash never falls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you what I'm gonna miss most,'' he says. ``It's
B.S.-ing with all the guys.I'll miss that. Yes, I will.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nicholses plan to enjoy their retirement. First will be a
trip to Cancun, Mexico. And they plan a lot more traveling, too.
</P>
<P>
   New owners are reopening the diner in January. Nick Nichols
might even help with the cooking just to show them how.
</P>
<P>
   But it won't be Nick and Betty's Cafe anymore.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the plates clank and the ice cubes jingle and glasses
fizz over with R.C. Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Nick will nod one last time and turn the signs to
``Closed.'' He'll unwrap his apron, twirl it into a ball, and flick
the light switch off.
</P>
<P>
   The front door will lock with a click. A click echoing the end
of an era _ Nick and Betty's Cafe, closed forever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
