<DOCNO> NYT19991212.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-12 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7059 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      12-12 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ANAHEIM, Calif. _ After a couple of days of feeling out other teams
and gauging interest in their players unsigned beyond 2000, the
Astros may have found a trading partner.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sources said Sunday the Astros and Boston Red Sox are discussing
a deal that would send center fielder Carl Everett to the American
League in exchange for top shortstop prospect Adam Everett and at
least one more player _ one of whom likely would be a pitching
prospect.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources, the next move belongs to the Red Sox, who
might have to make some roster adjustments to afford the Astros'
arbitration-eligible center fielder, who could make as much as $5
million next season. It's also possible the Red Sox could be
looking into the feasibility of signing Carl Everett to a long-term
contract before pulling the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   A deal does not appear imminent at this point. Astros general
manager Gerry Hunsicker, as per his policy on trade speculation
involving specific players, declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett, who made $2.4 million in 1999, has been with the
Astros since December 1997, when he was acquired from the New York
Mets in exchange for righthanded reliever John Hudek.
</P>
<P>
   Everett has a .310 batting average with 40 home runs, 184 RBIs
and 41 stolen bases in two seasons with the Astros, including a
breakout season in 1999 when he hit .325 with 25 homers and 108
RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros don't have a burning desire to trade the 27-year-old
switch hitter, but they do need to relieve the logjam in their
outfield, and they also run the risk of losing Everett without
compensation on the free-agent market next winter.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker has said any player not under contract beyond 2000 is
a candidate to be traded in the absence of working out a contract
extension. Lefthanded pitcher Mike Hampton and right fielder Derek
Bell also fall into that category. Hunsicker has said negotiations
on contract extensions for Everett and Hampton are ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   The GM also has made it clear that acquiring a shortstop is a
top priority. Whether Adam Everett, 22, is ready for the major
leagues remains to be seen, but many baseball observers love his
upside potential.
</P>
<P>
   The righthanded-hitting shortstop, best known for dazzling
defense, hit .263 with 10 home runs, 44 RBIs and 21 stolen bases
last season for the Red Sox's Class AA affiliate in Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the caution with which Hunsicker has advanced young
players to the majors, Adam Everett likely would spend some time at
Class AAA New Orleans if the trade were completed.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-1, 167-pound shortstop has played in only 119 career
minor-league games. The Astros plan to open the season with Tim
Bogar as their every-day shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Bogar started 75 games at shortstop in 1999 _ mostly while Ricky
Gutierrez was on the disabled list _ and hit .239 with four homers
and 31 RBIs. The Astros are willing to sacrifice offense with Bogar
because his glove is so reliable.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros could have as much as $17 million committed to their
starting outfielders if Carl Everett is not traded, considering
Hunsicker has had no luck moving Moises Alou or Bell. Alou has a
no-trade clause, and there hasn't been much of a market for Bell,
who is coming off his worst season and will make more than $6
million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The aforementioned outfield alignment also would keep talented
youngsters Richard Hidalgo and Daryle Ward on the bench. Any
outfield alignment the Astros employ in 2000 will not include Ken
Griffey Jr., whose agent, Brian Goldberg, on Sunday said Griffey
doesn't intend to play anywhere other than Seattle or Cincinnati.
The Reds backed out of trade discussion for Griffey on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he (Griffey) can't go to Cincinnati, he's going back to
Seattle for the final year of his contract,'' Goldberg said. ``He's
not a rent-a-player.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had discussions with the Mariners on Sunday but
concluded there was no match. Several teams are coming to that
conclusion at these meetings, which have not been as active as some
might have expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised (by the relative inactivity), because you
just never know,'' Hunsicker said. ``A lot of people come here with
great expectations, but in reality there are only about a
half-dozen trades every year. Some years there are more; some years
there are less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think money is holding up a lot of teams from doing
anything. Odds are, we won't do anything here, but I wouldn't rule
it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
